<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Longtime senator gives farewell to party brethren  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Daniel Patrick Moynihan bid farewell to his
fellow New York state Democrats with a brief address to a
convention dominated by the woman Democrats want to succeed him in
the U.S. Senate, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's time to go,'' Moynihan told some 10,000 people Tuesday
night as his wife Liz, manager of his four successful campaigns for
Senate, stood by his side on the podium at the Pepsi Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan, 73, is retiring at the end of 2000 to spend more time
writing and with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan spoke for just eight minutes as he recounted a
half-century-long career in government and politics which began in
1953, when he worked on the New York City mayoral campaign of
Robert F. Wagner Jr. His first state Democratic convention,
Moynihan remembered, came a year later when party leaders met at
the 69th Division Armory in New York City to nominate W. Averell
Harriman for governor.
</P>
<P>
   He also met Elizabeth Brennan, his future wife, at that
convention, Moynihan reminisced.
</P>
<P>
   He said the threat of nuclear war hung over the world for
virtually all his governmental career, with the globe at the brink
during the Cuban Missile Crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ''We came close by accident many times more than people know,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton's election to the Senate would be in keeping
with New York's tradition of firsts involving women's rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''This year for the first time in history a first lady is going
to be elected to the United States Senate,'' he said to the cheers
of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Then he bowed out.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now we say goodbye,'' he said. ''We thank the party and the
people of our state for a great run. Good night.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to his speech, a video tribute was shown consisting
exclusively of Moynihan's appearances over the years on ''Meet the
Press'' and his sometimes prescient comments on domestic issues and
foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In one clip from the mid-1980s he criticized Republican Sen.
Phil Gramm of Texas for misrepresenting his record on defense
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ''You're in (the Senate) one year, fella,'' Moynihan said. ''You
don't do that to another senator.''
</P>
<P>
   The acclaim of the convention was just one of several honors
Moynihan is receiving as his political career winds down. On
Monday, the House of Representatives unanimously gave final
approval to a bill renaming the federal courthouse in Manhattan
after Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Moynihan is one of the ''wisest'' public servants
in American history.
</P>
<P>
   ''There isn't a person in the party, in the state or the nation
who is not in his debt,'' Clinton said. ''And I am at the top of
that list.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Mayor Anthony Masiello called Moynihan an ''icon of our
party,'' state Comptroller H. Carl McCall said he is a ''great
visionary'' and state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer said Moynihan
is ''one of the great hearts and minds of our age.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to becoming senator in 1976, Moynihan had a long career in
cabinet-or sub-cabinet-level posts under Presidents Kennedy,
Johnson, Nixon and Ford. He was U.S. ambassador to India from
1973-75 and U.S. representative to the United Nations in 1975 and
1976.
</P>
<P>
   While in Washington, Moynihan often drew as much attention for
his scholarly writing as his politicking. Noted works detailed his
visions for reforming welfare and keeping the Social Security
system solvent.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan also largely avoided the nitty-gritty of state party
politics, campaigning only selectively for other state Democrats.
He cited his antipathy toward having to raise money for another
campaign as a factor in his decision to retire this year.
</P>
<P>
   During one now-famous appearance before the 1988 state
Democratic convention, Moynihan was to have spoken on Republican
mishandling of upstate New York's economy. Instead, at the last
moment, he scrapped that address and spoke about the threat to
world peace that Pakistan and India posed by both holding nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   For 18 years, Moynihan formed an unlikely duo in the Senate with
New York's other representative in that chamber, Republican Alfonse
D'Amato. D'Amato reveled in his reputation as ''Senator Pothole'' --
a legislator focused on local projects and winning federal aid for
his state -- while Moynihan seemed to prefer national and global
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their differences in party and style, the two men
generally worked well together.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
