<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 00:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Niagara Mohawk remolding itself again for new competitive era  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM KATES
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Niagara Mohawk turns 50 this year and
change is the reason for its historical staying power, according to
Chairman William E. Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 begins a new era for Niagara Mohawk Holdings Inc.,
which has changed its name and is completing the transition from a
power producer to an energy provider.
</P>
<P>
   Davis on Tuesday recounted Niagara Mohawk's history of change
for about 100 shareholders as he outlined the company's path of
progress for the future. It was a small crowd compared to past
annual meetings, some of which drew as many as 2,000 stockholders,
often to complain about mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   ''The theme of responding to and leading change echoes
throughout our company's history,'' Davis told the sparse crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have inherited the responsibility to continue the
transformation of the energy industry. Our company will always be a
work in progress,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Although its predecessor companies go back to the late 19th
century, Niagara Mohawk Power Corp. formed in 1950 out of three
operating companies -- Buffalo Niagara Electric, Central New York
Power and New York Power and Light -- and began building and
expanding an upstate empire of fossil fuel generating plants, hydro
stations and nuclear plants. Before deregulation, Niagara Mohawk
provided gas and electric service to 2 million customers and
employed 15,000 people. Today, it has 7,200 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Davis told shareholders today's Niagara Mohawk has nearly
completed selling off all its generating plants as it moves in
other business directions. Last week, Niagara Mohawk completed the
sale of the Albany Steam Station and it has a pending sales
agreement for the Roseton plant in Newburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Niagara Mohawk has changed course on the sale of its nuclear
plants on Lake Ontario, Davis said. The utility had reached a
tentative agreement to sell its share of the plants for $163
million to AmerGen, a Philadelphia-based international power
conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We see there is now a better market than when we first put the
plants up for sale. There are more people interested in buying
nuclear plants these days,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the plants will be sold at a competitive auction. No
date has been set but Davis said the process is moving forward.
</P>
<P>
   As Niagara Mohawk sheds itself of its power producing plants, it
has begun investing in unregulated energy service businesses and
other areas through a wholly owned subsidiary, Opinac NA. Its
biggest investment has been in Telergy, a rapidly rising regional
telecommunications company, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Niagara Mohawk lost $35 million in 1999 and its stock
performance was down 13 percent (still 6 percent better than the
industry average). But the company's financial stability improved
as it paid off more than $1.1 billion in debt, saving itself $85
million in annual interest costs, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   There were other signs of regained fiscal health, he said.
Revenues grew by 2.3 percent, net earnings rose $270 million and
cash flow increased to $488 million in 1999 from $311 million in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''Faced with this confusion, it is a natural reaction to ask if
we're still on the right course. I believe strongly that we are,''
Davis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
