<DOCNO> APW20000517.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 00:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise Slightly  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose slightly Wednesday morning after
a hike in a key U.S. interest rate boosted confidence that U.S.
officials will control inflation. The dollar edged higher against
the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 34.43
points, or 0.20 percent, to 17,585.68 points at the end of morning
trading. On Tuesday, the average closed up 237.57 points, or 1.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 109.52 yen in late morning, up 0.58 yen from
late Tuesday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of
109.44 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index started higher after the
U.S. Federal Reserve Board Open Market Committee on Tuesday raised
its target for the federal funds rate -- the interest that banks
charge each other on overnight loans -- from 6 percent to 6.50
percent, the highest level in nine years.
</P>
<P>
   The Nikkei average then moved into negative territory as some
investors locked in profits, but posted slight gains toward the
morning close, traders said.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Fed action, which was widely anticipated in
financial markets, stocks in New York rose on hopes Fed Chairman
Alan Greenspan will win his fight to keep inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
   Hiroichi Nishi, a deputy general manager at Nikko Securities,
said the Fed's rate increase decision, coupled with higher
overnight futures prices in Chicago, was supporting an early rise
in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 126.79 points
to 10,934.57 at Tuesday's close. The Nasdaq composite index rose
109.92 points to 3,717.57 points.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 5.32 points, or 0.33 percent, to 1,648.39
points. The TOPIX closed up 15.72 points, or 0.96 percent, the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar strengthened against the yen
following the Fed's decision. Higher interest rates tend to make a
nation's currency more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Also, tension between Taiwan and mainland China ahead of
Saturday's inauguration of Taiwan President-elect Chen Shui-bian
provided added support for the greenback, traders said.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar is sometimes regarded as a safe haven in times of
international unrest.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 98.77 yen, down from
99.02 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond
stood at 1.7450 percent, unchanged from Tuesday's finish. Its price
remained unchanged at 100.47.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
