<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court: Man can't sue despite medical examiner's misconduct  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- New York City is shielded from a suit by a
man who said his life was ruined because a city medical examiner
didn't tell police his son died of natural causes after first
deciding the boy was slain.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the seven Court of Appeals judges Tuesday wrote sharp
dissents in which they argued that Edward Lauer should get the
chance to convince a jury about the merits of his $10 million suit.
</P>
<P>
   Lauer said his wife divorced him and he had to move out of his
neighborhood in Queens because he was being harassed by people who
thought he was responsible for killing his 3-year-old son Andrew in
August 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eddy Lilavois, a medical examiner for the city, had
initially ruled Andrew's death a homicide due to blunt injuries to
the boy's neck and brain. After further investigation, however,
Lilavois determined two months later that the Lauer child died of a
natural cause, a ruptured brain aneurysm.
</P>
<P>
   Lilavois, however, did not change the cause of death on Andrew's
death certificate from his initial finding nor did he notify police
of the change. For nearly two years, until the New York Daily News
reported Lilavois' change, police and the people close to Lauer
considered him a suspect in his son's death, according to court
papers.
</P>
<P>
   As Judge George Bundy Smith said in his dissent, ''His wife
divorced him. His family, friends and neighbors shunned him. For
close to two years, plaintiff (Lauer) needlessly lived under a
cloud of suspicion, allegedly enduring depression and loss of
weight caused by the nightmare he lived.''
</P>
<P>
   Lilavois resigned after the Daily News' report, the court noted.
</P>
<P>
   Though acknowledging the difficult circumstances of the Lauer
case, the five judges in the majority Tuesday nevertheless said
laws do not allow him to sue the city for the actions of the
medical examiner. To do so, Lauer would have to show that the
medical examiner owed a special ''duty'' to him and Lauer had not
demonstrated that, Chief Judge Judith Kaye wrote for the majority.
</P>
<P>
   Allowing Lauer to sue, Kaye wrote, would be tantamount to
''radically enlarging both the responsibility of the Office of
Chief Medical Examiner and the potential liability of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   The court has frequently ruled on matters of governmental
immunity from suits by citizens, and generally found that concepts
of sovereign immunity bar such litigation. Kaye said Tuesday that
such cases have ''likely divided this court more than any other
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith and the other dissenter, Joseph Bellacosa, said Lauer did
show that a special duty existed between Lilavois and Lauer and
that Lauer should get his day in court.
</P>
<P>
   Barring Lauer's suit would ''reward government agents who hide
the truth and sweep wrongdoings under a rug'' of impunity,
Bellacosa wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Lilavois' actions were ''grossly indifferent'' and not letting
Lauer sue ''seals an undeniable miscarriage of justice,'' Bellacosa
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lauer's lawyer, Peter James Johnson Jr., said Kaye's decision
gets lost in the ''wilderness of arcane language and concepts''
about government's responsibilities toward its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the majority opinion suggests a 19th century solution
to a 20th and 21st century problem because it puts pursestrings
ahead of people,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said the Court of Appeals was the final step for Lauer's
appeal. There are no federal constitutional issues that would
warrant taking the case to federal courts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Kalkstein, an assistant New York City corporation
counsel, said the majority of the court was cautious about imposing
additional liability burdens on municipalities. He ackowledged that
the Lauer case was a ''tragic'' one.
</P>
<P>
   In other rulings Tuesday by the Court of Appeals:
</P>
<P>
   IMPAIRED FIREFIGHTER
</P>
<P>
   The court upheld the dismissal of a White Plains firefighter for
testing positive on the job for a cocaine derivative called
benzoylecgonine. Ian Scott Wilson had argued that the evidence
which helped trigger the blood and urine tests -- an anonymous
letter -- was not sufficient to warrant the testing.
</P>
<P>
   The court said, however, that Wilson's bosses had other evidence
to suggest that Wilson was a substance abuser, including excessive
absences from work and the fact his co-workers had come to nickname
him ''Scotch'' Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   DORM TAXES
</P>
<P>
   The judges sided with Hobart and William and Smith colleges in
its dispute with the city of Geneva over property tax assessments
on a dormitory built on college land in 1996 under a leaseback
arrangement with a private developer.
</P>
<P>
   Geneva had argued that the colleges should pay taxes on the
dormitory building because the developer primarily owns it while
the colleges acquire equity over 40 years in the lease-back deal.
But the court ruled Tuesday that the building is college property
and its property tax exemption as an educational institution
stands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-17-00 0042 </TRAILER>
