<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuomo, McCall insist they are not running -- yet  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State Comptroller H. Carl McCall and federal
Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo -- the two New York Democrats most
interested in running for governor in 2002 -- say they are not yet
vying against one another.
</P>
<P>
   The two men shook delegates' hands at their party's state
convention Tuesday and spoke at the convention at which Hillary
Rodham Clinton was nominated for Senate. Both said their only focus
now is getting Clinton and Al Gore elected this November.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, the only black ever elected to statewide office in New
York, got a warmer reception with his speech, saying, ''We are a
party that brings in inclusion and diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, some members of the audience began chanting ''Run,
Carl, Run,'' to which he replied, ''We're gonna get to that. My
turn will come.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall also received a standing ovation in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo focused largely on issues his party advocates, drawing
applause when he called for equal pay for women, cost-of-living
adjustments for pensions of retired state workers and economic
boosts for upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo also alluded to the 2002 governor's race in his remarks,
saying that ''in 2002, it's the governor's mansion'' that the
Democrats want to take over. He didn't say whether he'd like to be
the Democrat to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters after his speech, Cuomo said it is still
''way premature'' to discuss gubernatorial nominations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to engage in a 2002 race today, which could
divide the Democratic Party. We have plenty of time to worry about
2002,'' Cuomo said. ''It's important to focus on the here and now.
We need to win the presidential and the senatorial (races) and we
need to stay united to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Both McCall and Cuomo had reportedly been dueling to be the one
to nominate the first lady at the convention, but Clinton's camp
solved that dilemma by giving the honor to U.S. Sen. Charles
Schumer.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo, the eldest son of former Gov. Mario Cuomo, has said he is
considering a run for the post his father held for three terms
before being defeated by Republican George Pataki in 1994. The
younger Cuomo said it was too early to be campaigning for governor
but added that he would not rule out a primary against McCall.
</P>
<P>
   McCall has privately told supporters that he will seek the
governorship in 2002, but said he will not make any public decision
until after the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with WROW-AM in Albany Tuesday morning, McCall
said friction between Cuomo and himself over nominating Clinton
''was really generated by the media.'' However, he said that after
November, it is ''quite possible'' that he and Cuomo will emerge as
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ''But believe me, not before then,'' the comptroller said.
</P>
<P>
   McCall has been working for several months at lining up support
for a possible gubernatorial nomination and so far has gained the
support of state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer, state Assembly
Majority Leader Michael Bragman and former Lt. Gov. Stan Lundine.
</P>
<P>
   McCall was one of the hosts of a post-convention reception at an
Albany hotel sponsored by the state Democratic Party. Cuomo, on the
other hand, was a prominent guest at a reception aboard a Hudson
River cruise boat featuring singer Tony Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   If both men decide to run, they seem likely to encounter Pataki.
The governor gave his strongest signal to date Monday about his
plans for 2002, when he said running for governor is ''the most
likely scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   A statewide poll conducted by Marist College's Institute of
Public Opinion in April showed Pataki ahead of Cuomo, 50 percent to
40 percent and leading McCall, 52 percent to 33 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
