<HEADLINE> Navy's presence in Vieques protested at convention  </HEADLINE>
By HADLEY PAWLAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- When 18-year-old Carlos Rossy-Lozada votes
for the first time in November, the tiny Puerto Rican island of
Vieques will be on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ''This issue will determine a lot for me,'' Rossy-Lozada said
outside the New York state Democratic convention Tuesday. He, and
about two dozen others, gathered outside the convention to protest
the Navy's use of Vieques for military practices.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Bronx Assemblyman Roberto Ramirez called for convention
delegates to pass a resolution today that would demand that the
Navy's use of the island cease immediately. His supporters in the
crowd chanted ''Vieques si (yes), Marina (Navy) No!''
</P>
<P>
   ''I am calling on you, the heart and soul of the New York state
Democratic Party ... to restore peace to the island of Vieques,''
Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   He defended his use of the convention as a forum for the issue
saying, ''There is never a wrong forum, a wrong time, or a wrong
place when the lives of 10,000 people are at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy controls two-thirds of Vieques and uses it for weapons
storage and military exercises. Protesters say that the more than
six decades of training on the island -- which has included bombing
exercises -- has harmed the health of residents, stunted tourism,
and harmed the environment.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 31, President Clinton agreed to order the Navy out by
May 2003 if the island's 9,400 residents vote in a referendum to
expel it.
</P>
<P>
   A poll of island residents taken in February found that 84
percent would vote evict the military.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez's resolution calls for an immediate referendum.
</P>
<P>
   ''Puerto Ricans are loyal American citizens and have let the
military use their island to prepare during World War II, Vietnam
and the Gulf War,'' said Kenneth Agosto, a Bronx young Democrat.
''It's time they get a little bit back before it's totally
uninhabitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Agosto said that Hillary Clinton's support of an end to the
Navy's practices in Vieques has led to ''one of the biggest moral
imperatives that we (Hispanic voters) vote for her.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll released in April found that Hispanic voters in New York
support the first lady 73 percent to 17 percent over Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not only Vieques,'' Agosto said. ''She (Clinton) follows
our views and listens to us about problems like police brutality
and asthma.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also supports an end to military maneuvers on the
island.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the convention, a small group of protesters gathered,
shouting ''No more bullets, no more guns. Look at what the Navy's
done.''
</P>
<P>
   When a motorcade suspected of carrying Presidents Clinton drove
past, the protesters yelled: ''Clinton send the Navy out. Everybody
scream and shout.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a Democrat, but that doesn't matter,'' said Efrain Dones
of Albany who was protesting Tuesday. ''That is beside the point
because I'm an American citizen like them, and I don't believe
citizens should be exposed to things like bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This catches my attention because I've been to the island and
I've seen the devastation,'' Rossy-Lozada said. ''This issue is
crucial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-17-00 0050 </TRAILER>
