<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dominicans Vote for President  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS HAWLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- Left-leaning populist
Hipolito Mejia declared himself a winner Wednesday on early results
in presidential elections marked by heavy voter turnout and
frustration with the government's inability to reduce poverty.
</P>
<P>
   With 27.7 percent of polling stations counted, Mejia's
opposition Dominican Revolutionary Party and its allies had 49
percent, or 373,368 votes, to 26.7 percent, or 203,356 votes, for
former President Joaquin Balaguer of the conservative Social
Christian Reformist party. Free-market advocate Danilo Medina of
the incumbent Dominican Liberation Party trailed with 23.67
percent, or 180,254 votes. Smaller parties split the remainder.
</P>
<P>
   Mejia needs more than 50 percent of the vote to avoid a run-off
election on June 30. Final results were expected Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the reported lack of the needed 1 percent, Mejia
declared victory at his campaign headquarters, where supporters
cheered wildly as he assured: ''We have gotten more than the 50
percent and we continue to increase.''
</P>
<P>
   Police reported two deaths that appeared to be related to the
elections, but voting was otherwise peaceful and turnout was
massive throughout the Caribbean nation of 8 million people. In
Santo Domingo, guards scuffled with reporters covering 93-year-old
Balaguer as he cast his own vote in his quest for an eighth term as
president.
</P>
<P>
   Some 4.3 million Dominicans were registered to vote, with women
casting ballots in the morning and men in the afternoon under a
system designed to prevent repeat voting.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters saw the election as a chance to spread the wealth of
a four-year economic boom under President Leonel Fernandez, who by
law couldn't seek a consecutive term. The economy grew by almost 40
percent under Fernandez, but the median per capita income is just
$2,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''This government is good, I suppose -- but for the poor people,
nothing has happened,'' said Rosa Nereda Garcia, 49, as she waited
to vote at the Socorro Sanchez School in Santo Domingo's Villa
Duarte neighborhood. The voter line wrapped around the block and
zigzagged through the school grounds as police and soldiers, armed
with rifles, stood watch.
</P>
<P>
   Mejia, 59, the owner of an agrochemical business, capitalized on
popular resentment, promising social programs and small
community-level public works projects to create jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Medina, a 48-year-old career technocrat, ran a lackluster
campaign, insisting with little passion that benefits eventually
will trickle down.
</P>
<P>
   Balaguer, considered a master political strategist despite his
years and frail health, offered to ''govern as I have always
governed'' -- which critics say means a return to authoritarian
control and patronage.
</P>
<P>
   A scuffle erupted when Balaguer's car pulled up to a voting
station and was immediately surrounded by news media. Guards toting
rifles and nightsticks shoved reporters away as elections officials
delivered a ballot and ballot box to the car; a hand inside the car
took the ballot and passed it back moments later.
</P>
<P>
   ''Balaguer! We need you!'' a man screamed as Balaguer's car
quickly pulled away. Several people were splashed with red ink from
a bottle used to mark voters' fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Balaguer was forced from power under pressure from the United
States after international observers accused him of stealing the
1994 election. In 1996, he threw his weight behind Fernandez to
prevent a victory for his longtime foes in the Revolutionary Party
-- an alliance local analysts say would recur in a second round this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Police reported that a man was shot and killed Tuesday during an
argument with a rival party supporter in the southwestern town of
San Juan de la Maguana. A 76-year-old woman died of a heart attack,
apparently after being shoved by a guard at a polling station in a
Santo Domingo neighborhood, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents reported confusion at some polling stations, with
elections officials reporting about 100,000 voters had not picked
up their voter cards by election day.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Baker arrived at one Santo Domingo voting station with her
3-year-old son at 5 a.m., cast her ballot, then was prohibited from
leaving because her name didn't appear on the rolls. ''This is
chaos,'' she grumbled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 0100 </TRAILER>
