<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, May 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Putin's Pick for Premier Questioned
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian lawmakers questioned President Vladimir Putin's
nominee for prime minister Tuesday, a day before a parliamentary vote on the
appointment that he appeared certain to win. Nearly all parties in the
centrist-dominated lower house of parliament, the State Duma, said they would
support the candidacy of Mikhail Kasyanov, a pro-reform politician expected to
focus on the economy. The vote was scheduled for Wednesday. Kasyanov has
effectively led the Cabinet since early January, when Putin -- then both acting
president and prime minister -- made him first deputy prime minister.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Booted Napster Users Want Back On
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Thousands of Metallica fans booted by the online music
sharing software company Napster for allegedly swapping the heavy metal band's
music want their access restored. Napster Inc. said Tuesday it received notice
from more than 30,000 MusicShare software users claiming they were misidentified
as people who had illegally traded Metallica's copyrighted songs in the popular
MP3 digital format. If Metallica does not take legal action against individual
users within 10 days of Tuesday's notice, Napster will restore those blocked
accounts, citing federal copyright law.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fed Hikes Interest Rate a Half Point
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Reserve bumped up interest rates Tuesday by a
bold half point, pushing a key rate to its highest level in nine years. Fed
policy-makers signaled they were prepared to move even more aggressively if
needed to fight inflation. The central bank raised its target for the federal
funds rate, the interest that banks charge each other, to 6.5 percent. It was
the sixth time the Fed has increased the funds rate since last June but the
first half-point move. All the other rate changes were smaller quarter-point
increases.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clintons Together for Nomination
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- In a supporting role on the sideline, President Clinton
applauded Tuesday night as New York Democrats nominated his wife, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, as their candidate for the Senate. Clinton walked hand in hand with the
first lady as she was introduced on stage at a downtown arena before an audience
of more than 11,000 people. After a few waves and without a word, the president
stepped back as Mrs. Clinton moved to the microphone and accepted the unanimous
nomination from the 352 delegates to the State Democratic Party convention.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Five Rescued From North Pole
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- Five adventurers -- including the aviation legend
Dick Rutan -- were rescued from the North Pole after their biplane broke through
the ice and sank more than 13,000 feet to the bottom of the Arctic Ocean. An
airplane dispatched from Canada picked up the men Monday night after they had
spent 12 hours at the top of the world. They were not injured.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dalai Lama Ready for Autonomy
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- The Dalai Lama said Tuesday he was seeking autonomy
and not independence for Tibet, but that officially atheistic China must not
have control over spiritual issues. ''China maintains strict control over all
aspects, including cultural and spiritual,'' the exiled Tibetan spiritual leader
said. ''Those fields that we in Tibet can manage, we should manage.'' The 1989
Nobel Peace Prize winner was making his first stop on a swing through
Scandinavia. He was to meet Wednesday with Prime Minister Goeran Persson despite
objections by China, which controls Tibet and sees the Dalai Lama as a rallying
point for pro-independence forces.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Senior Democrat OKs China Trade Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation to grant permanent trade benefits to China won
what could be a crucial endorsement Tuesday from Rep. Charles Rangel, the senior
Democrat on the House Ways and Means Committee. ''It makes sense for the United
States to have normal trade relations with all countries,'' the New York
congressman said in announcing his long-awaited decision. Rangel's choice was
important because other wavering Democrats on the committee, which takes up the
trade bill tomorrow, were looking to him for guidance in the election-year
debate over trade with China.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Advance Moderately
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks advanced moderately Wednesday. The Nikkei gained
82.12 points to 17,633.37 points in early trading.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Trail Blazers 81, Jazz 79
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Scottie Pippen, dazed for several minutes after being
inadvertently knocked down from behind by teammate Arvydas Sabonis, hit a
3-pointer with 7.3 seconds left Tuesday night, lifting the Portland Trail
Blazers to an 81-79 victory over the Utah Jazz. The loss eliminated the Jazz 4-1
in the best-of-seven series. Pippen led the Blazers with 23 points, nine
rebounds and eight assists.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
</SUBHEAD>
