<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rowland announces grant for business development  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARMINGTON, Conn. (AP) -- Million-dollar development projects
like Hartford's Adriaen's Landing may draw people to the cities,
but corporate and civic leaders say strengthening smaller
businesses is necessary to keep them there.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John G. Rowland on Tuesday announced a $5 million grant to
help small businesses, part of a revitalization strategy for the
state's five largest cities.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not the big type of project that commands headlines, said
Ken Decko, president of the Connecticut Business and Industry
Association, a business trade association with 10,000 members.
''But it's the type that if successfully implemented, will provide
jobs and help the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   With unemployment under 3 percent and hundreds of new companies
moving into the state in the last two to three years, ''We are in
the most perfect position to revitalize the cities,'' Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, the program provides incentives for investment in
inner-city business and services for small business owners. Jobs
training focuses not just on getting workers ready for an initial
position, but on preparing them to move into executive roles and
one day start businesses of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The program also calls for inner-city businesses to form
''clusters'' to share operating costs, information and technology.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide initiatives are designed to complement plans
tailored for each city by corporate, government and civic leaders.
In Hartford, corporations and businesses schools are joining to
coordinate support services for inner-city entrepreneurs.
Manufacturers in both Bridgeport and Waterbury have partnered to
address modernization, shrinking markets and a shortage of skilled
workers.
</P>
<P>
   New Haven's plan focuses on using the city's university and
research facilities to create a presence in the biotechnology and
information technology fields. New Britain plans to establish a
health care training center to provide staff for local hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The state funding is just a boost to the revitalization effort,
officials said. The strategy relies heavily on contributions of
time and money from the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone complains about the condition of the cities -- the
high taxes, the traffic, the young people not coming back,''
Rowland said. ''Our complaining days are behind us. We're into the
productive days now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
