<HEADLINE> State Supreme Court to consider Millstone appeals  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Connecticut Supreme Court will review disputes between
environmental groups and the operator of the Millstone nuclear
power complex.
</P>
<P>
   The high court took from the state Appellate Court three cases
that allege the nuclear reactors emit illegal pollution discharges
and are damaging the Long Island Sound fishery.
</P>
<P>
   Lower courts ruled in favor of Northeast Utilities, the operator
of the three-reactor complex in Waterford.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups from Connecticut and Long Island, N.Y. aim
to shut down the reactors or curb their operation during fish
spawning season.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Burton, a lawyer for Fish Unlimited and other
environmental groups bringing the claims, said she is pleased the
Supreme Court is taking up the cases. Three hours of arguments are
scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The spotlight shines brighter on the Supreme Court,'' Burton
said.
</P>
<P>
   NU spokesman Joe Pillittere said the Berlin-based utility looks
forward to arguing the merits of the cases in court. The company
declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Television Network, which is a Connecticut
version of the cable TV channel C-SPAN, has applied to cover the
arguments for broadcast. The Supreme Court will review any
objections to the broadcast before deciding whether to allow a
camera in its chamber.
</P>
<P>
   One case involves a 1998 settlement between NU and the state
Department of Environmental Protection over alleged violations of
Millstone's water discharge permit. The $1.2 million settlement
included a $700,000 fine and a $500,000 donation to environmental
causes, including Mystic Marinelife Aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   Fish Unlimited claims the settlement violates public policy and
amounts to collusion between NU and the DEP. The group also claims
the aquarium is an improper beneficiary of settlement funds.
</P>
<P>
   A second appeal relates to allegations that Millstone Unit 2's
cooling system is damaging the winter flounder fishery in Niantic
Bay and Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit by Fish Unlimited sought to shut down the plant until
a cooling system was installed that would recirculate water from
the sound instead of drawing in fresh water.
</P>
<P>
   NU has said that its nuclear plant cooling systems have a
negligible impact on the fish population.
</P>
<P>
   A Hartford Superior Court judge last year blamed overfishing --
and not the plant -- for the drop in fish and allowed the plant to
restart.
</P>
<P>
   The third appeal deals with allegations that the DEP has issued
an improper wastewater discharge permit to the Millstone complex.
The environmental groups claim the permit is invalid since the
complex was idled for months because of safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   NU has said it has the proper permits. Millstone Unit 1 is being
decommissioned.
</P>
<P>
   Other parties to the appeals include the Green Party of
Connecticut; Don't Waste Connecticut; Standing For the Truth About
Radiation of East Hampton, N.Y.; the North Fork Environmental
Coalition of Mattituck, N.Y.; New York State Assemblyman Fred
Thiele of Long Island and the town of East Hampton, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-17-00 0123 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0030 </DOCNO>
