<BODY>
<HEADLINE> You can call him Prince ... and this time, he means it  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It was a simple greeting from a reporter: ''Hi,
Prince.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That sounds great,'' the artist once again known as Prince
replied Tuesday at a Manhattan news conference. ''I haven't heard
that in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, to be exact, when he swapped his given name of
Prince Rogers Nelson for an unpronounceable symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Well, forget the symbol and erase his acronym (TAFKAP). The
artist says he will, now and forever, spell his name P-R-I-N-C-E.
</P>
<P>
   ''On Dec. 31, 1999, my publishing contract with Warner-Chappell
expired, thus emancipating the name I was given before birth --
Prince -- from all long-term restrictive documents,'' the
freshly-minted Prince told the crowded press event.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will now go back to using my name instead of the symbol I
adopted to free myself from all undesirable relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   That was easy, huh?
</P>
<P>
   Prince's re-renaming kicked off a quirky, hour-long news
conference where the Minneapolis rocker made an assortment of
announcements -- including plans for a weeklong party dubbed
''Prince: A Celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the event, his Paisley Park studio will be opened for
tours between June 7-13, with a special Prince concert set for June
13 at Northrup Auditorium in Minneapolis. A new Prince song,
''Cybersingle,'' will also be available at his web site, as will a
modified version of his last album, titled ''Rave In2 the Joy
Fantastic.'
</P>
<P>
   The return to the Prince name ends a 7-year battle between the
performer and Warner Bros. Records, which had Prince under contract
through the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Prince, charging that Warner Bros. exercised too much control
over his music, switched his name to a symbol in 1993. With the
contract now over, Prince said he's confident that are no new names
in his future.
</P>
<P>
   Prince also touched on a variety of other subjects, from his
marriage to his future touring plans to his search for
spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   -- On his marriage to similarly single-named Mayte: ''We're still
friends ... The clearest I can put it is she does her thing, and I
do my thing, and sometimes we do our thing together.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On his immediate plans: ''My main concern now is to study
things of a spiritual nature.'' Asked to amplify his answer: ''It's
pretty personal.''
</P>
<P>
   -- On his ''weird'' persona: ''I've never thought of myself as
weird. And people who know me don't think I'm weird either. How you
perceive me is how you perceive me.''
</P>
<P>
   Prince later added that he would continue his fight against what
he perceives as major label domination of the nation's music scene.
</P>
<P>
   He promised, with a sly smile, not to ''give up the store to
Forrest Gump accounting firms who think a royalty check is like a
box of chocolates. You never know what you'll get.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the web: http://www.npgonlineltd.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-17-00 0131 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brother of Mexican Candidate Brash  </HEADLINE>
By AMPARO TREJO
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS MOCHIS, Mexico (AP) -- Mexico has a long tradition of
''uncomfortable brothers'' -- siblings of presidents who cause
embarrassment or enrich themselves using their family's name.
</P>
<P>
   But never has a president had such a brash, open, unabashedly
redneck brother as Eduardo Labastida. At 64, he is six years older
than Francisco Labastida, the man who is in a neck-and-neck race to
be Mexico's next president.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo likes to bet on cockfights and horse races. He likes to
drink. He has a direct sense of humor and makes no apologies. But
he denies news reports that he has been involved in shady business
dealings.
</P>
<P>
   In an afternoon interview on his farm in the northwestern state
of Sinaloa, Eduardo Labastida came off as a fun-loving good ol'
boy. He smelled of alcohol, and repeatedly slapped a reporter on
the arm as he joked about his relationship with Francisco, the
candidate of Mexico's ruling party in the July 2 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he was the ''uncomfortable brother,'' Eduardo
laughed, then turned the tables on his brother Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ''The uncomfortable brother is him,'' he deadpanned. ''Because
he doesn't let me play the cocks and the horses. He forbid me.''
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Labastida also laughed when asked about his brother's
gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've told him to stay away from the cockfights, but he likes
them,'' he said, shrugging.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers are reminded of former President Carter's
colorful brother, Billy.
</P>
<P>
   A successful peanut farmer, Billy caused his brother
considerable embarrassment during his 1976-80 administration. He
once defined himself as a beer-drinking good ol' boy and put his
name on a brand of beer.
</P>
<P>
   He participated in a Canadian bellyflop competition, jumping in
with a can of beer in his hand and a rose between his teeth. And he
caused serious controversy with racist remarks and by accepting
money from Libya to pay off personal debts.
</P>
<P>
   The sins of Mexican brothers tend to be a bit more serious, just
as the power of Mexican presidents has been broader over the ruling
party's 71 years in power.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Salinas de Gortari, brother of former President Carlos
Salinas, is serving a 27-year sentence at a maximum-security prison
for masterminding the murder of a ruling-party rival, and has $114
million frozen in Swiss banks, allegedly profits from drug ties
during his brother's administration.
</P>
<P>
   Rodolfo Zedillo, brother of President Ernesto Zedillo, has been
sued for fraud for his construction businesses. He also reportedly
has been involved in shady real-estate deals with the Mexican army
during the current administration.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo concedes his farming business has done well as his
brother has risen through the political ranks, but says he has
never used government money or political influence.
</P>
<P>
   His booming farming business grows hot peppers, zucchini and
potatoes for the domestic market and for export to Japan and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''I started with (166 acres) and a pickup truck and now I farm''
3,954 acres, he said. ''I've done that by using my head -- and a lot
of luck.''
</P>
<P>
   The Labastida family is from Los Mochis, a farming city on the
Pacific coast of Sinaloa state, of which Labastida was governor
from 1987-92.
</P>
<P>
   Still living there are brothers Eduardo and Juan Enrique.
Brother Jaime and sisters Gloria Luz and Blanca Guadalupe live in
Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Enrique also is a farmer, and has been accused of shady
dealings. An outstanding debt of his reportedly was covered by a
multibillion-dollar bank bailout, although he and Francisco both
deny that.
</P>
<P>
   ''Juan Enrique had a loan he couldn't pay back -- he's a farmer --
but he already presented collateral for the credit,'' the candidate
said.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Labastida said none of his brothers held positions in
his government in Sinaloa state, so their alleged shortcomings are
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've never been involved in any official activity,'' he
said. ''They weren't before, and they certainly won't now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Eduardo said the reason he didn't hold a position was
because he didn't want to.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we had wanted opportunities, we've never lacked for them,''
he said. ''But we've never wanted them. No relative has ever done
business backed by the government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 0146 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chaos at Sierra Leone's Front Line  </HEADLINE>
By TIM SULLIVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASIAKA, Sierra Leone (AP) -- In the heat of the midday sun, at
the last highway junction before rebel country, young men with
glassy eyes sit in the shade of what's left of the Bond Street
Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Rocket launchers lie at their feet. Automatic rifles are cradled
in their hands, or stand propped against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   From their patio headquarters -- an orange and blue building
pocked with bullet holes and blasted by explosive rounds -- they
look over a town wracked by combat, littered with spent shell
casings and emptied of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Few of these men have much training, fewer still have uniforms.
Their notion of discipline often comes down to little more than
testosterone-fueled wars of will, with semi-soldiers shouting and
posturing and pointing their guns at one another.
</P>
<P>
   But for many of the people in the towns and villages outside
Freetown, the heavily guarded capital of this West African nation,
they are the protectors.
</P>
<P>
   ''These boys are fighting for us,'' said Abdul Kalokoh, one of
the small number of residents in town on a recent afternoon,
digging through his hut for food to carry back into the jungle,
where he was hiding from Sierra Leone's rebels. ''I want to come
back'' to Masiaka, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the two-lane highway from Freetown, where the city fades
quickly into small towns, palm plantations, thatch-roofed villages
and finally dense jungle, Masiaka is a key crossroad tying the
capital, about 45 miles to the west, to the interior.
</P>
<P>
   Until early May, a few thousand people lived here. Then, when
the Revolutionary United Front rebels launched an attack on
Freetown, Masiaka emptied, its people fleeing toward the capital or
into the surrounding forests.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels briefly held the town before Sierra Leone's ragged
military units -- its army, ousted junta soldiers and militia of
pro-government traditional hunters known as the Kamajors -- joined
to fight them back.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the rebels have launched attacks on Masiaka every
few days, most recently on Sunday, but have been repulsed each time
by the pro-government forces who are trying to push them further
away from Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   While the town is very tense, with soldiers watching for
possible guerrilla attacks or highway ambushes, it is also fairly
quiet, with more squabbling among its defenders than shooting from
the forest.
</P>
<P>
   The fighters form an unlikely combination. The army, allied with
the Kamajors, had fought the junta, allied with the rebels, just a
couple years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And none of them were even supposed to have guns. According to
the July peace accord that ended Sierra Leone's civil war and
brought the rebels into a rocky power-sharing government, all the
country's fighters were to be disarmed, and thousands of U.N.
peacekeepers were watch over the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The disarmament, though, limped along from the start and
thousands of fighters held onto their weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, apparently emboldened by the departure of a
Nigerian-led intervention force that acted as the country's de
facto army, the rebels began attacking the peacekeepers, eventually
taking hundreds captive along with their vehicles, weapons and
uniforms. A few days later, the RUF launched its attack on
Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a summons from ousted junta leader Johnny Paul
Koroma, the streets of Freetown were soon buzzing with commandeered
cars sprouting machine-gun barrels from every window. The Kamajors,
rural mystics who believe they can protect themselves in combat
with elaborate charms, began patrolling the city fully armed.
</P>
<P>
   But if such pictures would fuel fears of anarchy in the West,
many Sierra Leoenans welcomed the fighters back, seeing the U.N.
peacekeepers as useless protectors. Koroma, vilified just a few
years earlier after his forces ravaged Freetown following his 1997
coup, became a hero.
</P>
<P>
   For all their differences, the fighters are linked by a virulent
hatred for the RUF. It's a hatred that could, some say, enable the
rebels to finally be crushed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're all brothers now, except for the RUF, because they want
to kill all of us,'' said Lt. Abu Conteh, the 29-year-old Masiaka
commander. ''You tell the government'' we will take the main rebel
bases, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most Sierra Leoneans live in terror of the RUF, who during the
eight-year civil war mutilated victims by the thousands in a brutal
campaign of terror, hacking limbs from children as young as 2 and 3
years old.
</P>
<P>
   But Masiaka's soldiers don't look much like protectors. Even by
regional standards, where many armies are composed of poorly
trained and miserably paid men, many fighters seem more like gang
members than soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   They spend much of their days lounging at checkpoints, harassing
the few passers-by for change or cigarettes, drinking beer or small
plastic baggies of gin or smoking marijuana. Shouting matches among
the different units is common.
</P>
<P>
   Conteh, a 12-year army veteran whose serious demeanor often
seems out of place amid his raucous fighters, insists the forces
are serious soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking at a large-caliber shell casing lying on the asphalt, he
says they eventually will defeat the rebels: ''This is a cohesive
force that must be reckoned with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 0151 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NYC School Chief Has New Approach  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The man picked to run the nation's biggest
school system has never been a teacher and does not have a degree
in education. But the former banking executive notes that he has a
lot of experience dealing with ''screw-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The parallels with my corporate jobs are obvious: I want to
make sure the enterprise is run with a degree of humanity, but
tightly,'' said Harold Levy, a 47-year-old New Yorker who has been
interim chancellor of the New York City school system for the past
three months.
</P>
<P>
   Levy was expected to win Board of Education approval today to
run the 1.1 million-student system, which is plagued by guns, rats,
crumbling buildings, low test scores, an exodus of teachers, an
unyielding bureaucracy and an organization chart that looks like a
plumbing diagram.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, he supports raises for the district's 78,000
teachers, whose starting pay averages $31,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   He has also tried to appeal to students and administrators'
higher faculties.
</P>
<P>
   Levy sent poems by Wallace Stevens to the city's 43 school
superintendents, with a memo telling them he is interested in ''the
inner souls of people.'' Then he arranged a group violin lesson for
them at Carnegie Hall with virtuoso Isaac Stern to impress upon
them how difficult it is to learn -- and how music can be the
ultimate teaching tool.
</P>
<P>
   ''Art and music are the hook by which we get the attention of
students who might otherwise drift away,'' Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers union president Randi Weingarten said that raising
salaries ''is the only way to solve the biggest teacher shortage
we've ever faced, by attracting better ones.'' She pointed out that
New York City teacher salaries are about 25 percent lower on
average than those in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The private sector has outbid us when they want people with
similar skills,'' Weingarten said. ''Levy sees that. He's a strong
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy was named interim chancellor after the previous chancellor
left amid policy clashes with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. After a
nationwide search, all of the other candidates apparently decided
they had little chance against him.
</P>
<P>
   On teacher salaries, Levy could run into opposition from
Giuliani, who firmly controls the Board of Education's $10.6
billion budget. Giuliani supports raises based on teacher merit, as
judged by their students' performance.
</P>
<P>
   Board of Education member Ninfa Segarra, a Giuliani ally, said
she is not thrilled that Levy is the only candidate for chancellor.
And she suggested Levy is wasting time by talking poetry.
</P>
<P>
   She said he was hired for his corporate expertise, not for his
intellectual prowess, and ''he has a very limited amount of time to
do some very critical things.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy -- wearing an impeccably tailored dark suit and tasseled
dress shoes during a recent interview -- is on leave as director of
global compliance for Citigroup. Before that, he was the chief
litigator at Salomon Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   At Citigroup, ''I was in charge of screw-ups,'' Levy, an earthy
figure who occasionally drops four-letter words into the
conversation, said with amusement.
</P>
<P>
   He was also on the state Board of Regents, which oversees exams
required for high school graduation, before being named to the
$245,000-a-year post as chancellor. He is married, with two
children, a 6-year-old son and a 9-year-old daughter, who goes to a
private school.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Education headquarters building in Brooklyn may
itself be a metaphor for the state of the school system. It is
Kafkaesque labyrinth of rooms connected by long, dreary corridors.
</P>
<P>
   The day Levy first arrived, he said, ''it was filthy. There was
garbage in the halls. The word that leapt out was Windex!'' In his
office, he found two air conditioners going full blast, even though
it was January and the temperature outside was well below the
freezing point.
</P>
<P>
   He was told the air conditioners were needed to regulate the
antiquated heating system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
