<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ore. Court Denies Adoption Petition  </HEADLINE>
By TARA BURGHART
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- The Oregon Supreme Court has cleared the
way for adoptees 21 and over to find out the names of their birth
parents, the latest ruling in an emotional and closely watched
court battle.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-2 ruling Tuesday, the court dismissed motions to
reconsider its March ruling that upheld a law giving the adoptees
access to birth certificates.
</P>
<P>
   Barring appeals or injunctions, the decision means the law
approved by voters in 1998 will go into effect at 5 p.m. on May 30
-- allowing adoptees access to their birth certificates the next
day, according to Jim Nass, spokesman for the Oregon Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Hunsaker, the attorney representing six women who gave up
their children, said he and his clients were ''extremely
disappointed the court didn't review the case.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We felt it was the court's responsibility to rule on these
important constitutional issues and I'm at a loss as to why they
didn't,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The women, who have not been publicly identified, are expected
to make a decision on whether to appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court
before May 30. If they do appeal, Hunsaker said, he would first ask
for a stay keeping the records sealed. The court already has
refused to review a similar open adoption records law in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the law breaks a promise of secrecy made to women
who gave up their children for adoption. Adoptees say they have the
right to know the identities of their birth parents and the case
has dragged on too long.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has been an absolute roller coaster,'' said Helen Hill,
who sponsored the successful ballot measure. ''I understand we have
a system of checks and balances, and ultimately the system is very
fair. But it takes a lot longer than we would like to run its
course.''
</P>
<P>
   About 2,200 adoptees have applied for their birth certificates
from the Oregon Health Division. Cathy Allen, an elementary school
teacher in Beaverton, is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   A 49-year-old breast cancer survivor, Allen wants to find out
about her birth parents and her family's medical history to gain
information that could help her and her two children.
</P>
<P>
   She doubts her birth parents are alive but is aware she has some
half-siblings. She said she work through an intermediary to contact
them and honor their wishes if they did not want to meet her.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not trying to create a family if there isn't one possible.
I'm just seeking information to make the best emotional and medical
plans I can for my family,'' she said. ''The issue has been voted
on, it's been talked about. I think it's time to take effect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
