<HEADLINE> Lawyers Argue Vs. Elian Cuba Return  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Throwing the latest jab in the Elian Gonzalez
case in court, the 6-year-old's Miami relatives say he eventually
would be forced to cut sugar cane in a work camp if he is returned
to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the relatives filed a 25-page document Tuesday in
response to a motion filed by Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who wants to
replace them as his son's representative.
</P>
<P>
   If the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals grants the father's
motion, he would be free to drop the lawsuit seeking a U.S. asylum
hearing for the boy.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives' lawyers said parental rights Juan Miguel Gonzalez
claims in this country would be denied in Cuba, where Elian would
be separated from his father in a few years and sent to work camps
for months at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ''Irrespective of (his father's) wishes, Elian will be doing
agricultural work such as cutting sugar cane in the fields, to
further indoctrinate him and separate him ... for extended periods
to break down the bond between parent and child and cement the bond
between child and state,'' the lawyers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers filed their own brief Tuesday, reiterating
their argument that answers to questions on the asylum application
Elian signed in block letters reflect the beliefs and concerns of
his great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez, not the boy himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''None contains information that came from Elian,'' the
government lawyers wrote. ''All are written in the third person.
There is no reason to believe that Elian could possibly affirm
their contents.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian was rescued Thanksgiving Day off the Florida coast after a
boat wreck killed his mother and other fleeing Cubans. After living
with his Miami relatives for five months, he was taken from their
home by federal authorities April 22 and is with his father at a
Maryland retreat.
</P>
<P>
   Three judges from the 11th Circuit are considering whether a
child as young as Elian can seek asylum despite his father's wish
to return with the boy to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives -- Elian's cousin Marisleysis and Lazaro
Gonzalez -- want the court to force immigration officials to give
Elian an asylum hearing. The government has sided with Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, who says he should be allowed to decide for the boy as
his sole surviving parent.
</P>
<P>
   Elian has been ordered to remain in the United States until a
decision is reached by the judges, who heard oral arguments in the
case last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
