<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newark Sued Over Bearded Police  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- The Justice Department has sued the city,
claiming it is discriminating against two Muslim police officers
because of their religion.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit filed Tuesday on behalf of all bearded Muslim
officers in Newark seeks damages for any current or former officers
who were the victims of bias. Seven months ago, the U.S. Supreme
Court allowed the two officers to have beards as an exception to
department policy.
</P>
<P>
   The city threatened the officers with termination and other
sanctions because of their beliefs, which include wearing beards,
according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ''Employers have a duty to accommodate reasonably the religious
observances, practices and beliefs of employees,'' said Bill Lann
Lee, acting assistant attorney general for civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   The city has argued the no-beard policy was intended to present
a ''professional and dignified image to the public'' and establish
discipline and solidarity within the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   But after the two officers won in the Supreme Court, Newark
Police Director Joseph Santiago said the department would change
its rules to abide by the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The department has since submitted a revised ''grooming policy''
to the city for review, and has not disciplined any officers for
wearing a beard, the department said in a statement issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The department declined to comment further, as did a spokeswoman
for Mayor Sharpe James.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, a State Park Police officer who claimed he was
suspended for wearing a beard as a sign of his Muslim faith will be
paid $25,700 in back wages and rehired as a ranger, attorneys said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement of a federal lawsuit, State Park Police
also agreed to revise regulations to specify that officers may seek
exemptions to the force's no-beard rule on religious grounds.
</P>
<P>
   New York Assistant Attorney General Bonnie Garone said the state
denies any wrongdoing. She asserted Officer Muhammad Ali always had
the right to apply for an exemption under the old regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Justice Department: http://www.usdoj.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
