<HEADLINE> Ore. Holds Mail-In Election  </HEADLINE>
By BRAD CAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Oregon made history Tuesday as ballots
were counted in the nation's first regular primary election
conducted not at polling places but by mail -- a move intended to
improve turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Ballots were mailed to voters' households on April 28 and had to
be returned to local election offices by Tuesday night to be
counted. Late Tuesday, the secretary of state's office estimated
voter turnout at 47 percent, which would be the highest since the
1992 primary, which had a turnout of 49.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since Al Gore and George W. Bush have sewn up their parties'
presidential nominations, and there is no Oregon governor's race
this year, the primary didn't generate much heat. But there were
six ballot measures, along with primary races for Congress,
secretary of state, treasurer and the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Voters rejected a measure that would have let the Legislature
clamp limits on the amount of ''pain and suffering'' money or other
damages people can be awarded when they sue over injuries.
</P>
<P>
   With 54 percent of the vote counted, the measure was being
trounced by a margin of 74 percent to 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and other supporters of Measure 81 said restrictions on
jury awards were needed to hold down insurance costs. Trial lawyers
and victims' rights advocates who opposed the measure said juries,
not politicians, should decide how much money is awarded to people
who are injured by faulty products or someone else's negligence.
</P>
<P>
   Another high-profile issue on the ballot headed for a resounding
defeat was a proposed nickel-a-gallon gasoline tax increase to pay
for road repairs. With 54 percent of the vote counted, the measure
was being voted down 88 percent to 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the tax pulled the plug on the campaign two months
ago after it became obvious people wouldn't vote for such an
increase at a time of rapidly rising gas prices.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Bush and Gore easily won their parties'
nominations.
</P>
<P>
   The most hotly contested state race was between ''the battling
Lynns'' -- two Republicans who want to run against incumbent
Secretary of State Bill Bradbury.
</P>
<P>
   With 54 percent of the state's precincts reporting, House
Speaker Lynn Snodgrass had 47 percent of the vote to 45 percent for
state Rep. Lynn Lundquist. Bradbury, who was unopposed for the
Democratic nomination, is considered the early favorite heading
into November.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1980s, Oregonians have voted by mail in local
elections and special statewide elections. But this is the first
all-mail ballot for a regularly scheduled election.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Oregonians voted to abolish the traditional
polling place in all statewide elections in favor of the mail
ballot. Supporters say it's cheaper and more convenient.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Oregon Secretary of State: http://www.sos.state.or.us/
</P>
</TEXT>
