<HEADLINE> Combs is denied separate trial  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Sean ''Puffy'' Combs' motion to separate his
bribery and gun trial from the trials of two co-defendants arrested
with him after a nightclub shooting has been denied.
</P>
<P>
   Combs' lawyer, Benjamin Brafman, said he asked for a separate
trial for his client because the judge plans to allow a jury to
hear evidence that would be barred if Combs were tried alone. The
evidence might be unfairly prejudicial, Brafman said.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan State Supreme Justice Charles Solomon, who will hear
the trial of the three men, denied Brafman's motion Tuesday, saying
he had ''failed to establish good cause for granting a severance in
this case.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge also rejected Brafman's challenge of the prosecution's
presentation to the grand jury. The judge said he found the
prosecution had set forth a sufficient basis to establish Combs'
guilt of the crimes charged.
</P>
<P>
   Combs, 30, was arrested with bodyguard Anthony ''Wolf'' Jones,
34, as the two fled the scene of a shooting at Club New York in the
Times Square area in the early hours of Dec. 27.
</P>
<P>
   Combs protege Jamal ''Shyne'' Barrow, 19, was arrested at the
scene after siding with his mentor during a dispute in which a man
reportedly threw money in Combs' face. Barrow, charged with
attempted murder, allegedly shot a woman in the face and hit two
men in their right shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Combs is charged with two counts of illegal gun possession. One
count stems from police allegedly finding a 9 mm pistol in the
Lincoln Navigator in which Combs, Jones and Combs' girlfriend,
Jennifer Lopez, fled the club. The other count was filed because of
a 9 mm pistol that was allegedly thrown out of the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Combs is also charged with bribery for allegedly offering to pay
his driver $50,000 to claim ownership of the gun in the car. Police
said he tried to sweeten the deal by offering the driver a diamond
ring Lopez had given him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm innocent,'' Combs said outside court. ''I want to go to
trial and get this behind me. When a jury hears my case, they'll
see that I'm innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, jury selection in a civil lawsuit against Combs
begins Monday. The lawsuit blames him for a deadly stampede during
a celebrity basketball game on Dec. 28, 1991, an event he organized
at City College of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Nine young people died and 29 others were injured in the crush
of people who tried to get into the event. One of the survivors,
Nicole Levy, sued CCNY, Combs and another rapper, Dwight ''Heavy
D'' Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Combs settled all the other CCNY-related lawsuits out of court.
</P>
<P>
   The judge scheduled hearings for June 14 for Jones and Barrow on
whether they were properly identified, whether evidence and
statements were legally obtained and whether prosecutors can ask
them about previous arrests. Those hearings do not involve Combs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
