<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Trade Bill a Yawn in Senate  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Like the summer squall that drenches only one
side of the street, the debate over granting China permanent trade
benefits has spawned a tempest on the House side, but left the
Senate basking under clear skies.
</P>
<P>
   The China trade bill is being fought to the wire in the House.
Organized labor is battling it fiercely, confronting an equally
intense campaign in support of the legislation from the Clinton
administration and the business community.
</P>
<P>
   With a week to go before a House vote, neither side can say for
sure who will prevail on the measure to normalize trade relations
with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're losing some and getting some,'' President Clinton said
Tuesday of the still-large ''undecided'' bloc in the House. Still,
he predicted its eventual passage.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, all is placid. The bill enjoys wide bipartisan
support, generating only a handful of naysayers.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House Ways and Means Committee and the Senate Finance
Committee take up the China trade bill today -- and their
deliberations should help underscore the differences in approach.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic divide across the congressional street ''reflects
institutional differences,'' suggested Lee Hamilton, the former
Indiana congressman who was chairman of the House International
Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think senators look upon themselves as national
officeholders more than members of the House do,'' said Hamilton,
who now heads the Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars.
''Members of the House look upon themselves as local officials.
There's a much different perspective, frame of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   House members have far more vulnerability in this election year.
Senators serve for staggered six-year terms -- so in any given
election year, only a third of the seats are up for re-election.
All 435 House seats are up at every election.
</P>
<P>
   And interest groups -- in this case labor unions and
environmental groups -- are able to more effectively rally
opposition in individual House districts than across an entire
state.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dick Lugar, R-Ind., a senior member of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee and a China-trade supporter, said that because
of narrower constituencies, many House members over the years have
consistently voted against trade-liberalization bills.
</P>
<P>
   That includes so-called fast track, legislation authorizing U.S.
membership in the World Trade Organization and the North American
Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''There might be a broader perspective'' in the Senate, Lugar
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   The China bill will be debated in the House next week. If it
passes, the Senate will take it up in June. Both houses must pass
the legislation for it to be enacted.
</P>
<P>
   It would end the annual practice of renewing China's trade
status and grant Beijing the same normal trade relations that the
United States extends routinely to nearly every other nation in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would ease China's entry into the Geneva-based WTO
-- although China could still become a member without congressional
consent.
</P>
<P>
   James Thurber, a political scientist at American University,
said House members represent ''a specific narrow constituency,''
while ''constituencies in the Senate are broad and complex.''
</P>
<P>
   ''When senators try to get re-elected, they have broader view of
what the public interest is,'' Thurber said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Labor has been running ads making life miserable for
Democratic House members,'' complains Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., who
opposes the bill but criticizes Labor's tactics.
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO President John Sweeney insists that with the bill, the
United States ''gives up -- permanently and unconditionally -- it's
ability to use economic leverage to insist that China stop its
horrifying human rights abuses.''
</P>
<P>
   But labor is not making the case as forcefully among senators.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean there are no Senate opponents. Sen. Arlen
Specter, R-Pa., announced his opposition on Tuesday, saying Beijing
''threatens world peace by flagrantly proliferating weapons of mass
destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's clearly in the minority.
</P>
<P>
   The president has been making a full-court press to win over
House members, meanwhile.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, the senior Democrat on the
Ways and Means Committee, said he didn't get much in the way of
goodies in exchange for his much-sought announcement of support on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're going to give me a free plane ride to Albany so I can
endorse the president's wife (in her Senate race),'' Rangel joked.
''Big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Tom Raum covers national and international
affairs for The Associated Press.
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   White House working group on China: http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO campaign to stop China Trade bill:
http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 0206 </TRAILER>
