<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 10:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Drops in Euro Nations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Inflation in the 11 nations that have
adopted the euro averaged an annual rate of 1.9 percent in April,
down from a record high of 2.1 percent in March, the European
Union's statistical office said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The easing will be welcomed by the European Central Bank, which
saw its 2 percent target exceeded in March for the first time since
the single currency was launched on Jan. 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Lower inflation was linked to a decline in oil prices. The rapid
rise in oil prices had pushed up the inflation reading at the
beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The April inflation rate was the lowest since January but well
above the 1.1 percent annual rate of April 1999, according to
Eurostat data.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the generally good news for the ECB, there will likely
be concern that prices excluding energy rose at a 1.1 percent
annual rate in April compared with 0.9 percent in March. Some
analysts attributed that rise to the weakness of the euro against
the dollar, which is making imported goods more expensive in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   EU officials were also worried by the growing gap between
inflation rates in various euro-zone nations. While France
registered a 1.4 percent annual rate and Germany 1.6 percent,
Ireland recorded 5 percent and Spain 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''The increasing inflation rate in Ireland confirms the ... view
that there are risks of overheating in the Irish economy,'' said
Pedro Solbes, the EU finance commissioner. He suggested the Irish
government should seriously consider increasing taxes to cool
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Taking in the four member nations yet to adopt the euro, the EU
inflation rate fell to an annual rate of 1.7 percent in April from
1.9 percent the previous month. Britain continued to have the EU's
lowest rate at an annual rate of 0.6 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
