<HEADLINE> Dow Down 107; Nasdaq Down 65  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell in early trading today as investors
took profits from the market's recent rally and determined that the
interest rate increase implemented by the Federal Reserve on
Tuesday may indeed threaten stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 107.60.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was down 16.53 to 1,449.51, and the Nasdaq composite
index was down 65.34 to 3,652.23.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said stocks were due to falter today as investors tried
to capture gains from a four-day rally that was capped Tuesday when
the Fed, as expected, raised interest rates a half-percentage point
-- its steepest increase in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates are generally bad for stocks, raising
borrowing costs and cutting into bottom-line profits. Investors had
bid stocks higher on the hope that Tuesday's increase could be the
last for a while, but with many economists predicting still higher
rates later this year, many investors lost their nerve today,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard, the top-performing Dow component on Tuesday,
fell 6~ to 133[. After the close of trading Tuesday, the company
reported second-quarter earnings that topped Wall Street analysts'
expectations. But testy investors may have been expecting
Hewlett-Packard to more dramatically exceed published estimates,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Rate-sensitive financial stocks were also lower. American
Express fell 7/16 to 36 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 8-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 115.57 million
shares, behind Tuesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 5.86 to 500.12.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.8 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 1.9 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 1.7 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 1.7 percent.
</P>
