<HEADLINE> U.S. Bancorp CFO Steps Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- One of the highest-ranking women bankers in
the nation is stepping down as chief financial officer of U.S.
Bancorp.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Lester, 43, said Wednesday that she decided to leave the
bank last year. She will be replaced by Andrew Cecere, 39.
</P>
<P>
   Lester, CFO since 1996 and executive vice president of finance
since 1995, said she told John Grundhofer, the bank's chief
executive officer, of her decision to leave in the early fall.
</P>
<P>
   Lester will stay with the bank for a couple of months to assist
Cecere's transition into the job. She doesn't know what she will do
next and doesn't plan to begin job hunting until October.
</P>
<P>
   Lester said she was most proud of her work on acquisitions,
which helped the once-ailing First Bank System become U.S. Bancorp,
the nation's 11th-largest bank spanning 16 states with $83 billion
in assets. She also was an advocate for better job flexibility for
employees struggling with work and life issues.
</P>
<P>
   Cecere joined U.S. Bancorp 15 years ago and most recently served
as vice chairman in charge of commercial services.
</P>
</TEXT>
