   Toyota Profits Jump 14 Percent
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Record export sales at Toyota Motor Corp. softened
the impact of a rising yen and helped lift profits 14 percent for
the year. Japan's largest automaker said today it posted a group
profit of 406.7 billion yen ($3.72 billion) in the fiscal year
ended March 31, up from 356.1 billion yen ($3.26 billion) a year
earlier. The maker of the Camry sedan and Lexus line of luxury cars
enjoyed record demand in North America and other export markets,
selling more than 3 million vehicles overseas for the first time
ever. Sales rose 1 percent to 12.8 trillion yen ($11.7 billion).
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong Plans High-Tech Park
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- The government signed a contract with Pacific
Century CyberWorks Ltd. today for the construction of a
high-technology industrial park. The construction cost for the
''Cyberport,'' a large-scale development that will include offices
for information technology companies and homes for workers, was
fixed at $2 billion, the government said in a statement. Any cost
overruns will be borne by PCCW, a local Internet startup owned by
33-year-old Richard Li, son of property tycoon Li Ka-shing,
according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Euro Nations Have 1.9 Pct. Inflation
</P>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Inflation in the 11 nations that have
adopted the euro averaged an annual rate of 1.9 percent in April,
down from a record high of 2.1 percent in March, the European
Union's statistical office said today. The easing will be welcomed
by the European Central Bank, which saw its 2 percent target
exceeded in March for the first time since the single currency was
launched on Jan. 1, 1999. Lower inflation was linked to a decline
in oil prices. The rapid rise in oil prices had pushed up the
inflation reading at the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Granada, Compass Groups To Merge
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Hotel and TV network owner Granada Group PLC said
today it plans to merge with hospitality business Compass Group PLC
to form a combined concern worth about $26.3 billion. The merger
would give Granada shareholders control of about 66.3 percent of
the enlarged group and is the first step toward the eventual sale
of shares in Granada's Media as a stand-alone business. Granada
said an independent Granada Media would be better placed to grow
through further consolidation. Such a step likely would heat up the
race to create Britain's largest commercial broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
   Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stocks markets closed mixed today, with
Japan and Hong Kong closing lower and other exchanges rallying on
relief that a long-anticipated U.S. interest rate hike fell within
expectations. In Tokyo, prices fell as investors sold shares that
had risen in the morning. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell
147.22 points, or 0.84 percent, to 17,551.25. Hong Kong shares
plunged as investors feared the territory's monetary officials
would increase local interest rates when they meet Friday. The
blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 2.2 percent, or 332.48 points, to
14,827.81. Taipei's Weighted Price Index rallied 357.92 points, or
4.1 percent, at 9,085.74.
</P>
