<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall on Profit-Taking  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks stumbled today as investors took profits
from the market's recent rally and determined that the interest
rate increase implemented by the Federal Reserve on Tuesday may
indeed threaten stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was down 133.30 at 10,801.27.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was down 18.91 to 1,447.13, and the Nasdaq composite
index was down 82.94 to 3,634.63.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said stocks were due to falter today as investors tried
to capture gains from a four-day rally that was capped Tuesday when
the Fed, as expected, raised interest rates a half-percentage point
-- its steepest increase in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates are generally bad for stocks, raising
borrowing costs and cutting into bottom-line profits. Investors had
bid stocks higher on the hope that Tuesday's increase could be the
last for a while, but with many economists predicting still higher
rates later this year, many investors lost their nerve today,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the accumulation of rate hikes that truly hampers stock
market performance over time,'' said Gail Dudack, chief equity
strategist at UBS Warburg in New York. ''We do expect lower lows in
May and June to materialize before a better and more sustainable
summer rally can begin.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard, the top-performing Dow component on Tuesday,
plunged 9 13/16 to 130 3/16. After the close of trading Tuesday,
the company reported second-quarter earnings that topped Wall
Street analysts' expectations. But testy investors may have been
expecting Hewlett-Packard to more dramatically exceed published
estimates, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Agilent, the testing and measuring equipment maker that was spun
off from Hewlett-Packard, fell 15} to 80\.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer goods stocks were also lower today. Johnson &AMP; Johnson
fell 1 3/16 to 86[ and Procter &AMP; Gamble fell 13/16 to 64\.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 8-to-3 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 279.09 million
shares, behind Tuesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 6.15 to 499.83.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
