<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 11:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ABC, WB Networks Present Schedules  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- CBS is retooling its Friday and Saturday night
schedules this fall to add four new dramas and is sending in Bette
Midler to compete against ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   Midler will star in ''The Bette Show'' on Wednesday nights, a
situation comedy in which she plays a character suspiciously like
herself.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is canceling its long-running medical drama ''Chicago
Hope,'' ''Martial Law,'' ''Early Edition,'' ''Now and Again'' and
''Ladies Man.'' Bill Cosby is also off CBS's schedule: His
''Cosby'' has retired and CBS hasn't picked up ''Kids Say the
Darndest Things.''
</P>
<P>
   On Fridays, CBS will air an update of the classic series ''The
Fugitive'' and ''C.S.I.,'' a drama about a team of forensic
investigators in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   With ABC and NBC both scheduling movies on Saturdays, CBS will
try three dramas. It will bring back ''Walker, Texas Ranger'' and
start two new series: ''That's Life,'' about a New Jersey girl who
ditches her blue-collar fiance and goes back to college, and ''The
District,'' about a police commissioner who tries to shake up
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is also shifting the newsmagazine ''48 Hours'' to Thursdays
at 8 p.m. and moving ''Diagnosis Murder'' to Thursdays at 10 p.m.
The medical drama ''City of Angels'' will stay on the schedule in
part because of concerns about the lack of minorities in major TV
roles, CBS President Leslie Moonves said after the fall lineup was
announced today.
</P>
<P>
   Fox and UPN are scheduled to announce their fall schedules
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Midler leads a pack of three new CBS comedies. She has the
unenviable task of competing against ''Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' the ABC game show that Moonves admits ''drives me
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I lie awake at night thinking of how to fight this thing and I
don't have the answer yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, ABC announced it would add a fourth night of
''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   With four prime-time hours of the hit show with Regis Philbin,
ABC is adding only four new series in the fall. The network
canceled the critically acclaimed ''Sports Night'' and trimmed its
newsmagazine schedule from four nights to three.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the youth-oriented WB network hopes to recover some
of its sizzle with a fall schedule that includes two nights of
comedies, including a parody of the teen angst dramas it has lived
on the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ''Millionaire'' has been a ratings juggernaut since its premiere
last August, and industry analysts have estimated it will earn
between $400 million to $600 million in profits next year.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is adding Geena Davis to its lineup in ''Geena,'' a comedy
about a career woman thrust into the role of mom by marrying a
widower. It also is adding a medical drama with former ''Homicide''
star Andre Braugher, and a comedy with Gabriel Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   The WB's young comedies on Friday include the new ''Grosse
Pointe,'' a spoof of the behind-the-scenes lives of actors starring
in a teen drama.
</P>
<P>
   The network, whose ratings sagged this year, scheduled six
comedies on Sunday nights. It picked up the animated show ''The
PJs'' from Fox and moved ''The Jamie Foxx Show,'' ''The Steve
Harvey Show'' and ''For Your Love'' to Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.cbs.com; http://www.abc.com and
http://www.warnerbros.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1132 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0074 </DOCNO>
