<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Finds Bear Stearns Negligent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bear Stearns Cos. was ordered to pay $111.5
million to a Canadian investor after a federal jury in Manhattan
found it acted negligently when it made unauthorized trades in his
account.
</P>
<P>
   Henryk de Kwiatkowski, the 76-year-old owner of a Kentucky
thoroughbred-horse-breeding farm who now lives in the Bahamas, had
claimed in a lawsuit that Bear Stearns Cos. cost him $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the jury in U.S. District Court concluded Tuesday that a
broker at Bear Stearns had not acted negligently and that the
company had not breached its fiduciary duty.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the jury did find that the company acted negligently and
owed de Kwiatkowski $111.5 million. It was one of the largest jury
awards ever handed a Wall Street firm accused of wronging an
individual investor.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the company argued during the two-week trial that de
Kwiatkowski was a sophisticated investor, putting up to $6.5
billion at stake in trading in the high-risk currency futures
markets.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Bear Stearns said: ''The verdict was against the
weight of the evidence, and we intend to appeal. We are confident
we will be vindicated upon appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Curran, a lawyer for de Kwiatkowski, said his client ''is
gratified that he was vindicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Curran said he would submit an application to the court
Wednesday for his client to receive interest on the damages.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Poland, de Kwiatkowski fled the Nazis and escaped
from a Soviet prison camp during World War II. He built his fortune
leasing airplanes and in sales before purchasing Calumet Farm in
Kentucky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1134 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0076 </DOCNO>
