<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amway To Cut 1,300 Jobs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADA, Mich. (AP) -- Direct-sales giant Amway Corp. said today it
plans to cut nearly 11 percent of its global work force, or 1,300
jobs, as part of a restructuring expected to save $300 million
annually.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was expected. Amway announced in February that
it was reorganizing in response to sluggish sales and the changing
business environment, and cuts were likely.
</P>
<P>
   About 900 jobs will be cut at the company's world headquarters
in Ada. Another 260 jobs will be slashed overseas with the
remainder of the cuts coming from Amway's California operations in
Buena Park and Lakeview.
</P>
<P>
   Management and salaried positions will be most affected by the
cuts, according to the company. The company expects to identify
most of the affected positions by Aug. 31. Most employees will
leave by year's end, but it could be 15 months before all the cuts
are completed.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the restructuring, Amway plans to divide its
worldwide operations into three business units.
</P>
<P>
   The privately held Amway, one of the world's largest
direct-sales companies with about $6 billion in annual revenue,
employs about 12,000 people worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1135 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Treasury Bond Prices Retreat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Treasury bond prices were retreating at midday.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the Treasury's 10-year note was down 9-32 point, or
$2.81\ per $1,000 in face value, around midday today, while its
yield rose to 6.45 percent from 6.42 percent late Tuesday. Prices
and yields move in opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bonds were down 13-16 point and yielded 6.16
percent, up from 6.10 percent late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 6.09 percent as the
discount fell 0.09 percentage point from late Tuesday to 5.93
percent. Six-month yields were 6.47 percent as the discount fell
0.03 percentage point to 6.19 percent. One-year yields were 6.35
percent as the discount held unchanged at Tuesday's late rate of
6.04 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1143 </TRAILER>
