<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Panel OKs China Trade Bill  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton's bill to extend permanent
favorable trade benefits to China gained a major boost today as the
Senate Finance Committee voted 18-1 to approve it.
</P>
<P>
   The House Ways and Means Committee was also expected to approve
the measure later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Finance Committee Chairman William Roth, R-Del., called
the measure ''a defining moment in our relationship with China.''
</P>
<P>
   The sole vote against the bill was cast by Sen. Jim Jeffords,
R-Vt. He said he was doing so primarily to protest the continued
imprisonment in China of Tibetan musicologist Ngawang Choepel, who
had attended a Vermont college.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords charged he was being held unjustly and that China had
also banned his mother from visiting her son in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''If China cannot obey its own laws in this case, how can we
expect it to follow the far more burdensome rules of the World
Trade Organization?'' asked Jeffords.
</P>
<P>
   The lopsided vote reflects the fact that the bill has wide
bipartisan support in the Senate. However, its fate in the House
was less certain, with organized labor waging an intensive campaign
to defeat it.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would end 20 years of annual congressional votes on
China's trade status and grant it ''permanent normal trade
relations,'' the same low-tariff access to U.S. markets that nearly
every other nation in the world already enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   It would also ease China's entry into the World Trade
Organization, the Geneva-based group that oversees world trade.
China was a founding member of the WTO's predecessor, the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, but it withdraw after the 1949
communist takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the wide margin of passage, several committee members
expressed some skepticism over whether normalizing economic ties
would bring about improvements in China's human-rights record.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those who say change will come quickly may be misjudging 5,000
years of Chinese history,'' said Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rockefeller and other proponents of the bill said they
were persuaded that it would help open Chinese markets to U.S.
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''We better figure out how we can live in peace with these
people because there are so many of them,'' said Sen. Bob Graham,
D-Fla., of the world's most populous nations.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., a top Senate sponsor of the trade
bill, portrayed the panel's vote -- the first of any congressional
votes on the measure -- as ''a good opportunity for us to seize the
momentum'' in advance of the more difficult House battle.
</P>
<P>
   On the House side, Rep. Sander Levin, D-Mich., and Rep. Doug
Bereuter, R-Neb., reached agreement with House Ways and Means
Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, and other key lawmakers on
language to be included in the China bill that would provide
protections for American industries against a sudden surge in
imports with China.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said that the compromise, which was reached in
negotiations late Tuesday night, was to be included in the bill
that the Ways and Means Committee was scheduled to vote on.
</P>
<P>
   Levin and Bereuter are also pushing for creation of a human
rights commission that would issue annual reports on China's
performance to take the place of the annual congressional vote. But
House aides said that final agreement on the language for that
proposal would probably not come until the House Rules Committee
takes up the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Their legislation is being sponsored in the Senate by Baucus and
Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1157 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'N Sync Feels the Power  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Know your power.
</P>
<P>
   Those three words of advice from someone who had been in their
position seem to be a secret mantra for the five members of 'N
Sync.
</P>
<P>
   They came from Jordan Knight, the ex-member of New Kids on the
Block who is enjoying a second act after teen stardom. He passed on
the wisdom when the two acts were touring together a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Know who controls your business and that's you,'' said 'N
Sync's Lance Bass. ''And we didn't realize that until this last
year -- that we are in control. And without us five guys, nothing
could happen. ... We finally realized that and took control of our
own business.''
</P>
<P>
   Who can argue with the results? 'N Sync is white-hot, now
plainly the leaders of the teen-oriented pop style that's driving
the music business today.
</P>
<P>
   The group shattered a record when its album, ''No Strings
Attached,'' sold 2.4 million copies in one week in March. It's now
up to 5.2 million sold and quickly climbing. Bass, Joey Fatone,
Justin Timberlake, Chris Kirkpatrick and JC Chasez are spending
their summer performing at sold-out concerts packed with squealing
girls.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing their power arguably put them in that position. ''No
Strings Attached'' plainly pokes fun at their image as a boy band
controlled by others; the album cover and video for ''Bye Bye Bye''
depicts them as puppets.
</P>
<P>
   The quintet fought a messy legal battle to extricate themselves
from a record deal arranged by its former promoter, Lou Pearlman,
that was settled late last year.
</P>
<P>
   The fight cast them in the role of artists under assault -- just
the kind of thing that brings out the overprotective instincts in
teen-age girls. It undoubtedly helped send ''No Strings Attached''
into overdrive.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were worried in the first place that we weren't going to
get out of it,'' Kirkpatrick said. ''We thought that this was going
to hold up our careers for a good five years, keep us in litigation
and different trials here and there. But, luckily, we got out.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirkpatrick advises anyone who considers 'N Sync just another
boy band to listen to the album.
</P>
<P>
   ''They can see us in performance and they can see us in
interviews and realize we're individuals,'' he said. ''We put
ourselves together. We're a totally different group than what
people are trying to make us out to be.''
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync's critics probably aren't even interested in listening
to the group's music, Fatone said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We enjoy the music,'' he said. ''It's not like we're just
trying to throw something together just to sell the album. It's
something that we put our blood, sweat and tears into, especially
this album due to all the legal issues.''
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync wasn't too happy about the ABC television series,
''Making the Band,'' which followed Pearlman as he tried to create
another teen sensation. It fell flat in the ratings and has been
canceled, but it still stung.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since it was made by one of the guys that put money behind us
in the beginning, you know, they flip it around and make it look
like he's out there, he's the one that's putting the group
together,'' Kirkpatrick said. ''He's the one sitting in
choreography rehearsals, putting in his input. He's the one in
vocal rehearsals when, in actuality, we didn't talk to him for
months at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ''It kind of clumps us into this thing and making us look like
we're like that group,'' he said. ''And it really kind of takes
away some of our credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatone's bought a house from the profits of ''No Strings
Attached.'' So has Bass. It's hard to know when they'll have the
chance to enjoy these fruits of their success.
</P>
<P>
   When the tour ends, they have August and September to write and
record another album. Then they head to Europe for a concert tour
with Britney Spears. Then it's back to North America for another
tour around the holidays. Then it's time to make a movie. By next
spring, it will be time to promote another album.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that when Fatone is asked to pick a song that best
describes what his life is like now, he chooses Michael Jackson's
''Working Day and Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Chasez said rehearsals for the concert tour were killers.
</P>
<P>
   ''This tour is going to be physically exhausting,'' he said. ''I
think everyone who watches the show, they're going to walk away
amazed, but they're going to walk away tired. That includes the
fans, because it's such a high-energy show. We've been looking at
the set list and working out the details of the show, and we're
literally now trying to find places where we can breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   What does 'N Sync see itself doing in 10 years?
</P>
<P>
   ''Most likely doing a little bit less dancing,'' deadpanned a
tired Chasez.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a bigger house,'' Kirkpatrick added.
</P>
<P>
   They're intent upon staying in the business. ''We're always
going to grow up with our fans,'' Bass said. ''You know, those
teens can't stay teens forever.''
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync admitted to some nervousness heading out on their
concert tour, not wanting to disappoint fans who overwhelmed phone
lines and box offices to snap up the tickets -- and maybe because of
their newfound power.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're excited to say that everything you see is done by us,''
Bass said. ''And it's dangerous to say that because if anything
goes wrong, if we happen to make a mistake here or there, we're
going to be blamed.
</P>
<P>
   ''But that's OK because, you know, we've learned from our
mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
