<DOCNO> APW20000517.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woody Allen Hits Campus Circuit  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- What an odd place for Woody Allen to turn up:
Los Angeles, the city whose only cultural advantage, he once said,
was that it let you ''make a right turn on a red light.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as strange is the venue: Allen, a self-professed lousy
student who was kicked out of New York University, now sits on a
theater stage at UCLA, leading an academic dialogue about writing
and moviemaking to an audience of film students, teachers and fans.
</P>
<P>
   Averse to the marketing mill, Allen decided to promote his
latest film -- the comedy ''Small Time Crooks,'' starring himself
and Tracy Ullman, and opening Friday -- by sharing 35 years of movie
experience with young filmmakers and industry enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   He went back to school for a week this month, visiting prominent
film schools to show the movie and answer questions about how he
does what he does. The tour of NYU, the University of Chicago, UCLA
and Harvard was fortuitously scheduled so Allen could be home in
Manhattan to catch the New York Knicks' home playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's all timed perfectly. I haven't missed a game,'' Allen
said before his UCLA appearance in an interview at his ornate
Beverly Hills hotel suite (the ''Mussolini suite,'' he calls it,
welcoming a visitor).
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought this would not only be a painless way to do
publicity for the film but a nice thing to do,'' Allen says. ''I'm
enjoying the experience of answering questions for them because I
think that I'm teaching them something and being helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   In the packed theater at UCLA, Allen's got an adoring audience.
They wouldn't be here if they didn't love his films. It's something
like the devotion shown by Emmet Ray, Sean Penn's jazz-guitarist
hero from Allen's ''Sweet and Lowdown,'' who swoons in the presence
of his idol, Django Reinhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ditched class to come here,'' one student tells the
director, adding that she spotted her professor in the room ''so he
ditched class, too.'' She says she wrote her question down so she
wouldn't throw up out of nervousness, and asks Allen if there's a
single theme running through his pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ''People think my films have a kind of sameness, like 'Oh,
another Woody Allen movie,''' Allen replies. ''From where I sit,
they're very, very different, but maybe I'm not seeing it.''
</P>
<P>
   He compares it to Chinese food: While a Chinese buffet might be
rich in variety, with 100 different dishes, diners tend to group it
all just as Chinese food.
</P>
<P>
   If his films do have a recurring theme, he wisecracks, it's one
''that keeps people out of theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Small Time Crooks'' could help Allen break out of his bind as
a beloved American filmmaker whose movies generally do little at
the U.S. box office. Loaded with sight gags and funny put-downs,
the story of a bank heist planned by a lovably cretinous gang is
one of his lightest comedies since the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ''My films are not made for box office, and indeed, they don't
get the box office,'' Allen says at his hotel. ''I've never been in
that hit-flop sweepstakes because I would be a consistent loser all
the time, and have been.''
</P>
<P>
   He's had a few breakout hits such as ''Hannah and Her Sisters,''
but Allen's movies generally remain in the $4 million to $12
million range domestically. The last two, ''Sweet and Lowdown'' and
''Celebrity,'' grossed $4 million to $5 million each.
</P>
<P>
   Much like jazz, which Allen plays weekly in New York City gigs,
he is a popular American export, however, and European audiences
have kept his film career going.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a different culture, so a film in Europe by certain
directors, no matter how serious it is or how comic, once they glom
on to a certain director, you become box office,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ''Again, if it wasn't for Europe, I think I would have been in a
different business 20 years ago. I mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for his fans that didn't happen, and the UCLA crowd tells
him so.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd like to ask you a favor: Do not stop working,'' one
student tells Allen. He asks if Allen has thought about doing
director's commentary or otherwise enhancing DVD releases of his
films. Allen says no.
</P>
<P>
   ''I make the film, this is the film, that's the end of it,''
Allen says. ''If you like it, you like it. If you don't like, you
don't. I've never thought of supplementing it with anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Another student tells Allen she's a ''humongous fan'' of his
Ingmar Bergman-style drama ''Another Woman.'' Another asks about
the inspiration for that movie, which prompts a discussion of
Allen's comedies vs. the much less popular dramas.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe they're not popular because I can't do them well. Maybe
they're not popular because dramas are never as popular,'' Allen
says.
</P>
<P>
   He confesses that for all his comic talents, he always wanted to
be a serious dramatist like Eugene O'Neill or Tennessee Williams --
''real heavy stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   That leads to talk about Allen's choices about what movies to
make and why he decided early on to take full artistic control,
after he wound up hating the first movie he wrote, ''What's New,
Pussycat?,'' from 1965. The movie became popular, and Allen found
himself having to say nice things about a movie he loathed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I vowed never to write another film if I couldn't direct it,''
he says, though he did do it once more, with ''Play It Again, Sam''
in 1972. ''It's better to have a film you love and people hate
rather than one you hate and people love. The ideal way is a movie
you love and they love, but that's hard to do. If you get that, you
hit the jackpot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitting the jackpot, with unexpected repercussions, is the idea
behind Allen's new movie. ''Small Time Crooks'' traces the rise and
fall of Ray and Frenchy Winkler (Allen and Ullman), low-class New
Yorkers who open a cookie store as a front to tunnel into the bank
two doors down.
</P>
<P>
   In an unforeseen manner, they strike it rich, but end up at odds
over Frenchy's Pygmalion-like desire to get some culture under the
tutelage of a suave Henry Higgins-type art dealer (Hugh Grant). Ray
just wants turkey meatballs and cheeseburgers for dinner after days
at the dog track.
</P>
<P>
   The part fit what Allen calls his limited acting range.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm really not an actor,'' Allen says at his hotel. ''There's
two things I'm believable as. Three things, actually. I'll get to
the third in a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm believable as an intellectual because I'm slight and I
wear big black-rimmed glasses and people think I'm an intellectual.
I'm not, but they think I am, and I can play that.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can also play a low-life, because that's much closer to me.
I really am the guy at home with the Beck's beer, the spaghetti,
the Knick game on or the baseball game on or the prize fight on.
That's really closer to who I am. So I can play Broadway Danny Rose
or this or the guy in 'Take the Money and Run.'
</P>
<P>
   ''The other thing is, I played an ant (DreamWorks' animated
''Antz'') and a sperm (Allen's ''Everything You Always Wanted to
Know About Sex But Were Afraid to Ask''). I can do creatures. But
in humans, I can do a low-life or an intellectual.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Small Time Crooks'' is partly an homage to Jackie Gleason's
''The Honeymooners'' -- ''one of the only things I find
authentically funny,'' Allen says. ''I truly find them hilarious,
and whenever the reruns are on television, no matter what late hour
it may be, I always manage to stay up and watch it and genuinely
laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kramden style, Allen and Ullman lovingly trade barbs and
threats, Ray raising his fist, barking at Frenchy to fix him
dinner, telling her, ''I'm going to slam your head off.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My parents, who are still alive, had that kind of relationship
my whole life,'' Allen says. ''It was a Ralph-and-Alice
relationship, where they were constantly battling but clearly loved
each other. ... They've stayed together and had a very good
marriage, though, you'd think, out of spite.''
</P>
<P>
   Ullman also appeared in Allen's ''Bullets Over Broadway'' and
worked on his musical, ''Everyone Says I Love You,'' though her
part was cut from that film.
</P>
<P>
   Allen has encountered new challenges casting female leads since
his breakup with longtime lover and co-star Mia Farrow. Their
relationship ended bitterly over Allen's affair with Farrow's
adopted daughter, Soon-Yi Previn, whom Allen then married.
</P>
<P>
   He reunited with Diane Keaton for ''Manhattan Murder Mystery,''
and has cast Goldie Hawn, Julia Roberts, Elisabeth Shue, and
regulars Judy Davis and Dianne Wiest in recent films.
</P>
<P>
   ''It opens you up, definitely, because I get a chance to work
with Elisabeth Shue or Julia Roberts and new people,'' Allen says.
''But you also have the problem of not working with someone you've
worked with before, and that's always a help to me. I can write
better for someone if I've worked with them. ...
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd love to do another piece with Diane Keaton because I think
there's some chemistry between us. I think we're funny together,
because I know her so well and I know how to get the most out of
her in a comic way.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen has backed away more and more from starring in his own
movies, partly because he felt he had better actors to take the
roles, partly because of his age, 64. He cast Kenneth Branagh as
the neurotic magazine writer in the dark ''Celebrity,'' the sort of
pathetic misfit of romance that Allen would have played himself 20
years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ''I couldn't do that part because I needed a 40-year-old, and
I'm a 60-year-old,'' Allen says. ''If a 60-year-old has those
problems, it's sort of tragic. If a 40-year-old has those problems,
he still has time to change his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen said he knew he lacked the acting chops for the fictional
guitarist in ''Sweet and Lowdown,'' so he cast Penn, who earned an
Oscar nomination for the role.
</P>
<P>
   ''I used to act in almost all my films. Now I do one out of
three or one out of two or something,'' Allen says. ''Jerry Lewis,
years ago, I asked him what the best thing was about not being in
your films when you're the director, and he said, 'You don't have
to shave.'
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew exactly what he meant. Those cold mornings when I have
to get up and shave and be out and be funny at 7 o'clock in the
morning on a freezing New York street. But when you're just the
director, you get up, take a shower, drive to work and look awful,
and the burden is on Kenneth Branagh or Sean Penn. They've got to
come in and make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   At UCLA, Allen is asked how he gets his cast to make things
happen, given his notoriously light directing touch and the fact
that he often gives actors only the pages of the script where their
characters appear.
</P>
<P>
   He says he lets actors play with the lines, improvise around
them, even throw them out completely and try something different.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very big on spontaneity,'' Allen says. ''I feel actors
should not know where they're going -- what they call in acting
school 'playing the results.' They should not know what they
wouldn't know in real life.''
</P>
<P>
   His evening on campus wraps up with blunt words on what young
filmmakers can expect in real life. ''Reality will winnow out the
ones who don't have it, and they will fall by the board
eventually,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Those that have the talent will find their way, Allen assures
them.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are not a lot of Martin Scorseses or Steven Spielbergs
or Francis Ford Coppolas walking around cursing the fact that they
are undiscovered,'' Allen says. ''You just have to give it a fair
shot and let reality take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   And this parting shot from Woody Allen:
</P>
<P>
   ''Reality eventually crushes you.''
</P>
<P>
   To a standing ovation, Allen quickly slips behind a red velvet
curtain, bound for his last college visit, at Harvard the following
night, then home to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet:
</P>
<P>
   ''Small Time Crooks'' site:
http://www.amazon.com/smalltimecrooks
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- From an interview with Woody Allen and his
session with a UCLA film audience:
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On why he never watches his previous movies:
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never seen any of them after I finish them. But only
because I wouldn't be able to take it. If I popped in and saw
'Bananas' today or 'Hannah and Her Sisters' or any of them, I would
just be sitting there saying, 'Oh, if I only had a little more
money I could have done that better, or look at that joke, it's not
holding up, I don't think it's very good. I could do this better
now.' And you can't do it over. ... It's just heartbreaking to look
at them.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On paying his actors on his low film budgets:
</P>
<P>
   ''We really pay a very low amount, shockingly low. Everybody
that works, whether it's Julia Roberts or Sean Penn or whoever it
is gets the same $5,000 a week. Whether they get $10 million on
another picture, they get $50,000 for our picture, and that's our
top.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On ''Small Time Crooks'' co-stars Tracey Ullman and Elaine May:
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't think of Tracey as I was writing it, but when I was
finished and I sat with Juliet Taylor, my casting person, she read
off a list of possibilities, and the second she read Tracey's name,
the two of us looked at each other and felt, who else could do it
but Tracey? She has that perfect edge to her, she can do those
accents perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whereas Elaine May I was thinking of as I was writing it. I
even named the character May in the movie because I've know Elaine
for years and find her brilliant. In this picture I was working
with two female comic geniuses, and I was intimidated because I've
known Elaine for 30 years and have always wanted to work with her,
but she was always elusive. You can call Elaine, and she's
brilliant but she'll say she can't work because she has to feed her
hamster or something. She's always got some strange reason why you
can't get her. And this one, I got her.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On early career prospects:
</P>
<P>
   ''I had toyed with going into a life of crime. It would not have
been brutal crime. First, I thought about going into law
enforcement, but they had height requirements. There's no height
requirement for criminals. I thought of maybe being a confidence
man or a bookmaker or trying clever burglary. Or a card cheat. I
saw myself on boats or cruises cheating people playing cards. Or a
safecracker.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On Samantha Morton, nominated for an Oscar for her role as a
mute waif in ''Sweet and Lowdown'':
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw her on a videocassette, and I said, 'My God, that face
should have been in silent movies.' She's got that kind of little
gamine's face. So I hired her immediately the minute I saw her.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On what's really important to his bank-robber character in
''Small Time Crooks,'' and to Allen himself:
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a guy who likes the turkey meatballs and the pinball
machines and just to hang out, and when he did get all that money,
thinking he needed a big score in his life, he didn't. He needed a
little bit of money so he could go to Florida and go to the dog
races and eat the stone crabs. ... It's the action he wants, the
work itself that is distracting in life sufficiently to be
therapeutic. It's the same thing with the film business. Making the
film is the fun. I've been on the end of films that were wildly
successful and very unsuccessful, and, you know, neither one means
that much. You go on to make your next film. Your life doesn't
change hugely when you make a big success, and it doesn't go down
the toilet if you have a failure. It's somewhere in between. If
you're having fun for the year it takes you to make the film, then
your life has some meaning to it. It's an enjoyable experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On speaking to film students at NYU, which kicked him out in the
1950s:
</P>
<P>
   ''It is ironic. They wanted to give me an honorary degree at
NYU, and many colleges in the country have asked me to make
commencement speeches and come there to get degrees. I've never
done any of that because I've never wanted to, not out of anything
other than that it seemed a nuisance and an empty ritual, to travel
to a school to get a degree. I have nothing to say at a
commencement speech, and those degrees don't mean anything to them
or me. I haven't earned a degree. I don't have any of the schooling
for it. It's a public-relations ritual for them, and some piece of
paper you take to your house and after a week it falls behind the
bookshelf and you never see it again, or you throw it out because
the maid says you're accumulating too much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
