<DOCNO> APW20000517.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian-African Author Returns Home  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN LINNEE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- When night descended on the house on Desai
Road, the small boy shivered as windows and doors were shut and
bolted to keep out the Mau Mau and the fear they incited across
colonial Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have this image,'' recalls author M.G. Vassanji. ''My father
was alive then. He had bought a gun, and my mother was really
scared. I was really young then, but I always had this memory, and
I wanted to cope with it in a literary fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I finally have the courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Vassanji, a nuclear physicist and author of ''The Gunny Sack''
and other novels and short stories, recently returned to the
country of his birth from his home in Toronto to research his
latest work set in Kenya in the mid-1950s during the Mau-Mau
uprising against British colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
   ''All I can say is that it is inspired by the fear that I had of
the climate here, because the Mau Mau was active. There is a strong
Mau Mau element in the sense that that's what I'm trying to explore
-- how the Asians felt and what they did.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1952 to the late 1950s, fear swept beautiful Kenya, the
East African colony thousands of British and European settlers had
decided to call home. Many had obtained land seized from the
Kikuyu, Kenya's largest tribe. Determined to get their land back
and drive out the foreigners, Kikuyu fighters took to the forests
and swore vengeance against all who opposed their Mau Mau crusade.
</P>
<P>
   Although the period was reported in the Western media as a time
of barbaric violence against whites, especially those living on
isolated farms, Kikuyus and other Africans who sided with the
colonial government bore the brunt of the Mau Mau wrath.
</P>
<P>
   Records show that 32 European civilians, 26 Asians and 1,819
''loyal Africans'' were killed in what became known as ''The
Emergency.'' A report for the British colonial government said
11,503 ''terrorists'' were killed and another 26,625 arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The rebellion was stamped out by British troops and African
soldiers. Thousands of Kikuyus were uprooted and placed in
detention camps for years.
</P>
<P>
   ''How do you build? There's an image or an incident. Here, it's
just this fear we had on Desai Road at night when we closed the
doors, the windows, the curtains, and then you were really scared
of the darkness outside and what may come from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Vassanji, 50, is an Ismali Muslim whose ancestors came to East
Africa from the Gujarat region in northwestern India at the end of
the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants from the Indian subcontinent originally numbered tens
of thousands in what are now Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania. During the
colonial era, they were not first-class citizens, but they were
considerably better off than native Africans. Middle managers and
junior colonial civil servants, artisans and traders, some built up
large mercantile empires. They are known collectively as Asians,
and their relationship with their African homelands has often been
ambiguous and tense.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, at a time when more black Africans -- particularly
the Kikuyu -- were getting access to education in schools run by
missionaries, resentment against the Asians, who dominated trade
and the middle levels of the colonial civil service, was on the
rise.
</P>
<P>
   After independence in 1963, many Asian businesses were taken
over by Africans. In neighboring Uganda, at least 70,000 Asians
were forced to leave all together.
</P>
<P>
   Vassanji's family moved to Dar es Salaam in neighboring Tanzania
at the end of the Mau Mau period. He won an undergraduate
scholarship to study physics at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology in 1970 and obtained his doctorate from the University
of Pennsylvania in 1978. He says he only became aware of his
Asian-Indian heritage while studying in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ''So, I discovered India for myself and started reading
philosophy and Gandhi in the original. ... These things were
meaningless to me when I was growing up. We had disregarded it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was while living in Toronto where he had obtained a job
teaching nuclear physics that Vassanji began to encounter his East
African past. His wife, Nur Jehan, is also from Dar es Salaam, but
they only met in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''I started reading about my history in East Africa. ... I found
references to Indians. ... Not very pleasant, but still.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Vassanji -- Moyez to his friends -- returned to Dar es
Salaam for the first time in two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was such an experience. I landed at night. Early in the
morning I got out and started walking, and I walked all day. ... I
have never met an Asian, especially from our Ismali community,
especially from my generation, who talks of Dar es Salaam without
fondness. ... There's such a warmth to that memory. It was the best
years of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   On his return to Toronto, Vassanji, ''burdened by this sense of
the past and not knowing what to do with it,'' began putting the
pieces together and wrote ''The Gunny Sack,'' the saga of an
Asian-African family in East Africa told through the contents of a
magic gunny sack. It was his first attempt at fiction, and the
prestigious -- if not well-endowed -- African Writers Series of the
British firm Heineman published the work the same year. The book
went on to win the Commonwealth Prize for a first work of fiction
by an African author.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a kind of vindication to be published by the African
Writers Series as an Asian,'' Vassanji says. ''It was the only
place I sent the manuscript; they were the only people who would
know where Dar es Salaam was.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Uhuru Street,'' a book of short stories, and ''No New Land,''
followed. In 1994, he published ''The Book of Secrets'' another
engrossing account of Asians in East Africa based on a diary kept
by a junior British colonial administrator. It's a novel that cries
out to be made into a film, but the director, Vassanji says, would
have to be someone ''who understands India and Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Vassanji, who never studied writing, writes like he talks, in a
simple, straightforward way, pausing to highlight seemingly small
details that will illuminate his narrative. He has captured the
rhythm of those who speak in Kiswahili, in Gujarati and in English
and sometimes in all three together, both stilted and lilting, and
full of memory.
</P>
<P>
   The prologue to ''The Book of Secrets,'' published in the United
States by St. Martin's Press:
</P>
<P>
   ''They call it the book of our secrets, kitabu cha siri zetu. Of
its writer they said: He steals our souls and locks them away; it
is a magic bottle, this book, full of captured spirits; see how he
keeps his eyes skinned, this mzungu, observing everything we do.
... Because it has no end, this book, it ingests us and carries us
with it, and so it grows.''
</P>
<P>
   Vassanji and his wife started the Toronto South Asian Review
''as an Asian thing'' about 10 years ago; she now runs the
publishing side of the family, TSAR publications, as well as the
magazine, now known simply as the Toronto Review.
</P>
<P>
   His most recent book, ''Amrika,'' is a collection of vignettes
published last year in Canada by McLellan and Stewart, about Asian
East Africans in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher will probably also handle the new book, as
yet untitled. Vassanji says he wants to set it somewhere outside
Nairobi, perhaps in Nakuru on the edge of the Great Rift Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The chance discovery of a book written by an English woman who
lived during the Mau Mau period -- ''Letters to Nellie'' by Elspeth
Huxley -- has put his collective memories in motion.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just flipped through it ... it tells you how whites felt ...
things began to fall into place. For me, it was a matter of looking
at the ground, the trees ... and also trying to find out where to
take the novel from there,'' said the lapsed physicist who still
likes to solve problems. ''It will take a couple of years at least.
I want to move it into something that's of significance to me
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1205 </TRAILER>
