<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghent Goes 'Over the Edges' for Art  </HEADLINE>
By CONSTANT BRAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   GHENT, Belgium (AP) -- Ham-covered pillars rotting at the
university law faculty? A giant pink statue of a nude Cyclops
overlooking the city's most famous bridge? A naked bather suspended
over a busy intersection?
</P>
<P>
   It seems this ancient city has gone mad for art.
</P>
<P>
   ''Over the Edges'' touches all the human senses, and is an
exhibition so different, yet so simple. The city known for its
gothic churches, medieval squares and excellent cuisine is taking
art where few shows have gone before.
</P>
<P>
   April Fool's Day marked the beginning of a contemporary art
exhibition that mixes the bizarrely modern with the old and
traditional, the absurd with the routine. The show runs through
June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Curators Jan Hoet and Giacinto Di Pietrantonio are the
masterminds behind the ''Over the Edges'' show, which has brought
modern art to the old historical medieval heart of Ghent, putting
it on the crest of an arts wave the like of which the city has
never seen.
</P>
<P>
   Showcasing some 55 internationally renowned artists over the
entire area of the old city, the exhibition is meant to express the
link between the old and the new.
</P>
<P>
   It is part of the Ghent's celebration marking the 500th birth
year of its most famous native son: Emperor Charles V. The
16th-century Holy Roman Emperor ruled a huge empire that went from
the Netherlands to Sicily, included much of Germany and Spain, and
parts of Central and South America.
</P>
<P>
   ''We asked artists to create works for outside: for corners, for
crossroads, for the edge of the street,'' Di Pietrantonio said.
</P>
<P>
   The show's most controversial and most visited art piece is
Belgian artist Jan Fabre's ''fleshy tapestry'' of smoked ham
covering the eight, two-story-high pillars in the university's
neoclassical facade.
</P>
<P>
   Antipoverty groups argue the piece is not art but a bad-taste
waste of essential food, which should have been used to feed the
homeless. Animal-rights activists complain the pigs were needlessly
slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
   The City Council decided not to meddle in the show, but has
warned that if the state of the ham gets too bad, health officials
will step in.
</P>
<P>
   The notoriety of the show's center piece means a 24-hour,
round-the-clock police guard has been put on to protect the 8,000
slices of ham from vandals. Student volunteers have also been
posted at the ham pillars to protect them from intruding dogs and
cats hoping for a nibble at the now rotting and stinky art decor.
</P>
<P>
   Fabre told the local De Morgen newspaper the work will really be
at its best when it starts to attract swarms of flies, and when
worms emerge from the rank flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Some art experts have called the ham pillars questionable,
siding with critics who said it has gone too far, calling the work
''immoral'' and that it only promotes ''capitalist decadence.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There are more decadent things in a museum, perhaps,'' said
Han Van den Hoof, Ghent art student on a five-hour watch. ''People
say it's a waste of money, but I like the aesthetic quality of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire show is a treasure hunt through the narrow streets of
Ghent.
</P>
<P>
   If you listen carefully, you will hear the familiar yet
displaced cry of Tarzan echoing from atop the city's spires. Close
to one of the city's canals, plates fly out of a window, seemingly
the bizarre result of a couple's quarrel inside. In reality, it is
another exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   An aquarium on one of the city's busy intersections is filled
with gold fish and also had a naked woman in it during the opening
weekend. The ''sky bath'' caused mayhem for traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say it takes more than a day to see all the sites,
which includes the SMAK contemporary art museum. Art critics have
given the show much acclaim, lauding its uniqueness and calling it
progressive.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's fantastic,'' said visiting Hilde Jansenns. ''It brings
the art to the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were simply bemused. ''What is it all about?'' asked a
tourist from Uruguay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1205 </TRAILER>
