<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Entertainment highlights during the week of May
21-27:
<TEXT>
<P>
   45 years ago: ''Love Me or Leave Me,'' starring Doris Day and
James Cagney, opened at Radio City Music Hall in New York City. The
score included Day's hit ''I'll Never Stop Loving You.''
</P>
<P>
   30 years ago: The Beatles' ''Let It Be'' album, released with a
picture book in a cardboard box, topped the British chart. The New
Musical Express called it a ''cardboard tombstone.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Woodstock,'' the documentary about the 1969 rock festival in
Bethel, N.Y., premiered at a New York City theater.
</P>
<P>
   And the Grateful Dead played its first British concert at the
Hollywood Rock Music Festival in Newcastle-under-Lyme. Steppenwolf
and Mungo Jerry also performed.
</P>
<P>
   20 years ago: ''The Empire Strikes Back,'' the sequel to ''Star
Wars,'' opened in theaters nationwide. The film starred Harrison
Ford, Mark Hamill and Carrie Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   And Stanley Kubrick's ''The Shining,'' starring Jack Nicholson
and Shelley Duvall, opened in selected theaters in New York and Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   15 years ago: Cher won for ''Mask,'' William Hurt won for ''Kiss
of the Spider Woman'' and Jimmy Stewart got a prize for his life's
work at the 38th Cannes Film Festival in France. But the Golden
Palm -- the festival's top award -- went to Yugoslav director Emir
Kusturica for ''Papa Is on a Business Trip.''
</P>
<P>
   John Lithgow and Rosemary Harris won best actor and actress
honors at the Drama Desk Awards in New York City. Songwriter Roger
Miller won for his score and lyrics for the Huckleberry Finn
musical ''Big River.'' Lithgow portrayed an over-the-hill fighter
in ''Requiem for a Heavyweight.'' Harris won for ''Pack of Lies.''
</P>
<P>
   The premiere of the James Bond thriller ''A View to a Kill''
gave screaming fans a thrilling view of Roger Moore, Grace Jones,
Tanya Roberts and two members of the rock band Duran Duran. About a
third of the movie was shot in San Francisco, where the premiere
was held.
</P>
<P>
   And Sylvester Stallone's ''Rambo: First Blood Part II'' opened
in theaters throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   10 years ago: The top five positions on the U.S. singles chart
were held by female artists. Madonna was No. 1 with ''Vogue,''
followed by Heart with ''All I Wanna Do Is Make Love to You,''
Sinead O'Connor with ''Nothing Compares 2 U,'' Wilson Phillips with
''Hold On,'' and Janet Jackson with ''Alright.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago: The Recording Industry Association of America
said Bruce Springsteen's ''Born in the U.S.A.'' album had sold 15
million copies to become the third best-selling album ever. The
1984 release was surpassed only by Michael Jackson's ''Thriller''
at 24 million copies and Fleetwood Mac's ''Rumours'' at 17 million.
Springsteen's album was tied at third place with Boston's
''Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   And Terry Hatcher was Superpopular on the Internet. A picture of
the Lois Lane actress in a Superman cape and nothing else was
downloaded more than 20,000 times in six months, according to
Entertainment Weekly. ''It's a great shot,'' the co-star of the ABC
series ''Lois &AMP; Clark'' told the magazine. ''Not so much because
it's me. It's just cool-looking.''
</P>
<P>
   One year ago: The last episode of the popular TV sitcom ''Home
Improvement'' drew an estimated 35 million viewers, making it the
fourth most-viewed series finale of the 1990s. The ABC show, which
starred comedian Tim Allen, was on the air for eight years. Only
''Seinfeld,'' ''Cheers'' and ''The Cosby Show'' drew more viewers
during their series finales.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Susan Lucci won a Daytime Emmy for best actress after
losing for 18 consecutive years. She was honored for her portrayal
of Erica Kane on ABC's ''All My Children.''
</P>
<P>
   And Julian Lennon announced that ''Photograph Smile,'' his first
album in seven years, was dedicated to his late stepfather Roberto
Bassanini. Lennon told USA Weekend magazine: ''He was the one who
took me to school every day. He was the guy.'' As for John Lennon,
his biological father, he had this comment: ''The only thing he
taught me was how not to be a father.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken 10 years ago:
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no more to say about the character, which is my alter
ego, I can't deny that.'' -- Sylvester Stallone, announcing that
''Rocky V'' would be the last in the series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
