<HEADLINE> Wet Outlook Dampens Grain, Soybeans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices fell in early
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
</P>
<P>
   The retreat was led by soybean futures, which were weakened by
followthrough selling from Tuesday's technical slide. Forecasts of
significant rainfall for a large portion of the Midwest helped push
prices lower.
</P>
<P>
   A decline in soymeal futures prices also weighed on the soybean
market.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains expected today and Thursday also pressured corn
futures prices. The precipitation is expected to create
near-perfect crop-growing conditions in a region that has been
plagued by dryness.
</P>
<P>
   Weather concerns pushed aside news South Korea purchased 135,000
metric tons of U.S. corn. There also were reports Taiwan may be in
the market for corn.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness of corn and soybeans helped push wheat futures
prices lower.
</P>
<P>
   In early trading, wheat for July delivery was 1\ cents lower at
$2.80 a bushel; July corn was 1} cents lower at $2.33} a bushel;
July oats were } cent lower at $1.18\ a bushel; July soybeans were
4\ cents lower at $5.39{ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle and pork futures prices were higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle were .33 cent higher at 68.45 cents a pound;
August feeder cattle were .48 cent higher at 84.30 cents a pound;
June lean hogs were .80 cent higher at 71.70 cents a pound; July
pork bellies were 1.65 cents higher at 88.75 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
