<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Johnny Mathis Puts Audience At Ease  </HEADLINE>
By MARY CAMPBELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- When Johnny Mathis opens a concert, he sings his
most popular songs right away so his audience can relax. He
realized years ago that listeners get anxious, wondering whether he
will sing the hits.
</P>
<P>
   Being at ease -- and having his audience at ease -- is a priority
for Mathis, whose '50s hits include ''It's Not for Me to Say'' and
''Chances Are.'' Many of his fans can recall a romance that was
sweetened by one of his songs playing in the background.
</P>
<P>
   ''Music is really about memories,'' said Mathis, 64. ''At this
point in my life, there are very few surprises I can give to
people. They know what I'm going to sing. They've heard me sing.
The only thing I have to worry about is keeping my voice in
condition so I'll be able to sing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis always sings the songs that he is most comfortable with.
And he usually performs with a 26-piece orchestra -- with piano,
guitar, oboe, French horn and strings -- because that's the sound
listeners know from his recordings.
</P>
<P>
   When someone yells out a request from the audience and the
orchestra doesn't have an arrangement, Mathis may sing it anyway,
without accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   ''I remember almost everything. Or I remember enough of the song
to sing a little bit of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mathis has sold millions of records, he hasn't based
his career on how well his albums sell. ''If you're lucky, you have
one hit record and everybody finds out who you are. If you're
really lucky, you have a few hits.
</P>
<P>
   ''But you really need to get out and form a relationship with
audiences. It requires vigilance and nothing but hard work and
dedication. I always knew that. I always knew I wanted to sing all
my life and what it was going to take.''
</P>
<P>
   His new CD ''Mathis on Broadway'' (Columbia) features hit songs
from recent Broadway shows, including Stephen Sondheim's ballad
''Loving You'' from ''Passion''; and a combination of ''Children
Will Listen'' (from ''Into the Woods'') and ''Our Children'' (from
''Ragtime''), sung with Betty Buckley.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've made over 100 albums; I don't know exactly how many,''
Mathis said. ''For the first 15 years or so, I made four albums a
year. They had the orchestra in the studio. I'd do four songs a day
in three hours. It took three days to do a record. Now I sing and
sing and sing and they say, 'Would you do it again?' I swear I
can't hear the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis was an outstanding track and field athlete at San
Francisco State College and was invited to try out for the 1956
U.S. Olympic team. But a jazz executive at Columbia Records heard
Mathis sing and signed him. His first recording, which was jazz,
didn't sell well. But Mitch Miller, a pop music executive at the
company, believed Mathis could be a smooth singer of soft, romantic
ballads and chose songs that brought him success.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's Not for Me to Say,'' ''Wonderful, Wonderful'' and
''Chances Are'' were hits in 1957. ''Misty'' followed two years
later. In 1958, only two years after signing him, Columbia Records
released ''Johnny's Greatest Hits,'' which was on Billboard's top
albums chart for nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   He quit smoking in his 20s, stopped drinking alcohol 10 years
ago, and tries to eat healthful foods. He does most of his own
cooking, a skill he learned from his parents, who were domestic
workers in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a very domesticated person,'' said Mathis, who has lived
in the same house for 40 years. He bought it when he was doing a
lot of recording in Los Angeles. ''I love being home. I go to the
golf course and market and home. That's where I'm happiest.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also enjoys performing and trying new venues. He still
sings in Las Vegas and in Atlantic City, N.J., and with symphony
orchestras. A few years ago, he started singing on stages in
vineyards, in casinos operated by Indian tribes and in refurbished
movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's kind of a nice time for me. People know my music and what
to expect. I'm able to sing more or less whatever I want to,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   An avid golfer, Mathis participates in golf-related charities.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes I travel to Great Britain just to play golf for a
week or two,'' he said. ''I found out I should take the time to
enjoy my life a little bit. If not now, when? It gives me more
incentive to come back to the music, if I get away from it a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The official Johnny Mathis Web site is:
http://www.johnnymathis.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
