<DOCNO> APW20000517.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals court orders new trial in Colonial case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A federal appeals court has ordered a new
trial for an accountant acquitted two years ago by a federal judge
of wire and mail fraud charges in the Colonial Real Estate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves former Arthur Andersen accountant Edmund M.
Autuori who had been convicted of 16 fraud counts on March 12,
1998. The jury found that he had conspired with Colonial, in 1989
and 1990 to hide damaging information about a Colonial syndication
deal from investors.
</P>
<P>
   Colonial's $2 billion real estate empire collapsed in 1990,
costing over 6,000 investors more than $300 million.
</P>
<P>
   Senior U.S. District Judge Ellen Bree Burns, who had presided
over Autuori's 18-day trial, threw out the jury's verdict five
months later, saying the convictions were based on ''a morass of
conflicting testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns wrote that she felt compelled to overrule a jury for only
the second time in her 20-year judicial career, to prevent a
''manifest injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2nd Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals Tuesday reversed Burns'
acquittal of Autuori on a dozen charges, while affirming his
acquittal by the judge on four other counts.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge appellate panel refused to reinstate the guilty
verdicts. Instead, it ordered a new trial on the dozen charges.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court did agree with Burns that were ''serious
contradictions and conflicts in the government's evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it said that the standard for reversing a jury is high.
A trial judge is not entitled to set aside a verdict simply because
he or she would have reached a different verdict, the appeals court
said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Peter A. Clark said the government would
review the decision before deciding on a course of action.
</P>
<P>
   William M. Bloss, one of Autuori's lawyers, said he hoped the
government would end the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ''There should be no doubt now that four federal judges, the
three appeals judges and Judge Burns, viewed this as a remarkably
weak case,'' Bloss said Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
