<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Bill Advances in Congress  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After months of debate, legislation
normalizing trade relations with China advanced in Congress on
Wednesday, gaining the near-unanimous endorsement of the Senate
Finance Committee and moving toward expected approval by a
counterpart House panel.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which would end 20 years of annual congressional votes
on China's trade status, has the strong support of the Clinton
administration and business groups but is opposed by organized
labor and some human rights groups, particularly in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Still, its approval by the House Ways and Means Committee later
Wednesday was expected by supporters and opponents alike. The full
House will take up the bill next week.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would grant China ''permanent normal trade relations,''
the same low-tariff access to U.S. markets that nearly every other
nation in the world already enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   It would also ease China's entry into the World Trade
Organization, the Geneva-based organization that oversees world
trade. China was a founding member of the WTO's predecessor, the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, but it withdrew after the
1949 communist takeover in China.
</P>
<P>
   The United States normalized diplomatic relations with China in
1979, but has kept the restrictions on trade.
</P>
<P>
   To make the measure more palatable to labor unions and human
rights groups, the House was expected to include side legislation
to set up a commission to monitor human rights and a mechanism to
protect U.S. businesses from surges in low-cost Chinese products.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Finance Committee went first, voting 18-1 to approve
the China trade bill and to ready it for a vote by the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Committee Chairman William Roth, R-Del., called it ''a
defining moment in our relationship with China.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., a member of the
committee, said he hoped the bill would be ''approved
overwhelmingly'' by the Senate. ''It's not a totally easy vote ...
but I think you've got to look at the benefits for this country ...
and within China itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters assert the legislation will open China's vast markets
to U.S. businesses and help bring the nation of 1.2 billion people
-- the world's most populous -- into the world community. Labor
opposes it, criticizing China's human rights and worker protection
policies and suggesting the measure could cost American
manufacturing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The sole Senate vote against the bill was cast by Sen. Jim
Jeffords, R-Vt. And he said he was doing so primarily to protest
the continued imprisonment in China of a Tibetan musicologist,
Ngawang Choepel, who had attended a Vermont college.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffords said he was being held unjustly, even under Chinese
law, and that China had banned his mother from visiting her son in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''If China cannot obey its own laws in this case, how can we
expect it to follow the far more burdensome rules of the World
Trade Organization?'' asked Jeffords.
</P>
<P>
   Before the House Ways and Means panel took up the measure, Rep.
Sander Levin of Michigan, the senior Democrat on the panel, and
Rep. Doug Bereuter, R-Neb., reached agreement with Chairman Bill
Archer, R-Texas, and other lawmakers on language to be included
that would provide protections for American industries against a
sudden surge in imports from China.
</P>
<P>
   Levin and Bereuter are also pushing for creation of a human
rights commission that would issue annual reports on China's
performance to take the place of the annual congressional vote. But
House aides said that final agreement on the language for that
proposal would probably not come until the House Rules Committee
takes up the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Their legislation is being sponsored in the Senate by Sens. Max
Baucus, D-Mont., and Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the wide margin in the Senate panel, several Finance
Committee members expressed skepticism over whether normalizing
economic ties would bring about improvements in China's
human-rights record.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those who say change will come quickly may be misjudging 5,000
years of Chinese history,'' said Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rockefeller and other proponents of the bill said they
were persuaded that it would help open Chinese markets to U.S.
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The China trade bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House working group on China:
http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO campaign to stop China trade bill:
http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1329 </TRAILER>
