<HEADLINE> New Programs on CBS and PAX  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Thumbnail sketches of new programs to debut on CBS
this fall:
<TEXT>
<P>
   --''The Bette Show,'' stars Bette Midler in a comedy in which she
plays a character remarkably similar to Bette Midler.
</P>
<P>
   --''Welcome to New York,'' is a comedy about an Indiana
weatherman who tries to hold his own when he gets a job at a New
York television show. The show loosely parallels David Letterman's
life, and comes from his production company. CBS is thinking about
changing the title to make it more palatable to non-New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   --''Yes, Dear,'' is a comedy about two young couples with
outrageously different views on parenting. It stars Mike O'Malley,
whose NBC sitcom bearing his name failed quickly last year.
</P>
<P>
   --''The Fugitive,'' updates the classic 1960s action series,
starring Tim Daly as the man wrongfully accused of killing his
wife, who hunts for the real murderer.
</P>
<P>
   --''C.S.I.,'' is a drama about a team of forensic investigators
solving crimes in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   --''That's Life,'' is a drama about a New Jersey woman in her 30s
who decides to dump her blue-collar fiance and return to college.
</P>
<P>
   --''The District,'' stars Craig T. Nelson, formerly of ''Coach,''
in a drama about a newly-hired police commissioner who tries to
shake up Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbnail sketches of new programs to debut on PAX TV this fall:
</P>
<P>
   --''Mysterious Ways,'' is a drama about a professor who is
fascinated with unexplained phenomenon. Rae Dawn Chong stars as a
skeptical psychiatrist who works as his partner.
</P>
<P>
   --''The Rumfords,'' is a comedy about a family of cartoon
characters that moves into a suburb and live among live-action
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   --''Encounters With the Unexplained,'' is a reality series that
attempts to answer the questions: How did we get here? Where did we
come from? Are we alone in the universe?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
