<DOCNO> APW20000517.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former 'Millionaire' contestant accused of embezzling $190,000  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- A publisher was as surprised as anyone
Wednesday to learn the author of a book offering tips to get on the
popular television game show ''Who Wants to be a Millionaire'' is
accused of embezzling nearly $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first we heard of this was yesterday so it's been less
than a day and we are trying to understand a little bit more about
the situation,'' said Peter Kaufman, publisher of TV Books.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman said it was premature to say what impact the revelation
might have on the upcoming release of ''Who Wants to be a
Contestant,'' a book by Paul Barbour of Baldwinsville, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour and his two brothers, Mark and Mike, were the first
three siblings in the country to appear on the popular game show.
On Wednesday, the brothers appeared on ''The Rosie O'Donnell Show''
to talk about their appearances on the game show. Other national
outlets, including ''Extra'' and ''Inside Edition,'' have told
their story.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Barbour also has attracted other interest.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury in July accused Barbour and Kellie Moran of
defrauding Nationwide Insurance Co. out of more than $190,000 by
authorizing dozens of payments to a phony medical services company
between April 6, 1998, and Dec. 4, 1998, the Syracuse newspapers
reported.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury indicted them on charges of scheming to defraud
Nationwide, mail fraud and money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour, 38, who worked as an in-house attorney, was accused of
authorizing 145 checks from Nationwide to Medical Evaluation
Services of Central New York as payment for medical evaluations
performed on Nationwide clients, then spending that money on
personal expenses of his and Moran's.
</P>
<P>
   Moran, 40, a registered nurse from Liverpool, N.Y., performed
only one medical evaluation in those cases, the indictment said.
The indictment said Moran set up the company as part of the scheme
to defraud Nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just a good guy who didn't do anything wrong who's really
getting screwed here. I'm trying to vigorously defend the
charges,'' Barbour told the Syracuse Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Having successfully advised his brothers on how to get on the
show, Paul decided to write a book with tips on how to qualify as a
contestant. The 200-page book is scheduled to be distributed by
HarperCollins, said Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour said he disclosed the charges to his publisher. Kaufman
said that was not true. He was waiting Wednesday to talk to Barbour
who appeared on the show Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Paul didn't make it past the preliminary ''fastest-finger
round,'' the prelude to sitting in the hot seat answering trivia
questions from host Regis Philbin. Neither did brother Mark, who
appeared on the show March 30. The third brother, Mike, finally
made the show that aired last Wednesday night. He also failed to
make it to the hot seat.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's part of the story of the book that I've
been wrongfully accused of something,'' Paul Barbour told the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour plans to go to trial to fight the charges. He is
scheduled to appear in court June 2. If convicted, he could face up
to 20 years in prison and a $500,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Andrew Baxter declined to comment on the
case except to confirm that charges are pending against Barbour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
