<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 3:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Wednesday, May 17, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Incomes Rise Faster Than Inflation
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Incomes grew faster than inflation in every
state last year, with residents of Wyoming enjoying the fastest
growth, the government reported today. ''Basically, it's entirely a
function of this exorbitant job growth we've seen,'' said economist
Richard Yamarone of Argus Research Corp. Nationally, average income
for America's 272.7 million people last year was $28,518, up 4.8
percent from 1998, the Commerce Department said. The figures
include not only wages and salaries but also other sources of
income, such as investment earnings and government benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Dow Drops 162; Nasdaq Off 67
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- With many economists predicting more interest
rate hikes later this year, investors lost their nerve that fueled
Wall Street's recent rally. ''It is the accumulation of rate hikes
that truly hampers stock market performance over time,'' said Gail
Dudack, chief equity strategist at UBS Warburg in New York. ''We do
expect lower (stock prices) in May and June to materialize before a
better and more sustainable summer rally can begin.'' Just before 3
p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were down 162.77 at 10,771.80. On the
NYSE, decliners led advancers 1,925-914. The Nasdaq was down 67.46
at 3,650.11.
</P>
