<P>
   Time Warner, NBC Sign Coverage Deal
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Time Warner Inc.'s cable division, fresh from a
nasty fight with ABC, has signed an agreement with NBC to carry the
network's main feed as well as cable channels CNBC and MSNBC
through 2008. The deal includes coverage of the Olympic Games,
which NBC has exclusive U.S. broadcast rights through 2008. NBC
also plans to offer extended coverage of the Olympics on its cable
channels beginning with the Sydney Olympics this fall. Time Warner
Cable spokesman Michael Luftman said NBC asked for, and received,
extra compensation for its Olympics coverage, but he declined to
say how much Time Warner was paying NBC overall.
</P>
<P>
   Terra, Lycos Merging in $12.5B Deal
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Lycos Inc. stock was down 13 15/16 at 58 11/16
this afternoon on news that Terra Networks, the leading Internet
service provider in the Spanish-speaking world, is buying it. It's
the first time a major U.S. Web portal has been bought by a foreign
company. The widely expected acquisition by Terra was announced
yesterday. The Spanish company is paying $12.5 billion in stock for
its beachhead in the United States, where it likely hopes to
attract Hispanic subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Gov't Filing Rebuttal to Microsoft Plan
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government is defending its proposed
breakup of Microsoft in what essentially will be the last official
word before a federal judge holds a hearing on what remedies to
impose on the company's business practices. The Justice Department
and 17 states were filing a rebuttal this afternoon to Microsoft's
request to dismiss a plan that would split the company into two
businesses. The spinoff plan was proposed as a remedy to behavior
found to be anticompetitive -- and illegal -- by U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson. In addition to asking that the proposal be
dismissed, Microsoft last week offered to impose several
restrictions on itself instead.
</P>
<P>
   Philippines Seek 'Love Bug' Law
</P>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- A senior Department of Justice
official has ruled that a law investigators hoped to use against
suspects in the ''Love Bug'' computer virus case does not apply to
computer crimes. The decision severely handicaps the investigators,
who have struggled to find a legal basis on which to charge any
suspects. The Philippines has no laws specifically addressing
high-tech computer crimes such as the ''ILOVEYOU'' virus, which
earlier this month crippled e-mail systems worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Amway To Cut 1,300 Jobs
</P>
<P>
   ADA, Mich. (AP) -- Direct-sales giant Amway Corp. said today it
plans to cut nearly 11 percent of its global work force, or 1,300
jobs, as part of a restructuring expected to save $300 million a
year. The announcement was expected. Amway announced in February
that it was reorganizing in response to sluggish sales and the
changing business environment, and cuts were likely. About 900 jobs
will be cut at the company's world headquarters in Ada, 260
overseas, and the remainder in Amway's California operations in
Buena Park and Lakeview. Management and salaried positions will be
most affected, according to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Bankrupt AmeriServe Sues Ex-CEO
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Troubled restaurant supplier AmeriServe Food
Distribution Inc. has filed a lawsuit against its founder and
former chief executive, claiming he improperly pulled tens of
millions of dollars out of the company before it filed for
bankruptcy in January. AmeriServe charged that John Holten
wrongfully diverted funds from the company into other companies
under his control under the guise of expense reimbursements,
management fees and other transactions. In its lawsuit filed late
yesterday in Wilmington, Del., the company asked for the return of
the money and unspecified punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Jury Finds Bear Stearns Negligent
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bear Stearns Cos. was ordered to pay $111.5
million to a Canadian investor after a federal jury in Manhattan
found it acted negligently when it made unauthorized trades in his
account. Henryk de Kwiatkowski, the 76-year-old owner of a Kentucky
thoroughbred-horse-breeding farm who now lives in the Bahamas, had
claimed in a lawsuit that Bear Stearns Cos. cost him $300 million.
The jury in U.S. District Court concluded yesterday that a broker
at Bear Stearns had not acted negligently, and that the company had
not breached its fiduciary duty but did act negligently and owed de
Kwiatkowski $111.5 million. It was one of the largest jury awards
ever handed a Wall Street firm accused of wronging an individual
investor.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Bancorp CFO Steps Down
</P>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- One of the highest-ranking women bankers in
the nation is stepping down as chief financial officer of U.S.
Bancorp. Susan Lester, 43, said that she made her decision to leave
the bank last year. She will be replaced by Andrew Cecere, 39.
Lester, CFO since 1996 and executive vice president of finance
since 1995, will stay with the bank for a couple of months to
assist Cecere's transition into the job. Lester said she was most
proud of her work on acquisitions, which helped the once-ailing
First Bank System become U.S. Bancorp, the nation's 11th-largest
bank spanning 16 states with $83 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel Hires Kraft Exec As New CEO
</P>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) -- The former chief of Kraft Foods today
was named the new chairman and CEO of Mattel Inc., the troubled toy
manufacturer that has been plagued with sagging sales and profits.
Robert A. Eckert will immediately take over the helm at the world's
largest toy maker. He replaces Jill Barad, who resigned in February
after more than a year of declining share prices and disappointing
earnings reports. ''This is one of the best consumer goods
companies on the planet. There are some wonderful assets on which
to build,'' Eckert said in a telephone interview. Mattel stock was
up 1 1/16 at 12 5/16.
</P>
