<HEADLINE> Judge: Wynette Files Off Limits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Medical and financial information about
late country music legend Tammy Wynette will stay off limits to the
public -- and her four daughters -- even after her widower hands it
over to a federal court, a judge said.
</P>
<P>
   Wynette's widower George Richey has to provide the materials as
part of a wrongful death lawsuit over the singer's death in April
1998. An autopsy showed her death was caused by repeated blood
clots that led to heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   Wynette's daughters have sued Dr. Wallis Marsh and Care
Solutions of Nashville Inc. Marsh is a Pittsburgh physician who
treated Wynette for six years before her death. Care Solutions is
the pharmacy that filled some of Marsh's prescriptions. The lawsuit
alleges that Marsh prescribed too many painkillers.
</P>
<P>
   Richey asked that the information be sealed. He said one of
Wynette's daughters has admitted selling information to a tabloid
and cannot be trusted with the requested data.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate Juliet Griffin issued a protective order Tuesday
and directed that the documents be returned to Richey or destroyed
when the lawsuit is concluded. Trial is set for October 2001.
</P>
