<DOCNO> APW20000517.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 166; Nasdaq Down 70  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks stumbled today as investors took profits
from the market's recent rally and determined that the interest
rate increase implemented by the Federal Reserve on Tuesday may
indeed threaten stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow
Jones industrial average was down 166.03 at 10,768.54.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index was down 19.33 at 1,446.71, and the Nasdaq composite
index was down 70.28 at 3,647.29.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness on Wall Street didn't surprise analysts, who
believed stocks were due to falter as investors tried to capture
gains from a four-day rally. The market's gains were capped Tuesday
when the Fed, as expected, raised interest rates a half-percentage
point -- its steepest increase in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates are generally bad for stocks, raising
borrowing costs and cutting into bottom-line profits. Investors had
bid stocks higher on the hope that Tuesday's increase could be the
last for a while, but with many economists predicting still higher
rates later this year, many investors lost their nerve today,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the accumulation of rate hikes that truly hampers stock
market performance over time,'' said Gail Dudack, chief equity
strategist at UBS Warburg in New York. ''We do expect lower (stock
prices) in May and June to materialize before a better and more
sustainable summer rally can begin.''
</P>
<P>
   Dudack pointed out that in the 11 volatile months since the Fed
began raising rates, the Dow has declined modestly. The Nasdaq is
up about 35 percent since June 1999, but has tumbled dramatically
from its all-time high of 5,048.62, set March 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow's performance, Dudack said, is more typical during a
time of escalating rates, and the Nasdaq's recent slump may be
bringing it in line with historical measures.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard, the top-performing Dow component on Tuesday,
plunged 8~ to 131[. After the close of trading Tuesday, the company
reported second-quarter earnings that topped Wall Street analysts'
expectations. But testy investors may have been expecting
Hewlett-Packard to more dramatically exceed published estimates,
analysts said. Others suggested that the company may be growing
dependent on lower margin areas such as personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Agilent, the testing and measuring equipment maker that was spun
off from Hewlett-Packard, fell 16| to 79].
</P>
<P>
   Consumer goods stocks were also lower today. Johnson &AMP; Johnson
fell 7/16 to 86~ and Procter &AMP; Gamble fell 5/16 to 64}.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T fell 1| to 37\ after Salomon Smith Barney analyst Jack
Grubman said he expects the company to earn $2.55 per share in
2001, instead of his previous estimate of $2.75. Grubman said AT&AMP;T
is facing higher sales, general and administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a better than 2-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to a
moderate 654.12 million shares, behind Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 6.48 to 499.50.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
