<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DA in court to hear of husband's 'greed and lust'  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- With District Attorney Jeanine Pirro
in the front row of the gallery, a federal prosecutor said
Wednesday that her husband's ''greed and lust for material
possessions,'' ranging from a Ferrari to a custom-made pigpen, led
him into a tax-fraud conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   The husband, lobbyist Albert Pirro, ''subsidized a lavish
lifestyle by cheating on his taxes,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Cathy
Seibel said in her opening statement to the jury.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney, who sat with her mother, dismissed the
claims as so much ''theater'' and said she was confident the
charges are false. She called the case ''an overreaching effort by
the government.''
</P>
<P>
   She came to court, she said, because ''My family is in trouble
now.'' She has not been charged in the case and much of the trial's
interest is in how closely she is linked to any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   During her morning in court, the district attorney showed little
emotion. When Seibel alleged that Albert Pirro had spent -- and
illegally deducted -- $70,000 to fight a paternity suit filed
against him, Mrs. Pirro looked toward the jurors once but did not
otherwise react.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Gustave Newman acknowledged that Pirro's tax
returns had ''misclassified'' many personal expenses as business
write-offs, but he attributed that to ''the hectic life'' of the
real estate dealmaker, lobbyist and Republican fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ''He wasn't hands on,'' Newman said. ''He did not sit down and
approve every check and look at every check.'' He claimed, for
example, that Pirro signed only 24 percent of the checks issued
from his personal checking account and as few as 2 percent of the
checks drawn on some of his business accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro's brother Anthony, who was his accountant and is a
co-defendant, ''signed a whole series of checks and paid bills
without ever discussing it with him,'' Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Seibel said that between 1988 and 1997, Albert Pirro
''fraudulently deducted ... hundreds upon hundreds upon hundreds of
personal items as though they were business expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Many involved the Pirros' home in Harrison, she said. Pirro
illegally deducted checks for work ranging from an exterminator's
visit to a pool man to a $45,000 electronically controlled driveway
gate. There was also a custom wrought iron enclosure for the
family's potbellied pigs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Newman implied that the driveway gate was required for Jeanine
Pirro's security. Although Seibel noted that Mrs. Pirro was not yet
district attorney when the gates were designed, Newman said she was
a county judge dealing with murderers and drug addicts.
</P>
<P>
   Also illegally deducted, Seibel said, were expenses from Jeanine
Pirro's campaigns for public office and the salaries of business
employees Albert Pirro used to do substantial personal work for
himself and his family, including the furnishing of his vacation
home in West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Newman said Pirro's behavior -- keeping just one set of books,
noting some personal expenses on the checks, making records
available to the IRS -- was not the behavior of ''somebody who wants
to commit a fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that after Pirro learned his taxes were being
investigated, he amended his returns, showed them to the Internal
Revenue Service and asked, ''Is there anything else you want me to
add?''
</P>
<P>
   Pirro, 52, ended up paying back half a million dollars plus
interest, Newman said -- more than was actually due.
</P>
<P>
   ''Think he got a refund?'' Newman asked the jury. ''You know
what he got? He got an indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Seibel said paying taxes after learning of an investigation
is no more of a defense than ''a bank robber paying the money back
after being caught red-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Pirro's lawyer, Roger Stavis, said several times that
his client was ''only the accountant.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Anthony Pirro is not a big shot, not a powerful man, not the
reason why I don't think there's a seat to be had in the
courtroom,'' Stavis said. ''He was paid regular accounting fees for
regular accounting work. ... The evidence will show that there was
no conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothers, if convicted, could be sentenced to up to five
years in prison if convicted of any of the scores of counts against
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
