<HEADLINE> India Altering Nursery Rhymes  </HEADLINE>
By RAMOLA TALWAR BADAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOMBAY, India (AP) -- Mary and her famous lamb will turn into
Meera and her cat for thousands of Indian children when new English
language textbooks come into use in June.
</P>
<P>
   And, instead of ''Rain, rain go away,'' some 8.5 million
students in the water-thirsty western state of Maharashtra will
recite ''Rain, rain come again.''
</P>
<P>
   '''Rain, rain go away' is a disastrous proposition in the Indian
context. So we changed this ...,'' Ramesh Dhongde, chairman of the
English committee of the textbook firm, Balbharati, told The
Associated Press on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   English nursery rhymes have been taught for more than 50 years
in primary schools in India, a former British colony.
</P>
<P>
   But as part of an effort to make the rhymes ''more Indian,''
teachers and textbook writers have been told they can substitute
the animals and other objects in the rhymes.
</P>
<P>
   The new English language textbooks will be introduced in June in
60,000 regional language schools all over Maharashtra, of which
Bombay is the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a government decision to Indianize. We academics merely
implemented it,'' said Dhongde, professor of linguistics at Deccan
College in Pune.
</P>
<P>
   ''But we kept the rhythm and used objects Indian children are
familiar with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 64-page book called, ''My English'' has short explanatory
texts for teachers in Indian languages, such as Urdu, Marathi,
Gujarati, Telugu, Kannada and Sindhi.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian Express newspaper reported the book will contain a
picture of a beaming Indian shepherd wearing a traditional dhoti or
wrap-around trousers to illustrate the rhyme, ''Ba, Ba, black
sheep.''
</P>
<P>
   Nursery rhymes such as ''Twinkle, twinkle, little star'' and
''Jack and Jill went up the hill'' were left untouched since
academicians felt these were universal.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's no point just changing names. We've tried to introduce
some Indian culture and make them more appealing,'' said Dhongde,
part of the five-member committee that revised the syllabus.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want children to feel threatened by a new language.
They should enjoy it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1545 </TRAILER>
