<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Unions Open to Reform  </HEADLINE>
By HANS GREIMEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- In the egalitarian world of Germany's
consensus economy, there was a time when unions held out for
one-size-fits-all contracts that covered nearly every field from
shipbuilding to semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
   But with Europe's biggest economy scrambling to compete in a
global economy where wages are increasingly set by local conditions
and profitability, Germany's most powerful union seems finally
poised to rethink old tactics -- and in doing so could give an extra
boost to Germany's fledgling economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   A breakthrough came recently when IG Metall, the world's largest
union representing 3.4 million metal and electronics workers in
such blue-chip companies as DaimlerChrysler AG and Siemens AG,
invited its members to contemplate a wide range of reform topics
that once were considered taboo.
</P>
<P>
   That includes mixing up pay scales, accepting different work
weeks for different industries, and even allowing opt-out clauses
for companies that cannot afford the unions' demands.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to realize that the different branches of the economy
have different needs,'' said IG Metall spokeswoman Dagmar
Opoeczynski. ''The idea is to open up to greater flexibility to
serve all our members.''
</P>
<P>
   The move has ramifications for the whole German economy because
IG Metall has traditionally set the standard for contracts in other
industries.
</P>
<P>
   Union vice president Juergen Peters asked members for feedback
Monday as part of a plan to draw up negotiating points that offer
more flexibility when the union goes back the bargaining table in
2002. IG Metall has already sealed a two-year contract to keep them
working until then.
</P>
<P>
   That contract gives equal wage increases to workers in the
eastern and western parts of the country. But it failed to get
eastern workers a shorter, 35-hour workweek to match western hours,
settling instead for a 38-hour workweek.
</P>
<P>
   That was the first sign of trouble for the unions' strategy of
demanding identical contracts throughout the country, an outcome
employers have long decried as artificially driving up unemployment
and labor costs.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling companies in the eastern part of Germany resist
paying equal wages saying it would force them out of business
because productivity in the east continues to lag western levels.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, high-tech workers in information technology,
telecommunications and semiconductors shun unions for usually
lumping them together with other fields and depressing their
otherwise higher salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Those pressures are starting to show in union membership.
</P>
<P>
   In the past six years, the number of German workers belonging to
unions dropped 17 percent. If that weren't bad enough, high-tech
workers -- the engine of the new economy and a big growth field --
tend not to join unions, making up only 10 percent of IG Metall's
membership.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unions are realizing that they are losing members so this
approach is more realistic,'' said Peter Meister, an economist with
BHF Bank in Frankfurt. ''It's important that they make changes and
this should help the impression that Europe is resistant to
reform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1552 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
