<HEADLINE> Civil-Rights-List  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Other civil rights cases that recently have been
reopened:
<TEXT>
<P>
   --February 1994: Byron De La Beckwith is convicted for the June
12, 1963 murder of Medgar Evers, the first field secretary for the
NAACP. Beckwith had been tried twice before for the crime, but both
trials ended with hung juries. He is appealing the conviction.
</P>
<P>
   --In 1998, Police in Jackson County, Miss., reopen investigation
into the 1967 death of Benjamin Brown, who was shot to death by
police during a student protest at Jackson State University. Brown
had not been protesting, and no action was taken against the police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   --April 1998: Police in Natchez, Miss., begin reinvestigating the
1967 death of Wharlest Jackson, treasurer of the Natchez NAACP, who
was killed by a car bomb. Weeks before his death, Jackson had been
promoted to a position at a local tire plant that had previously
only been held by white men. No one was ever arrested for the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   --August 1998: Sam Bowers, former imperial wizard of the Ku Klux
Klan, is convicted for the 1966 murder of Vernon Dahmer. Dahmer,
president of the NAACP in Hattiesburg, Miss., was killed in a
firebombing of his house. Originally, 14 Klansmen were tried for
the crime, and three were convicted. The case of another suspect,
Charles Noble, ended in mistrial in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   --November 1999: Charles E. Caston, James Caston and Hal Crimm
are each sentenced to 20 years in prison for the 1970 murder of
Rainey Pool. Pool, a one-armed sharecropper from Midnight, Miss.,
was beaten and dumped in a river. Seven white men were originally
arrested for the crime, but charges were dismissed. Two had since
died, one was acquitted in June 1998 and another pleaded guilty to
reduced charges in 1999. Charles Caston died in prison in March,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   --February 2000: The FBI reopens investigation into the 1964
murders of Charles Eddie Moore and Henry Hezekiah Dee in Natchez,
Miss. The House Un-American Activities Committee questioned at
least five men in connection with the killings, and two were
arrested, but authorities dismissed the charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1554 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Behind-the-scenes battle over Assembly leadership  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The halls of the state Capitol were sizzling
Wednesday with reports that state Assembly Majority Leader Michael
Bragman, possibly with the help of opposition Republicans, might
move to oust fellow Democrat Sheldon Silver as Assembly speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ''The message from Mike is that there's just no comment at this
time,'' said Bragman spokesman Daniel Weiller when asked about the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman, a Syracuse-area Democrat, is the leader of the
Assembly's conservative upstate Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Lynch, a spokesman for Manhattan Democrat Silver, said
she was not commenting on the reports of a possible rebellion
against the Assembly's No. 1 Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he puts a statement out, then I'll respond,'' Lynch said
when asked about Bragman.
</P>
<P>
   One scenario had Bragman lining up some fellow Democrats who are
dissatisfied with Silver's leadership and joining up with some or
all of the chamber's 51 Republican members to come up with the 76
votes needed in the 150-member Assembly to elect a new speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Republican votes might be used to help Bragman
against Silver, Assembly Minority Leader John Faso, the leader of
the chamber's GOP forces, said: ''That remains to be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Bragman has been talking to some Republicans,'' said one
senior Republican member of the Assembly, who spoke only on
condition of not being identified.
</P>
<P>
   Silver loyalists insisted Bragman would be unable to muster the
votes to depose Silver, even if he could form an alliance with the
Assembly Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Relations have been strained between Silver and Bragman for some
time over a host of issues, including Bragman's desire to someday
have Silver's job.
</P>
<P>
   More recently there has been tension over Bragman's decision to
get behind the possible 2002 gubernatorial candidacy of state
Comptroller H. Carl McCall. Silver had urged members to stay
neutral for the time being and there has been speculation that
Silver really favors the potential rival candidacy for governor of
federal Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   Bragman was also not among the 24 speakers that addressed the
Democratic state convention Tuesday that nominated Hillary Rodham
Clinton for the U.S. Senate. Silver had much influence over who got
those speaking assignments.
</P>
<P>
   With the Assembly is in recess until Monday, no formal action
could come before then.
</P>
<P>
   The possible move by Bragman against Silver was the hot topic at
the state Capitol on Wednesday, even in the Republican-led state
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just heard people talking about it in the aisle,'' state
Sen. William Larkin, an Orange County Republican, said.
</P>
<P>
   Also creating tension between Bragman and Silver is the
traditional upstate-downstate split in New York. The Assembly has
long been controlled by New York City-area Democrats who tend to be
more liberal than Bragman and other Democrats from outside the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Silver was elected Assembly speaker in 1994. Bragman has been
majority leader that entire time.
</P>
<P>
   The last Albany leader to be deposed was then-state Senate
Majority Leader Ralph Marino, a Long Island Republican, who was
ousted in a 1994 Thanksgiving Day weekend coup led by current
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, a Rensselaer County Republican. At
the time, Marino's troops insisted Bruno didn't have the votes to
pull off the coup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-17-00 1557 </TRAILER>
