<HEADLINE> Ohio man sentenced to 6 months for assaulting child on plane  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- An Ohio man who pleaded guilty to
charges he assaulted a 7-year-old girl aboard a Northwest Airlines
flight was sentenced to six months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Howard, 40, of Sylvania, Ohio, told the girl's family he
was sorry for the crime at a sentencing hearing Tuesday. But the
child's mother rejected his apology.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has no idea what he has done to my family,'' the mother
told U.S. District Judge Dean Buttram. ''I do not accept his
apology.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard entered a guilty plea in December to assaulting the girl
last May 14 while she was traveling alone from Birmingham to see
her father in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The girl was first seated in the back of the airplane, but
flight attendants moved her to first class, where an intoxicated
Howard tried to start a conversation with the girl and hold her
hand. He pulled her hair to keep her in the seat, leaving the
little girl with scrapes and bruises.
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendants moved the girl to the back of the airplane,
but Howard followed. He was asked to return to his first-class
seat, and flight attendants finally put a beverage cart in the
aisle to thwart him.
</P>
<P>
   The girl's family is suing Minneapolis-based Northwest Airlines,
Howard and his employer, Toledo, Ohio-based Midport Electronics
Inc., claiming negligence.
</P>
<P>
   ''What you've done disturbs the court,'' Buttram told Howard.
''I wish I could do more to you than what I'm allowed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He ordered Howard to pay a $5,000 fine with interest and $400 in
restitution to the girl's parents.
</P>
<P>
   Howard's attorney, Lorin L. Zaner, told the judge Howard is not
a career criminal and listed various charities his client is
involved in.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a plea agreement, the prosecution recommended Howard
serve his sentence at a prison camp.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney James Phillips asked Buttram to dismiss
a charge of sexual contact. Buttram did so, but said the action was
taken ''reluctantly and disapprovingly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
