<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dispute Over Queen Mother's birthday  </HEADLINE>
By AUDREY WOODS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The Queen Mother Elizabeth turns 100 this summer,
a joyful occasion for much of the nation -- and the surprising
source of a dispute that reached the House of Commons on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The publicly funded British Broadcasting Corp. last week
announced it would not televise the celebratory pageant to be held
in the Queen Mother's honor two weeks before her Aug. 4 birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Outrage, dismay and mutterings about disloyalty echoed around
the land.
</P>
<P>
   ''How Dare The BBC Snub The Queen Mother'' trumpeted the tabloid
Daily Mail. The more sedate Daily Telegraph called it ''sad and
surprising that the BBC is ignoring the main pageant in honor of
this extraordinary life.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair, answering a parliamentary question
Wednesday, said he hoped the problem could be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think everyone would like to see a televised broadcast of
the Queen Mother's celebration because everyone wishes her well --
it would be a fantastic event for the whole of the nation,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Within the hour, the commercial ITV network rode to the rescue,
announcing it would televise the pageant.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am delighted that ITV, Britain's favorite channel, will lead
the salute to Britain's favorite grandmother,'' said ITV's program
director David Liddiment, seizing the high-profile moment to plug
his network.
</P>
<P>
   But the Queen Mother is far more than an appealing grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   As queen consort during World War II, she was a source of
strength to King George VI and a focus for homefront morale. In the
half-century of change that followed, she became a bulwark of the
monarchy and remained untainted by the criticism that afflicted her
daughter, Queen Elizabeth II.
</P>
<P>
   She has retained the affection and loyalty of the wartime
generation, and maintains ties with the surviving men and women who
served at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The July 19 pageant involves a cast of 7,000, as well as many
charities for whom the Queen Mother is patron.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights will be a march of the scarlet-coated
Household Cavalry, an air show by World War II aircraft, music from
the Royal Philharmonic Orchestra and a tribute from actor Sir John
Mills.
</P>
<P>
   The BBC said it would focus its coverage instead on the Aug. 4
events, having decided that ''Her Majesty's birthday itself should
be our main priority and that the BBC's comprehensive level of
coverage was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Details of the Aug. 4 celebrations have not been publicized, but
the BBC said it planned a full schedule of tributes for that day,
as well as coverage of a July 11 service of thanksgiving at St.
Paul's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   As always, the Queen Mother herself kept well away from the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman at Clarence House, her London residence, said no
comment would be made, and that the arrangements were a matter for
the TV companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1600 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0139 </DOCNO>
