<HEADLINE> State senator's son gets charges reduced in plea bargain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CANTON, N.Y. (AP) -- The son of long-time state Sen. Ronald B.
Stafford has pleaded guilty to having an altered license, but he
avoided several other charges in a plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Parker K. Stafford, 20, a St. Lawrence University student, was
charged April 22 with driving while intoxicated, driving while
ability impaired by drugs, possession of marijuana and driving
without headlights. All of those charges were dismissed Tuesday by
Village Justice Michael C. Crowe.
</P>
<P>
   Parker Stafford, who was represented by attorney Charles B.
Gardner of Gouverneur, was fined $50 and ordered to pay a $30 fee
for the altered-license charge.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe also ordered him to pay a $125 civil penalty and suspended
his driver's license for six months for violating the state's zero
tolerance law.
</P>
<P>
   The zero tolerance law, enacted in 1996, applies to drivers
under age 21 who are found to have blood alcohol levels between .02
and .07 percent. A drunken-driving charge in New York requires a
blood alcohol level of at least .10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the zero tolerance law, there were no sanctions to
apply to someone under 21 who was drinking and driving but not
legally drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Stafford has represented the Plattsburgh area in the
state Legislature since 1966.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
