<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Approves Land Spending Bill  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House panel voted Wednesday to slash
President Clinton's plans for purchasing new parklands next year by
70 percent, prompting Democratic warnings that a veto battle lay
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts were part of a $14.6 billion measure financing the
Interior Department and cultural programs in fiscal 2001. The
measure has other environmental provisions the administration also
opposes, including a prohibition on improvements in the four
national monuments Clinton has created this year in California and
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The overall bill, approved by voice vote by a subcommittee of
the House Appropriations Committee, provides $300 million less than
this year and $1.7 billion less than Clinton requested. Democrats
declared the bill unsalvageable for now.
</P>
<P>
   ''We might as well get on with the hanging and see if we can
resurrect the corpse somewhere down the road,'' said Rep. David
Obey, D-Wis.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would increase the overall budgets of the National
Park Service, the Fish and Wildlife Service and the Bureau of Land
Management, with most of the extra money for maintenance, not
expansions.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was our highest priority,'' said Rep. Ralph Regula,
R-Ohio, the subcommittee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   By trimming Clinton's $620 million proposal for acquiring
federal, state and local land to just $186 million, Republicans
were once again targeting one of his top legislative priorities. In
a bill written earlier this month, House Republicans would kill his
plans to help communities hire new teachers and repair schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can guarantee the president won't sign this bill into law
unless this level is significantly raised,'' said Rep. Norm Dicks,
D-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The amount in the bill falls well below the nearly $3 billion a
year that would be set aside for land purchases, wildlife
protection and other environmental programs under a huge
conservation bill the House approved last week. Should that measure
become law, it would not take effect until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   A provision sponsored by Rep. James Hansen, R-Utah, would bar
any expenditures for planning, designing or managing the new
national monuments. Democrats said they believed the language would
even prohibit expenditures for roads or law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans and business interests have opposed Clinton's
monument designations, calling them federal land grabs that were
hurting local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, he has designated the Grand Canyon-Parashant
and Agua Fria national monuments in Arizona; the California Coastal
National Monument, which is thousands of tiny islands; and more
than 30 groves of giant sequoia trees across California. They total
more than 1 million acres.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's 1996 designation of the 1.7-million-acre Grand
Staircase-Escalante National Monument in Utah would not be
affected.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also includes:
</P>
<P>
   --$350 million in emergency funds for the Interior Department's
and Forest Service's costs of fighting fires this year, including
the huge blaze that has devastated much of Los Alamos, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   --Language slowing efforts to tighten federal restrictions on
public lands in Washington state east of the Cascade Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   --A halt to Fish and Wildlife Service plans to create a new
refuge at Yolo Basin, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   --$98 million for the National Endowment for the Arts, the same
as this year and $52 million below Clinton's request.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1621 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
