<HEADLINE> Man Arrested at Congress Hearing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A man carrying an Australian passport was
arrested Wednesday after he smashed two glass bottles during a
House hearing on China trade and threatened to kill himself if he
was not heard.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Capitol Police spokesman Lt. Dan Nichols said one police
officer suffered a superficial cut on the wrist when he and an
Agriculture Department special agent subdued the man, identified as
Daniel Chagashvili, 49.
</P>
<P>
   He said Chagashvili was a native of the Republic of Georgia and
a naturalized Australian citizen who has been living in the
Brooklyn borough of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols said Chagashvili would be arraigned as early as Thursday
in U.S. District Court on charges of assaulting a federal police
officer and disrupting the official business of Congress, both
federal offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman was testifying at the time on
the effects of U.S.-China trade on agriculture. Commerce Secretary
William Daley and U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky
were also present at the packed hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Baca, D-Calif., who was attending the hearing, said the
man, after smashing the large bottles, raised one to his head and
said he would kill himself if he was not heard. Baca said the two
security officers reacted immediately, wrestling him to the ground
before he could approach any of the officials.
</P>
<P>
   Baca said that after his initial comment the man spoke in a
language Baca did not understand.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Earl Pomeroy, D-N.D., said he also grabbed the man from
behind and the man fell on top of him before the security officers
pushed him into the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols said it appeared the man was carrying soft drink
bottles. He said the contents were checked for chemical or
biological materials, but the tests were negative.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing stopped with the incident, but resumed in the
afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
