<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 166; Nasdaq Off 72  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Investors resumed a cautious stance today,
sending stocks lower as they determined that the interest rate
increase implemented by the Federal Reserve on yesterday may indeed
threaten stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 166.03 to close at
10,769.74.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower, although their losses
were more modest. The Nasdaq composite index fell 72.68 to
3,644.89.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 18.25 to 1,447.79.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by nearly a 2-to-1 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,908 down, 1,015 up and 483
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 813.68 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs.
945.94 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 6.32 to 499.66.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness on Wall Street didn't surprise analysts, who
believed stocks were due to falter as investors tried to capture
gains from a four-day rally that extended through Tuesday, when the
Fed, as expected, raised interest rates a half-percentage point --
its steepest increase in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates are generally bad for stocks, raising
borrowing costs and cutting into bottom-line profits. Investors had
bid stocks higher on the hope that Tuesday's increase could be the
last for a while, but with many economists predicting still higher
rates later this year, many investors lost their nerve today,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The market is supposed to have a difficult time when the Fed
is raising rates,'' said Robert Streed, senior investment counselor
at Northern Trust in Chicago. ''The old adage says 'Don't fight the
Fed,' and I think people forgot that for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks have, in fact, suffered while the Fed has been raising
rates in an attempt to slow the economy's growth to a more
sustainable pace. Gail Dudack, chief equity strategist at UBS
Warburg in New York, pointed out that in the 11 volatile months
since the Fed began raising rates, the Dow has declined about 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq, which had a history-making surge in late 1999 and
early 2000, is up about 35 percent since June 1999. But the index
has tumbled dramatically from its all-time high of 5,048.62, set
March 10, and a large number of stocks in the index are down for
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Dudack said the Dow's performance is more typical during a time
of escalating rates, and the Nasdaq's recent slump may be bringing
it in line with historical measures. Further rate increases will
only worsen the damage, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the accumulation of rate hikes that truly hampers stock
market performance over time,'' Dudack said, adding that she
expects the market to dip further in May and June before rallying
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard, the top-performing Dow component on Tuesday,
fell sharply today. After the close of trading Tuesday, the company
reported second-quarter earnings that topped Wall Street analysts'
expectations. But testy investors may have been expecting
Hewlett-Packard to more dramatically exceed published estimates,
analysts said. Others suggested that the company may be growing
dependent on lower margin areas such as personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Agilent, the testing and measuring equipment maker that was spun
off from Hewlett-Packard, also fell after releasing its earnings
report, which revealed weakness in health-care products and
chemical-analysis equipment divisions.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T fell after Salomon Smith Barney analyst Jack Grubman said
he expects the company to earn $2.55 per share in 2001, instead of
his previous estimate of $2.75. Grubman said AT&AMP;T is facing higher
sales, general and administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
