<HEADLINE> Jackson Set for Sierra Leone Trip  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
welcomed the arrest of rebel leader Foday Sankoh of Sierra Leone,
civil rights activist Jesse Jackson was planning to depart
Wednesday on a five-nation West Africa tour to promote peace in
that country.
</P>
<P>
   Sankoh, head of the Revolutionary United Front, is held
responsible for sabotaging a 10-month old peace agreement, and
Albright hailed his arrest as good news. Sankoh was seized by
pro-government troops in the Sierra Leone capital of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, the administration's special envoy to Africa, scheduled
a late afternoon departure for Nigeria, which is weighing the
possibility of deploying military units in Sierra Leone to
supplement U.N. peacekeepers already there.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Jackson will visit Liberia, Mali, Guinea and Sierra
Leone, security conditions permitting, State Department spokesman
Richard Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is departing on his mission a day late. For unexplained
reasons, the chronology of the countries he will visit changed
substantially overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher said Jackson's mission is to consult with regional
governments on ways the United States can support their efforts to
solve the Sierra Leone crisis and to bring about the release of
U.N. peacekeepers, who are being detained by Sankoh's forces.
</P>
<P>
   Albright visited Sierra Leone last October and met with Sankoh,
imploring him to abide by the July peace agreement, which was
designed to end long years of fighting that had catastrophic
consequences for the civilian population.
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Sierra Leone deteriorated rapidly after a
Nigerian-led intervention force departed the country almost three
weeks ago. Sankoh's forces took 500 U.N. peacekeepers hostage,
about a third of whom have been released.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has shown little inclination to
become involved in the situation, declining to go beyond an offer
of airlift and logistics in support of an expanding U.N. deployment
of peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The issue of what happens next for Foday Sankoh and the peace
process is really in the hands of the people and the government of
Sierra Leone,'' Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration seems to have a mixed view on Sankoh. On
Monday, Boucher said Sankoh has a ''chance to play a positive
role'' in resurrecting the peace agreement that he signed almost a
year ago and then violated.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the administration had said that Sankoh, by his
actions, may well have forfeited his right to the amnesty he and
his forces were granted as part of the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International USA, meanwhile, expressed grave concern
that Sankoh won't be brought to justice despite continuing human
rights violations by his forces.
</P>
<P>
   The group said the violations are ''serious breaches of
international humanitarian law and possible crimes against
humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   It also said that Jackson, during his West Africa mission,
should ''oppose the granting of renewed impunity to the
perpetrators of atrocities and human rights abuses''
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department:
www.state.gov/www/regions/africa/index.html
</P>
</TEXT>
