<HEADLINE> FBI Releases Files on Puerto Ricans  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The FBI director released decades-old
surveillance files on suspected Puerto Rican independence leaders
to a New York congressman on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Director Louis Freeh also pledged increased cooperation in
releasing additional files, Democratic Rep. Jose Serrano said after
he and lawmakers from Puerto Rico's Senate met with the FBI leader.
</P>
<P>
   ''The meeting for me was historic, dramatic and important
because I saw from the director a desire to deal with this ugly
part of our history,'' said Serrano, who was born in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI only recently acknowledged that it played a role in
police surveillance in Puerto Rico that produced more than 135,000
secret dossiers spanning more than three decades. FBI officials did
not immediately return a phone call Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the files released dated back to the 1930s. A batch of
documents had been released in the 1970s and 1980s, but much of the
information in them was deemed classified and blacked out. Serrano
said Freeh had assured him that the newly-released files would
contain ''99 percent less blackouts.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the dossiers contained in the four boxes released
Wednesday was that of Pedro Albizu Campos, leader of the Puerto
Rican independence movement. Campos was jailed several times,
including a 1954 arrest after four of his followers opened fire
inside the U.S. House of Representatives, wounding five lawmakers.
He died in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   The recent decision to dedicate New York City's Puerto Rican Day
Parade next month to Campos has drawn fire from some circles.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear what if any new information the files would
contain. Serrano said a review would take time.
</P>
<P>
   Police began collecting information on suspected independence
advocates as Puerto Rico moved toward its current commonwealth
arrangement with the United States. The government passed the
so-called Gag Law in the 1948, which made it illegal to show the
Puerto Rican flag, sing nationalist songs or hold ''seditious''
rallies.
</P>
<P>
   The files, some released in 1989 when the practice was declared
unconstitutional, carried detailed notes and even photographs
tracking people's jobs, lives, family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   In December, after 10 years of legal battles, Puerto Rico's
government apologized and offered $5.7 million to compensate those
who were under surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand for the meeting Wednesday was Charlie Rodriquez,
president of the Senate of Puerto Rico, as well as Sens. Manuel
Rodriguez-Orellana and Eduardo Bhatia-Gautier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1650 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
