<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Magnetic Pads May Affect Pacemakers  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- People with pacemakers or implanted
defibrillators should never use those new magnet-laced mattress
pads touted to ease back pain because the magnets could temporarily
shut off the heart devices, scientists reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Magnets slipped inside shoe insoles, wristbands, back braces and
other gadgets are the newest rage, purported to treat different
aches and pains.
</P>
<P>
   Most never get close enough to the heart to affect a pacemaker
patient, said Dr. Thomas Mattioni of the Arizona Heart Institute in
Phoenix, who led the magnet study after some of his own patients
asked if they were safe.
</P>
<P>
   His best advice: keep ''therapeutic magnets'' 6 inches from your
chest if you have a pacemaker or defibrillator. ''You need to stay
that critical distance away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But rolling onto your stomach while sleeping on a magnet-laced
mattress pad could cause the heart devices to switch off
temporarily, concludes Mattioni's study, presented at this week's
North American Society of Pacing and Electrophysiology meeting.
</P>
<P>
   That could be life-threatening if the patient went into an
irregular heartbeat at the same time, Mattioni said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to mattress pads, it also is possible that a a
magnet-laced neck brace or shoulder wrap could get closer than 6
inches to the chest, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Mattioni discovered the magnets are not nearly as powerful as
the claims made by some manufacturers of magnetic strength equal to
an MRI, or magnetic resonance imaging, machine.
</P>
<P>
   When Mattioni measured a variety of magnets, he found even the
highest-strength ones were over 10 times weaker than claimed. They
rapidly grew weaker the farther away they are held from people's
skin. Most lost their ability to deactivate a pacemaker when 1 inch
away, and their power completely disappeared 6 inches away.
</P>
<P>
   Over 2 million Americans have pacemakers and 250,000 have
defibrillators to help their hearts beat properly.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people use magnets in hopes of alleviating back
pain or arthritis, even though there is no scientific proof they
work. A study in the Journal of the American Medical Association
this spring found no difference between patients using real magnets
and fake ones given as a placebo.
</P>
<P>
   Mattioni's study did not examine whether the magnets worked.
Instead, he performed the first known safety tests after some of
his pacemaker patients told him the magnets made them feel better.
</P>
<P>
   No magnets are approved by the Food and Drug Administration,
which worries more about magnet manufacturers making improper
health claims than about their safety.
</P>
<P>
   But the new findings are ''something to be concerned and aware
of,'' said FDA scientist Mitchell Schein, a pacemaker specialist.
''I would advise the patient to consult their physician before
using such a mattress pad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1656 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
