<HEADLINE> Student Accused of Lacing Drink  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MICHIGAN CITY, Ind. (AP) -- A high school junior is accused of
trying to poison a teacher who dates her aunt by lacing a soft
drink with copper radiator sealant.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Kniola, 18, was charged Tuesday with criminal
recklessness. If convicted, she could face six months to three
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   According to court records, earlier this month Kniola had
another student deliver a tainted Dr Pepper to Michigan City High
science teacher David Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The student said she was initially unaware that the beverage
contained poison, but learned later that Kniola had allegedly put
something in it.
</P>
<P>
   Another student had warned Davis of rumors of a poisoning,
however, so Davis saved the soda and contacted police.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, according to court records, Kniola approached
Davis and said she heard he had been sick all night. He told her
she was mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   ''The suspect's eyes became very large, and she quickly walked
off,'' Davis told police.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also reported receiving a threatening letter and harassing
telephone calls from Kniola for several weeks last fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
