<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Pushes for China Trade Bill  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERETT, Wash. (AP) -- George W. Bush pushed for normalization of
trade relations with China Wednesday in a rare moment of agreement
with the Clinton administration, winning a warm reception from
Boeing Co. workers whose jobs depend on sales overseas.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential candidate said political differences
should not prevent congressional approval of the agreement. His
Democratic foe, Vice President Al Gore, also endorses the measure,
though it has been strongly opposed by some labor unions that fear
a loss of jobs to overseas competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Key committees in both the House and Senate gave their approval
to the measure Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The stakes are high, they're high on all sides,'' Bush said,
speaking to several hundred airplane builders from a platform in
front of an unfinished Korean Air Boeing 777-300. The plane, among
the newest models for the company, is a popular pick for Asian
airlines. On the other side of the factory, customers were touring
a completed Air China 777.
</P>
<P>
   ''For businesses and workers and farmers across our country, it
will mean much lower trade barriers, important opportunities for
U.S. exports and more work and jobs for United States workers. For
the people of East Asia, it will affect their relations with the
region's major power, and for the people of China, it holds out the
hope of more open contact with the world of freedom,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing was hampered earlier this year by a strike by its
engineers, members of the Society for Professional Engineering
Employees in Aerospace. Boeing missed at least 15 airplane
deliveries during the walkout in February and March.
</P>
<P>
   While the union has endorsed Gore, the Texas governor said
Tuesday, ''They may be supporting him, but this is not a political
event. ... I want the machinists to understand that opening up
China to trade would be good for their jobs and their job
security.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Association of Machinists, another union that
has endorsed Gore, praised him for earlier Boeing visits and
criticized the Republican Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''We find it ironic that George Bush shows up at the Boeing
Everett Plant five months before the election to do a major trade
event. This doesn't mean he understands or has spent any time with
our Boeing workers,'' the machinists' statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush's speech was warmly received and he spent over a
half hour afterward shaking workers' hands. One, Thomas Mariano, a
30-year-old fuel tank inspector, said he appreciated Bush's focus
on job creation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would think that either of the candidates, if they're for
working families, I think that would be the best benefit for most
folks,'' Mariano said.
</P>
<P>
   The China bill would end the annual practice of renewing China's
trade status and would grant Beijing the same normal trade
relations that the United States extends routinely to nearly every
other nation in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would ease China's entry into the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   With unions generally opposed to the measure, Gore had remained
mostly quiet on the issue until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, standing with former Presidents Ford and
Carter at the White House, Gore declared: ''It is right for
American jobs. It is right for the cause of reform in China and I
believe it will move us closer to the strong and stable world
community that we all seek to create.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in a swipe at Gore, said, ''This will be amongst the most
serious decisions our government will make this year, and no one
who is serious about shouldering the responsibilities of the
presidency should be silent on the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush highlighted what he said would be the agreement's economic
benefits. Boeing, for example, projects China to be its largest
market over the next 20 years, and China must cut industrial
tariffs and allow more imports of wheat, corn and other
agricultural products, perhaps creating new markets for U.S.
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush also argued that the benefits would be more than
economic.
</P>
<P>
   ''Economic freedom creates habits of liberty, and habits of
liberty create expectations of democracy,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1703 </TRAILER>
