<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sophia Loren Loses Voting Rights  </HEADLINE>
By PETER W. MAYER
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Sophia Loren has been cut from a leading roll.
</P>
<P>
   Loren, a symbol of Italian female beauty, was among more than
300,000 names stricken from the voter rolls, local officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Italian lawmakers last week ordered election officials to purge
names of voters who had died, emigrated or otherwise become
ineligible. Officials in the southern town of Pozzuoli near Naples
said they deleted the film star because she has long lived abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Loren's politician-niece, Alessandra Mussolini, insisted her
aunt still spends much of her time in Italy. ''If this could happen
to someone famous like my aunt, imagine all the ordinary citizens
who will lose their right to vote,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mussolini, whose grandfather was fascist dictator Benito
Mussolini, said Wednesday she would boycott a key nationwide
referendum to protest the voting-list cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   ''I already had my doubts about this referendum, but the way the
lists were purged is anti-democratic,'' said Mussolini, a member of
Parliament for the right-wing National Alliance party.
</P>
<P>
   The order came ahead of Sunday's referendum on pivotal election,
justice and labor reforms. Failures of past referendums have been
blamed in part on poorly maintained election lists with dead
voters, making it all but impossible to obtain the necessary votes.
</P>
<P>
   Mussolini's party supports the referendum and the purge of voter
rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Mussolini, herself a former actress, is the daughter of
Mussolini's son Romano, a jazz pianist, and Loren's sister, Maria
Scicolone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
