<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violence Erupts in Zimbabwe  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS SHAW
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Rival party supporters clashed in
western Harare, leaving one person dead and 18 injured, police said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the violence Tuesday night started when about 15
youths attacked Takudzwa Chipunza, who was believed to have been a
supporter of the opposition Movement for Democratic Change party,
police spokeswoman Tendai Nembire said.
</P>
<P>
   Chipunza died Wednesday at a Harare hospital from head injuries
suffered in the attack, bringing to 20 the number of people killed
in political violence since February.
</P>
<P>
   The overnight clashes occurred in the Budiriro township in
western Harare. Four of the injured were in serious condition,
Nembire said.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of those injured said they belonged to President Robert
Mugabe's ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   Some clashes took place outside the office of Chenjerai Hunzvi,
a doctor who leads a militant group of pro-Mugabe liberation war
veterans that led to independence in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Fire bombs were hurled into two homes, gutting them. Opposition
supporters smashed the windows of Hunzvi's offices, claiming that
veterans had dragged their colleagues into the clinic last week and
beaten and tortured them.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, the opposition group denounced Mugabe's call
for parliamentary elections to be held on June 24-25 as a violation
of electoral procedures, and opposition lawyers prepared for a
court action that could force a postponement.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition party says the government failed to release voter
lists and voting boundaries within the time frame that electoral
law demands. It planned to ask the High Court for the immediate
release of the information, and to argue that the government was
trying to thwart opposition preparations for polling, the party's
legal adviser David Coltart said.
</P>
<P>
   The elections pose the greatest threat to Mugabe's power since
1980, when he led this former British colony in southeast Africa to
independence.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe says candidates must be nominated by May 29. But Coltart
said that, under electoral law, the voting lists and boundaries
must be made public 14 days ahead of the nomination deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without the information required, it will be virtually
impossible to nominate 120 candidates by month end,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coltart said the opposition party's court application, expected
to be filed Thursday, would likely delay elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are as reluctant as anyone to see further delays, but we
have no option but to lodge this application. The government has
acted unconstitutionally and in breach of electoral law,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe's opponents say he has encouraged the often-violent
occupations of more than 1,200 white-owned farms to punish white
farmers and their workers for supporting the opposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1722 </TRAILER>
