<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Prepare Ad Campaign  </HEADLINE>
By RON FOURNIER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Democratic National Committee is
preparing to launch a multimillion dollar ad campaign designed to
bolster Al Gore's presidential campaign by introducing his
biography to Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The ad blitz, engineered by the vice president's political team,
could begin as early as this month and end at the presidential
convention this summer, costing upwards of $10 million, according
to Democratic officials in Washington who cautioned that the
details were still being worked out.
</P>
<P>
   One senior Democrat said the campaign would cost between $10
million and $20 million, though others said much of the money has
yet to be raised and a budget has not been finalized. A late-May
start-up is possible, officials said, but June is more likely.
</P>
<P>
   The officials spoke on condition that they not be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, meanwhile, are already accusing Gore of violating a
pledge to forsake unregulated, unlimited expenditures in the
presidential campaign. Gore challenged the Republican Party and
presumptive nominee George W. Bush to mutually disarm their
so-called ''soft money'' ad arsenals, but the offer was rejected
and no deal was struck.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC ads, which are still being tested in focus groups, will
be funded with a mix of ''hard money'' -- limited, regulated
donations -- and the so-called ''soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads were described by several party officials as a
discussion of Democratic issues that give way to biographical
material about Gore. Other Democratic candidates would
theoretically benefit from the DNC expenditure, though Gore would
be the primary benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   There was little chance that the first batch of ads would
criticize Bush, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers envision airing several different spots, placed
strategically in key media markets based on polling data that shows
what issues play well in various battleground states.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the outlines of the ad campaign were reviewed by
Gore's team last week. Senior officials asked for more data and
scheduled a meeting Thursday at Gore's campaign headquarters here.
The ad campaign will be discussed, but not necessarily finalized,
at that meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Since the vice president issued the challenge on the night he
and Bush secured their party's nominations, independent
Republican-allied groups have run issue ads paid with ''soft
money.'' Officials at the Republican National Committee itself say
they have not run ''soft money'' ads and have no control over
independent groups.
</P>
<P>
   ''If (Democrats) are looking for a loophole, they can find one.
We always knew that. In 1996 they ran an illegal campaign. This
year, they're running an unethical campaign,'' said RNC spokesman
Cliff May, who noted that Democratic-allied independent groups have
aired issue ads.
</P>
<P>
   DNC spokeswoman Jenny Backus said two GOP-allied interest groups
ran about $1.5 million in ads criticizing Gore shortly after the
vice president issued the challenge. ''They've violated (the
challenge) in both words and deeds right after it went out,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats privately concede they were looking for an excuse to
spend their ''soft money'' accounts to improve Gore's political
standing.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president narrowly trails Bush in national polls and is
not faring well in several traditionally Democratic states. His
advisers are more troubled by underlying poll results that show
Gore trailing Bush among key demographic groups; voters also
consider Bush to be a better leader.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's advisers say his fortunes will improve as
Americans learn more about him.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a similar situation in the primary race against former
New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, the vice president aired biography
ads and started talking more about his background in public -- the
achievements of his father, former Sen. Al Gore Sr, and mother, a
groundbreaking law student; his service in the Vietnam War; his
stint as an investigative journalist and his experience in the
House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's top advisers said there was debate within the campaign
almost immediately about whether challenging Bush was a good idea,
given the Democrats' reliance on ''soft money'' to close the
fund-raising gap against the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not accept federal matching money, thus is not bound by
spending limits. Gore is subject to the limits.
</P>
<P>
   Top Gore advisers such as Bill Knapp work both for the DNC and
the vice president's campaign, making it possible to navigate the
loosely regulated guidelines regarding coordination between party's
and campaigns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
