<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gold at 7-Mo. Low As Dollar Gains  </HEADLINE>
By HERBERT G. McCANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gold futures prices fell to a 7-month low Wednesday as the
dollar grew in strength against most major currencies in the wake
of the Federal Reserve's half percentage point increase in the
short-term borrowing rate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the firmer dollar, gold was weakened by the
negative sentiment in the market over the upcoming auction of gold
bullion by the Bank of England.
</P>
<P>
   On other markets, energy prices were mixed, and grain and
soybean futures prices were mostly lower.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in interest rates is an indication the Federal Reserve
is combating inflation, which makes the dollar strong and weakens
gold's appeal, according to analyst James Steel of Refco Inc.
</P>
<P>
   A strong dollar makes gold more expensive in non-dollar
economies, which is most of the world, driving demand lower because
those buying in rupees or yen will have to pay more because the
metal is sold in U.S. denominations.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to gold's selloff on the New York Mercantile Exchange is
the planned auction on Tuesday of 25 metric tons of gold by the
Bank of England. Because prices tend to weaken in the days leading
up to a gold auction and strengthen afterward, investors bailed out
the market, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The stronger dollar also weighed on silver prices, with the
weakness of gold also pushing silver futures lower.
</P>
<P>
   Gold for June delivery was $2.40 lower at $273.80 a troy ounce;
June silver was 10.5 cent lower at $5.016 a troy ounce.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's inventory report from the U.S. Department of Energy
sent crude oil futures prices lower on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department reported crude inventories rose 200,000
barrels last week, while gasoline stocks rose 1.7 million barrels
and distillates rose 300,000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
   The figures contradicted data released Tuesday by the American
Petroleum Institute, which reported crude oil stocks fell 2.234
million barrels, while gasoline rose 629,000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Natural gas futures prices rose 6.5 percent to reach a new,
three-year high as the market reacted to low storage inspections.
</P>
<P>
   The American Gas Association reported an injection of 46 billion
cubic feet last week, while the five-year average for the period is
71 billion cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   June light sweet crude was 41 cents lower at $29.32 a barrel;
June heating oil was .52 cent higher at 77.36 cents a gallon; June
unleaded gasoline was .33 cent lower at 97.98 cents a gallon; June
natural gas was 24.1 cents higher at $3.689 per 1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   Weather concerns sent soybean futures prices tumbling, while
grain futures prices were mixed on the Chicago Board of Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Corn futures prices, after falling at the start of trading,
ended the day unchanged, with the market having already factored in
forecasts of rain in the Midwest crop-growing area, according to
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   This week's rain and last week's precipitation has replenished
the top soil, which will allow the corn crop -- which is more than
90 percent planted -- to get off to a good start, according to
analyst Tim Hannagan of Alaron Trading Corp. The market is now
looking at long-term weather forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration has already
indicated that in the long term, conditions in the Midwest will be
drier and hotter than normal, which does not bode well for the corn
crop, Hannagan said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service 30- and 60-day forecast, expected
this week, will be looked at closely by traders to confirm those
fears, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Soybean futures prices fell in league with soybeans, although
the precipitation is not expected to affect the soybean crop, with
is about 55 percent planted, Hannagan said, adding the weather will
become a more important factor in crop development later in the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Precipitation in the hard red winter wheat belt this week eased
quality concerns in the market. The approach of the June wheat
harvest also weighed on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery was 4\ cents lower at $2.77 a bushel;
July corn was unchanged at $2.35{ a bushel; July oats were
unchanged at $1.19 a bushel; July soybeans were 2{ cents lower at
$5.41\ a bushel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
