<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-congressman says he's seeking GOP Senate nomination  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Ex-congressman Joseph DioGuardi said
Wednesday he is seeking the Republican nomination for U.S. Senate,
whether or not New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani decides to run.
</P>
<P>
   ''The longer we sit around waiting, the greater the chance that
(Hillary) Clinton will win by default,'' DioGuardi said.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to members of the Republican state committee and a
separate one to Gov. George Pataki, Dioguardi presented his
credentials as an anti-abortion, more-conservative alternative to
Giuliani. He criticized Giuliani for endorsing Democratic Gov.
Mario Cuomo in 1994, the mayor's close ties to state Liberal Party
head Raymond Harding and Giuliani for marching in Manhattan's ''gay
pride'' parade.
</P>
<P>
   ''If that isn't bad enough, the final insult is that Rudy
Giuliani is losing to Hillary Clinton, and our values are being
bartered not to purchase victory, but defeat,'' DioGuardi said.
</P>
<P>
   Polls generally show Giuliani and Clinton, formally given the
Democrats' Senate nomination Tuesday, running neck-and-neck.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Allen, a spokesman for state Republican Committee,
downplayed the impact of a DioGuardi candidacy among New York
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know who Joe DioGuardi is,'' Allen said. ''We are
nominating Mayor Giuliani on May 30th (in Buffalo). I don't know
where Joe DioGuardi is coming from and who he is talking to. ... We
plan on nominating him (Giuliani) barring any health considerations
on his part.''
</P>
<P>
   DioGuardi is already seeking the Conservative Party's Senate
nomination -- with the encouragement of Conservative boss Michael
Long -- and the Right-to-Life and Independence party lines.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has been pondering whether to stay in the Senate race
in light of his disclosure that he will need to undergo treatment
for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans have expressed an interest in running for the
GOP Senate nomination, including Reps. Rick Lazio and Peter King,
but only if Giuliani decides not to run.
</P>
<P>
   A decision by the mayor is expected any day. The Republicans'
nominating convention is May 30 in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   The 59-year-old DioGuardi, of Ossining in Westchester County,
was in Congress from 1985-89.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
