<HEADLINE> Senate Commends Million Mom March  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate voted Wednesday to commend last
weekend's Million Mom March and urge enactment of long-stalled gun
control legislation, capping an occasionally heated partisan debate
that belied the purely symbolic nature of the struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is strange that we find ourselves with such passion about
something that won't count,'' Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, a gun
control foe, said shortly before the 50-49 vote in favor of the
Democratic proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not substantive law. It is not intended to be. It is
intended to make a political point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they raised the issue on an unrelated spending
bill because Senate-passed gun control legislation, including
restrictions on sales at gun shows, has been stalled for months
without progress toward a compromise with the House. The Senate
last year approved the gun show restrictions, a requirement for the
sale of trigger locks and other gun measures as part of a bill to
crack down on juvenile crime.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a war at home and we have to have the courage to stand
up and say, 'enough is enough,' said Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif.,
''Let's commend the Million Mom March.''
</P>
<P>
   Apart from gun control, the issue brought long-simmering Senate
grievances to the surface in an institution where colleagues
customarily refer to one another as ''distinguished,'' or ''my good
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats accused Majority Leader Trent Lott of attempting
to run the Senate -- where unlimited debate is a proud tradition --
like the House of Representatives, where the rules strictly limit
what amendments can be proposed and how long lawmakers may speak.
</P>
<P>
   Several minutes later, the Mississippi Republican responded.
Looking toward Democrats a few feet away on the Senate floor, he
said he felt ''personally maligned ... and I don't appreciate it.
... I'm getting real tired of people questioning my commitment to
the Senate.'' He added it was the majority's responsibility to make
sure necessary legislation is passed.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Daschle, the Democratic leader, responded in equally
strong terms. ''The way the Senate is being run is wrong,'' he
said. ''No majority leader in history has attempted to constrain
debate as aggressively as Sen. Lott has chosen to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle added that Lott was ''trying to protect his members from
having to vote on tough issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic aides made no secret of their desire to make
Republicans vote on the issue of gun control.
</P>
<P>
   On the nonbinding vote, 43 Democrats and seven Republicans voted
in favor. Democratic Sen. Max Baucus of Montana joined 48
Republicans in opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The vote hinted at a modest shift in the GOP ranks. Sens. James
Jeffords of Vermont and William Roth of Delaware, both of whom are
seeking re-election this fall, sided with Democrats after opposing
the actual legislation a year ago. Sen. George Voinovich of Ohio,
who supported the legislation last year, opposed the Democratic
proposal on Wednesday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   The vote came moments after Republicans won approval for a
nonbinding proposal of their own. It accused the Clinton
administration of lax enforcement of the laws and failing to
''protect law-abiding citizens'' from gun violence. It, too, called
for passage of legislation dealing with juvenile crime, but did not
mention gun control provisions.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 69-30.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
