<HEADLINE> Tamil Tigers Shell Military  </HEADLINE>
By NEELESH MISRA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- Sri Lankan rebels shelled the military's
only airport in Jaffna Wednesday, threatening the supply line for
thousands of government troops.
</P>
<P>
   The international relief organization Doctors Without Borders
said it was planning to move its base out of Jaffna if large-scale
fighting breaks out in the city of 500,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, authorities blamed the rebels for a bombing Wednesday
that killed 19 and wounded at least 40 in the Sri Lanka town of
Batticaloa, 135 miles east of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
   The Tamil separatists, using 122 mm artillery that can hit
targets up to 10 miles away, hit Palali airport three times,
military officials reached by telephone said.
</P>
<P>
   There were no immediate reports of casualties or damage.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 40,000 government soldiers and support staff get
most of their supplies through the airport, built when Britain was
a colonial power in Sri Lanka, then called Ceylon.
</P>
<P>
   Palali has been under government control since 1983. But in
April 1995, the guerrillas shot down two Air Force Avro transport
planes, killing at least 100 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The insurgents on Tuesday resumed an assault on Jaffna, ending a
three-day lull in fighting, one of the few pauses since the
military's April 21 loss of the main causeway linking Jaffna
Peninsula to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Trujillo, the head of the French unit of Doctors Without
Borders, said by telephone that the organization was preparing to
shift about 60 civilian patients in Jaffna hospitals, to safer
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the United Nations Development Program moved
out some of its Jaffna staff, involved in clearing land mines,
saying it was no longer safe for them to work there.
</P>
<P>
   The minority Tamils claim they face discrimination from the
Sinhalese majority, which controls the government and the military.
They are fighting to establish a homeland in northern Sri Lanka for
the country's 3.2 million minority Tamils. The 17-year war has
killed more than 62,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels, formally known as the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, controlled Jaffna between 1990 and 1995, when they were
evicted by the Sri Lankan army after a 50-day war.
</P>
<P>
   During their five years of control of Jaffna, the separatists
set up their own Tamil administration for more than 1 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Sri Lankans celebrated the birth of Buddha
Wednesday by praying to end the country's ethnic war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
