<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NTSB: More Rest Stops for Trucks  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ZUCKERBROD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The National Transportation Safety Board, in
an effort to help truck drivers get more rest while on the road,
called Wednesday for an end to the ban on private development of
rest areas on some interstate highways.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB concluded there are not enough truck parking spaces
available in some parts of the country, especially near urban areas
and in parts of the Northeast and the South.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fatigue is one of the silent killers on our highways,'' said
NTSB Chairman Jim Hall, contending the parking space shortage has
forced drivers to park on highway shoulders or to keep driving when
they are tired, posing a risk to themselves and others.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB recommended that the Federal Highway Administration,
which is conducting its own study of the problem, ask Congress to
drop a federal ban on private development of rest areas on some
highways.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean private truck stops, commonly found near highway
exits, could potentially be built right on interstates.
</P>
<P>
   NATSO, an association that represents travel plazas and private
truck stops, opposes lifting the ban, Scot E. Imus, vice president
of government affairs, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   He said rest areas along interstate highways would keep truck
drivers from pulling off to visit the roughly 1,500 private truck
stops in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the long term, we'd go out of business,'' Imus said.
''There's no way we could compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Imus said his organization does not believe there is a shortage
of parking spaces. He said if there were, more private operators
would take advantage of the tight market.
</P>
<P>
   But the American Trucking Associations Inc., offered a different
viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a growing need for tens of thousands of parking
spaces,'' said Dave Osiecki, vice president of ATA safety and
operations.
</P>
<P>
   He said a lack of spaces makes it difficult for drivers to
comply with federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers currently can drive for no more than 10 consecutive
hours. Under rules proposed by the Department of Transportation,
drivers would be able to drive for 12 hours but would have to take
two, hour-long breaks or four, half-hour breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said federal and state governments have a responsibility to
help drivers comply with the law and to prevent accidents similar
to one that occurred in his home state of Tennessee last year.
</P>
<P>
   In that accident, five people were killed in a fiery wreck on
Interstate 40.
</P>
<P>
   A truck ran off I-40 and collided with three other trucks that
were parked on the entrance ramp to the highway from the public
rest area. In its report, the NTSB said the vehicles were parked on
the ramp, because the rest area was filled to capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB also recommended that the Federal Highway
Administration and other groups create a comprehensive guide for
truck drivers to inform them of parking areas and space
availability.
</P>
<P>
   The board did not make a recommendation concerning time limits
imposed on drivers at public rest stops in many states. It is
expected to issue a separate recommendation on that soon.
</P>
<P>
   Osiecki said the time limits force drivers to leave the areas
even when they are tired, or risk getting a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ''That puts a driver in a place where he has to make an
unfortunate choice,'' Osiecki said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
