<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Police have issued no tickets for truck ban on local roads  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Despite a state order to keep big trucks
off local roads and a new law creating fines for violators, no
tickets have been issued to enforce it.
</P>
<P>
   But State Police spokesman John Hagerty said Wednesday that
troopers have been briskly enforcing a wide array of truck
regulations, stopping and inspecting more than 300 trucks over four
months just on state Routes 31 and 29 leading north from Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   These stops resulted in 166 tickets and 34 cases in which
troopers seized control of the truck and had it impounded until
safety violations were corrected.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman in January signed a bill that sets fines
for drivers who take large trucks on roads that are not part of the
the National Truck Network.
</P>
<P>
   The action was taken after years of complaints from residents
and local officials along highways like Route 31 with heavy truck
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The Times of Trenton reported Wednesday that the State Police
had not issued a single summons to a wayward truck driver for being
on the wrong road since the law was enacted. Local police do not
have the authority to issue such tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Jayne O'Connor, a spokeswoman for the governor, said the truck
ban was being enforced and the lack of tickets was misleading.
</P>
<P>
   ''(The governor) has been assured that the enforcement is
happening. State Police are turning away trucks that violate the
ban,'' O'Connor said. ''The governor has been assured by the
attorney general that enforcement of the fines and penalties will
begin very soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Shatzkin, a spokesman for Attorney General John Farmer,
told the Times that some legal issues had to be worked out before
summonses could be issued and upheld in municipal court.
</P>
<P>
   Hagerty told The Associated Press that troopers have been
diligent in inspecting trucks and issuing summonses to improve
safety. However, he said there have been few instances in which
troopers have caught trucks of a certain size being found on roads
where they do not belong.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the 166 tickets issued on Routes 31 and 29 from January
to April, Hagerty said, ''These violations would probably have
included any oversized vehicles on the roadway, but our troopers
have inspected very few oversized vehicles, which is indicative
that the word (about the ban on local road travel) is getting
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The law carries stiff penalties: $400 for a first summons, with
fines of $700 to $1,000 for repeat offenders.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has returned to center stage since a video store clerk
was killed in Lambertville on Friday by a 20-ton garbage-hauling
truck that crashed into the store, prompting Mayor David Del
Vecchio to denounce the state's enforcement of the ban.
</P>
<P>
   ''This truck was coming from Massachusetts and going to
Pennsylvania. It had no business being on this road,'' Del Vecchio
told the Times in its Sunday editions.
</P>
<P>
   Charges have not yet been filed against the driver but
authorities said he lost control after running a traffic light in
an attempt to keep up with a caravan of trash trucks bound for a
Pennsylvania landfill.
</P>
<P>
   In Lambertville on Tuesday, where flowers had been placed at the
crash site, several residents and workers told the newspaper they
hadn't seen any decrease in local truck traffic since the ban was
put in place last summer and augmented with the penalties in
January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
