<HEADLINE> NYC Church Vandal Suspect Arrested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A suspect has been arrested in the vandalism of
statues at Roman Catholic churches and he told investigators he was
following orders from God, Police Commissioner Howard Safir said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''He told us that he believed that God had told him to do it --
that the Bible suggested to him that he should not worship graven
images,'' Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   Primus St. Croix, 34, allegedly led a group of a dozen followers
who helped him damage religious statues at Brooklyn churches. More
arrests are expected.
</P>
<P>
   St. Croix was arrested Tuesday after a tip was called to the
NYPD's Crime Stoppers, Safir said. St. Croix, who is Catholic,
confessed to taking part in five incidents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank DeRosa, spokesman for the Diocese of Brooklyn, said
parishioners were encouraged by the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ''The statues of Jesus, or of the Blessed Mother or the saints
are there to remind us how to live the Christian life -- there is no
idolatry involved,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   St. Croix faces several counts of criminal mischief and
aggravated harassment. He was to be arraigned late Wednesday. It
wasn't clear whether he had an attorney yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
