<DOCNO> APW20000517.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commerce Seeks Satellite Control  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BRISCOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Commerce Department wants to take back
control of U.S. satellite exports, which are dwindling rapidly
under strict State Department licensing that classifies them as
munitions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our experience in the past 14 months suggests that the changed
controls on satellite exports hurt the U.S. more than they hurt any
intended target,'' said Commerce Under Secretary William A. Reinsch
in testimony prepared for a Senate hearing Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Exports have declined 40 percent, from $1.06 billion in 1998 to
$637 million last year, the industry says, and the U.S. share of
the market has dropped from 73 percent to 52 percent for the last
three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department, which Congress gave final say over
satellite exports in March 1999, plans to issue new rules next week
to speed up exports to NATO countries and other allies, which
increasingly have been turning to European, Japanese and Russian
sources for satellites and related products.
</P>
<P>
   The law changing control of satellite exports was prompted by
concern that the technology could be used by Russia or China to
develop weapon systems or be transferred to hostile countries.
</P>
<P>
   But Reinsch and industry representatives say the whole idea of
classifying a $69 billion-a-year industry that provides TV
broadcasts, telephone service, Internet access and an increasing
array of commercial applications around the globe is misguided.
</P>
<P>
   ''The jurisdictional change has affected our foreign relations,
our national security and a broad range of U.S. industry,'' Reinsch
said in his testimony. No date was set for the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee hearing which he and other administration and
industry official gathered for Wednesday. It was called off due to
a backup of votes on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   John D. Holum, senior State Department adviser for arms control
and international security affairs, said in his testimony that the
department neither sought nor welcomed the change in jurisdiction
but has tried to make the best of it.
</P>
<P>
   He said special rules are being proposed to ''expedite satellite
related exports to U.S. friends and allies'' but no matter how
promptly licenses are handled, it will not be as fast as it was
when no licenses were required.
</P>
<P>
   New rules will allow four-year licenses covering multiple
shipments to any NATO or major no-NATO ally, including Australia,
New Zealand, Japan, Korea, Israel, Egypt, Jordan and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ''None of the special procedures will apply should the
transaction at any stage involve an activity beyond the territories
of U.S. allies, such as space launches from the People's Republic
of China or Russia,'' Holum said in his prepared testimony.
</P>
<P>
   All witnesses said they were concerned for national security and
for protecting against the leakage of weapons technology.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton Mowry, executive director of the Satellite Industry
Association, said the industry is committed to protecting U.S.
security.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that our national security is enhanced by having a
healthy and robust commercial satellite industry that can compete
on an equal footing in the international marketplace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The change in jurisdiction was prompted by congressional concern
over U.S. industry's involvement with China. A report by a special
House committee said valuable military technology flowed to China
by putting U.S.-built satellites into orbit on Chinese rockets.,
and the Clinton administration stopped one $450 million commercial
sale to China.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, the State Department accused Lockheed Martin
Corp. of illegally giving a conglomerate owned partly by the
Chinese government a scientific assessment designed to improve a
flawed Chinese-made satellite motor, threatening a $15 million
fine. Lockheed denied it had violated export laws.
</P>
<P>
   John J. Hamre, a former deputy defense secretary who now heads
the Center for Strategic and International Studies, a private
defense think tank, said putting State Department restrictions on
satellite exports was ''analogous to saying that since a burglar
broke into one person's garage, we now must move the entire
neighborhood to a new location.''
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a sharp loss in U.S. space exports and a
threat to U.S. technological leadership in a critical era, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
