<HEADLINE> Time Names New Real Simple Editor  </HEADLINE>
By SETH SUTEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Time Inc. has replaced the editor of Real
Simple, a new lifestyle magazine for women, just two issues after
the magazine launched.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Wyland, a former editor of Martha Stewart Living, had
developed the idea for the magazine over a two-year period at Time
Inc. and saw the publication through its launch in April.
</P>
<P>
   But reports of internal friction between Wyland and other senior
staff as well as a lukewarm reception from advertisers overshadowed
what the company called a strong reader response to the magazine's
first two issues.
</P>
<P>
   Time Inc. spokesman Peter Costiglio said Wednesday that it was
not clear whether Wyland would remain with the company. Wyland did
not return a call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Pearlstine, the top editorial executive at Time Inc.,
announced that Carrie Tuhy, the assistant editor at InSyle, would
take over as editor of Real Simple. Isolde Motley, who had been
editor of the recently closed Life magazine, will supervise Tuhy in
her new post as corporate editor for all of Time Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Pearlstine praised Wyland's efforts, saying the
magazine has had one of the highest response rates from readers by
a Time Inc. magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ''The underlying concept of the magazine has been validated,''
he said, adding that he hoped the new editors would ''build on the
momentum Real Simple has already achieved in the marketplace and
bring it to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Simple promised women in their 30s and 40s help with
stripping away clutter from their lives, offering tips on easy
meals to cook, basic personal finance advice, dieting and exercise.
But media critics as well as advertisers were not impressed with
the initial results.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think advertisers were disappointed with the execution, but
they are glad that Time Inc. is moving quickly to remedy the
situation,'' said Roberta Garfinkle, who buys print ads for
McCann-Erickson Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The abrupt change marked an unusual setback for Time Inc.'s
People magazine group, which has had a string of successful
magazine launches, including InStyle, Teen People and People en
Espanol.
</P>
<P>
   The People group had $942 million in ad revenues last year, a
significant portion of the $3.5 billion figure for all of Time
Inc., according to the Publishers Information Bureau. Time Inc.
publishes more than 20 magazines including Time, Fortune, Sports
Illustrated, Money and Entertainment Weekly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
