<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Holbrooke: Deploy Troops To Congo  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The head of a Security Council mission to
the Congo urged the United Nations on Wednesday to immediately
deploy U.N. observers to the northern city of Kisangani or risk
another flare-up in fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dates like July will not work for Kisangani,'' U.S. Ambassador
Richard Holbrooke said in calling for the ahead of schedule
deployment within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He was briefing the Security Council on his recent visit to
Congo with a council delegation. The trip resulted in an agreement
between Rwanda and Uganda to withdraw their forces and allow the
United Nations to take control of the divided northern city.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda support rival groups of Congolese rebels who
took up arms in August 1998 to oust Congolese President Laurent
Kabila, but all sides have since signed a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Rwandan and Ugandan armies clashed last week in Congo's
third-largest city when the Ugandans tried to introduce large
numbers of reinforcements and expel Rwandan units, according to the
Rwandan army and U.N. military observers.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Lt. Col. Akram Hossein, head of the small U.N.
team in Kisangani, said it would be at least July before the first
group of U.N. soldiers from the U.N. Observer Mission for Congo,
known as MONUC, lands in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said that was not soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''Time is essential,'' Holbrooke said. ''It is vitally important
that the forces from MONUC that will go to Kisangani get there
ahead of the initial deployment schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ''Otherwise the risks of war beginning again are very
substantial,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard, when asked about Holbrooke's
appeal, said he believed it would be possible to put Kisangani at
the top of the deployment list but that it still might not be
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not entirely in our hands. It does have to do with how
quickly governments would make their troops available,'' Eckhard
said.
</P>
<P>
   Several ambassadors, including French Ambassador Jean-David
Levitte, asked the peacekeeping department for a quick study of
what money and equipment would be needed to allow for the extra
deployment now envisaged for Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council has authorized a 5,537-strong force for the
Congo to monitor a cease-fire reaffirmed by the warring sides April
8. Deployment -- already held up because of security conditions --
has also been threatened by the outbreak of violence in Sierra
Leone, where 350 U.N. peacekeepers remain detained by rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every ambassador at the council meeting said the events
in Sierra Leone, while dramatic, shouldn't overshadow Congo.
</P>
<P>
   ''The needs of the Congo cannot wait for other problems
elsewhere to be solved,'' said British Ambassador Jeremy
Greenstock.
</P>
<P>
   But Canadian Ambassador Robert Fowler said the violence in
Sierra Leone underscored the precariousness of the Congo mission as
currently planned. Canada has consistently complained that the
Congo force is too small and its mandate too narrow to take on the
challenges that Congo presents.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials have privately criticized Canada's insistence
that the force be larger and given a broader mandate to ensure
compliance with human rights and humanitarian law, noting that
Canada hasn't committed troops for the mission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
