<HEADLINE> Santa Fe Lab Helps Los Alamos  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD BENKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- When fire closed Los Alamos National
Laboratory on May 8, scientists quickly lined up an alternative
laptop lab in exile.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Fe Institute, a think tank down the hill from Los
Alamos, has provided computer links with the lab and a kind of home
away from home for researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The lab remained closed Wednesday as the Cerro Grande Fire
continued to grow. And while most Los Alamos residents have been
allowed back home, no date for a lab reopening has been announced.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists started taking advantage of the Santa Fe Institute
offer last Friday, SFI researcher Erica Jen said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Los Alamos has been so important to the institute and the
general area, we really wanted to help in any way we could,'' said
Jen, a research professor at Santa Fe Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've provided them with the use of our machines so they can
get access to the lab,'' said Tim Carlson, director of computing
for the institute.
</P>
<P>
   The institute has long been a forum for the exchange of new
scientific ideas and a center for computer simulation.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson estimated 10 to 15 Los Alamos scientists are now working
at SFI. The Institute has provided computer hardware, software,
work stations -- even lunch, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some of them have brought their own laptops. We have put those
laptops on our networks,'' Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They can get into the unclassified lab computers from here,''
he added. ''Of course, you cannot get to the classified
computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say their laptops have allowed them to stay in touch
via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Wojciech Zurek, a Los Alamos researcher in quantum mechanics,
said he has been working on his laptop and his home computer, where
he has copied much of his recent work ''since I don't do any
classified work.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it's now on his laptop, Zurek knows his data is safe. He
also is optimistic that data left at the lab is safe.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Macken, a theoretical biologist, said she, too, has
been working at SFI.
</P>
<P>
   Working at SFI and at home has been productive, she said, but
not being able to meet personally with colleagues on projects has
hampered some of her research.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Frauenfelder, director of nonlinear studies at Los Alamos,
said his department's 20th annual conference also may have to find
an alternative location, but he hopes the lab will be open by the
conference's scheduled starting date of June 5.
</P>
<P>
   Because this year's conference is the 20th, he said, it was
decided to include all fields covered by his department.
</P>
<P>
   ''That includes black holes and cosmology and goes all the way
to the brain. We are having first-rate people in all of these
fields,'' he said, and they're all already invited, so cancellation
was not really an option.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
