<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists Blast Army Corps' Plan  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A panel of economists criticized the Army
Corps of Engineers' handling of a study that has prompted
allegations that top agency officials manufactured a case for
costly construction on the upper Mississippi and Illinois rivers.
</P>
<P>
   The economists' report, funded by the McKnight Foundation, the
Joyce Foundation and Environmental Defense, is being released by
the Northeast-Midwest Institute on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The economists reviewed the corps' 7-year, $54 million study
that aims to balance the economic benefits of expanding barge locks
on the rivers with the financial and environmental costs.
</P>
<P>
   The new review, based on public documents as well as those
provided by the corps, shipping interests and environmental groups,
was begun months before corps economist Donald Sweeney filed a
sworn affidavit that his superiors altered data and his original
conclusions to justify massive construction. Sweeney's charges
resulted in several pending investigations by the Army inspector
general, the National Academy of Sciences and some in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The panel said it did not attempt to conclude whether the corps
study had been rigged.
</P>
<P>
   But the economists did criticize the corps for not
comprehensively studying what the value of a crucial component of
its economic model should be.
</P>
<P>
   Without such extensive analysis, the variable value ultimately
chosen -- which accounts for shippers switching to alternative
transportation as barge costs rise -- ''seems at best to be
arbitrary and at worst possibly chosen to justify the project,''
they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The central charge in Sweeney's filing was that corps brass
ordered that variable lowered to make the $1 billion cost of
doubling the length of seven locks on the upper Mississippi and
Illinois rivers appear warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Corps officials have repeatedly denied wrongdoing, saying new
data -- not foul play -- caused the study to change.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Ron Fournier, a corps spokesman in the Rock
Island, Ill., district that is overseeing the study, said corps
economists had not had time to examine the new report. If they
determine it is based on ''solid data, instead of fear or emotion''
it is likely many of its criticisms would be addressed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not something that comes as any great concern to us,''
Fournier said.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of a years-long, fierce debate, the corps study is
expected to be finished this year. Its initial, unofficial
conclusion favors the seven-lock proposal, the most extensive still
on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Shipping interests say massive lock expansions are crucial to
keeping transportation costs low as grain exports -- and thus barge
traffic -- rise. Otherwise, they say, Midwestern products will not
be able to compete on the global market.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists argue that river's fragile ecosystem would be
further endangered by more large-scale changes.
</P>
<P>
   The panel said the study employs overly simplistic analysis,
uses faulty assumptions and ignores key factors.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to grade the corps' effort, Yale University's Steven Berry
and Charles Leven of Washington University called it ''inadequate
for the purpose.'' The panel's third member, Geoffrey Hewings of
the University of Illinois, was unavailable for the Wednesday
conference call.
</P>
<P>
   ''At best, parts are a nice try -- but not well executed,'' Leven
said. ''Other parts are just wrong, and still other parts just
aren't there.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Army Corps:
http://www.mvr.usace.army.mil/pdw/nav--study.htm
</P>
<P>
   Environmental Defense:
http://www.edf.org/programs/Ecosystems/mississippi
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1855 </TRAILER>
