<HEADLINE> Likely Domincan Winner Speaks  </HEADLINE>
By ISMAEL TORRES
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- On the verge of winning
the Dominican presidency, opposition leader Hipolito Mejia on
Wednesday credited his grass-roots base for drawing out the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''We looked for votes everywhere,'' the former tobacco farmer
said triumphantly -- even though he had yet to receive the simple
majority needed to avoid a runoff on June 30. ''I looked under
rocks, under a shrub, under a yucca tree and a the stump of a
plantain tree.''
</P>
<P>
   It was vintage Mejia, who has won many hearts by once
proclaiming ''I'm no jerk!'' and distancing himself from a
political establishment many believe is more concerned with
statistics than people.
</P>
<P>
   Mejia's informality delighted voters who, weary with the
seemingly aloof leadership, wanted more attention for ordinary
people struggling to live on an average of $2,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   While Mejia, 59, comes from the Dominican Republic's
light-skinned, landowning elite, he belongs to the left-leaning
Revolutionary Party that commands the strongest following in this
Caribbean nation of 8 million.
</P>
<P>
   He has promised to spend more on social programs and
community-level public works projects. And while he offers no
overreaching changes in economic policy, businessmen fear he'll
take money from much-needed infrastructure investments to make good
on his promises.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I promised, I will do,'' he said Wednesday. ''I will not
be a person who will be frustration for this society.''
</P>
<P>
   Mejia was born near Santiago in Gurabo, and studied at the
Polytechnic Institute in San Cristobal. He finished his studies in
tobacco production at the University of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, he was director of the Dominican Tobacco Institute, and
later worked for various private firms. In 1970, he was president
of the National Professional Farmers Association, and served as
agriculture secretary from 1978-82 under President Antonio Guzman.
</P>
<P>
   Married with four children, Mejia has been his party's vice
president for years but never held elected office.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, he was the vice presidential running mate of the
legendary Jose Francisco Pena Gomez -- a black shunned by most of
the white elite and widely believed to have lost the 1994 election
to fraud. Pena Gomez died in 1998, after three unsuccessful tries
for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Mejia and his vice presidential running mate, Milagros Ortiz
Bosch, visited Pena Gomez's grave Wednesday morning. They held
their hands over the tomb, and Mejia addressed his old friend:
''Pena, these hands will be used for the good of the people. They
will not be stained by robbery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1858 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Fire Season on the Move  </HEADLINE>
By DAN GALLAGHER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- While the Southwest is suffering through
dramatic blazes, the fire season is making its normal annual
migration from Florida to the Pacific Northwest, say experts at the
nation's fire suppression center.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this year's track record depends on whether summer
storms also pack moisture to douse the multitude of lightning
strikes flickering into the trees and brush.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the wild cards in the fire season is dry lightning,''
said Rick Ochoa, a National Weather Service meteorologist working
in tandem with Boise's National Interagency Fire Center. ''How much
will you get? It's difficult to project in advance.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal facility on Wednesday reported 10 large fires in the
Southwest and South, including the 47,000-acre prescribed fire that
roared out of control into Los Alamos, N.M. Firefighters also are
contending with a 13,000-acre fire on the northern rim of the Grand
Canyon which started as a 1,500-acre prescribed burn.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, 38,821 fires have blackened 928,945 acres
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Fire weather usually starts in Florida in February, then moves
across the South, reaching Texas and the Southwest in May, said
Mike Apicello, Forest Service public affairs officer at NIFC.
</P>
<P>
   Monsoons in the Southwest may douse fires there, but they
usually do not appear on the horizon for another 1{ months, Ochoa
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the days are long in Alaska, fire crews start scrambling.
</P>
<P>
   The danger of wildfires has eased since the National Weather
Service issued a one-day ''red flag warning'' last week for
wildfires in southcentral Alaska. The interior, however, is
beginning to dry out, said Bill Beebe, coastal regional fire
management officer for the Division of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
   The most dangerous time for wildfires is the period after snow
melts and before new grass grows, when low humidity and winds can
quickly dry out dead grasses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California, which only went off the official fire
season in February, has the potential for a ''somewhat worse than
normal'' fire cycle ahead, Forest Service spokesman Matt Mathies
said. California spent a record $145 million on blazes on private
and state lands last year, and the final tally is not finished yet.
</P>
<P>
   The fire spotlight then moves into southern Utah, western
Colorado, Wyoming and central and eastern Montana. Ochoa said those
areas are dry this year. Later in the summer, the northern Rockies
and Pacific Northwest start to burn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
