<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NTSB: Warn Airlines on Material  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ZUCKERBROD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The National Transportation Safety Board on
Wednesday recommended that the Federal Aviation Administration
advise airline carriers about the dangers of transporting hydrogen
peroxide, a hazardous material that could cause a fire.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB issued its safety recommendations in response to a
hydrogen peroxide spill aboard a Northwest Airlines passenger
flight on Oct. 28, 1998, from Orlando, Fla., to Memphis, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   The solution leaked from two undeclared plastic containers in
the plane's cargo compartment. The chemical spill was not
discovered until the cargo handlers in Memphis began unloading the
bags.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB reported that the handlers thought it was water and
sent contaminated bags to other destinations. They realized a
caustic chemical had spilled when about a dozen people had to be
treated for exposure.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, a bag that originally was on the Northwest flight
was discovered smoldering in an airplane cargo compartment. One
person was treated there. None of the injuries were serious.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB concluded that the passenger failed to properly package
and identify the hazardous material, and the airline did not ask
enough questions about the cooler she put on the plane. The FAA
bans passengers from bringing hazardous materials onto airliners.
</P>
<P>
   The board recommended that the FAA develop and distribute to
carriers guidance about the difficulty of identifying a hydrogen
peroxide spill and the danger of allowing hydrogen peroxide to dry
on organic materials, which could cause fire.
</P>
<P>
   The board also wants the FAA to issue guidance to carriers about
the need to isolate bags that have been involved in a hazardous
material spill and make sure they are not put on another flight.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important to promptly identify any hazardous material ...
before allowing passenger baggage or cargo to be distributed to
other aircraft,'' said Robert J. Chipkevich, director of the NTSB
Office of Pipeline and Hazardous Materials Safety.
</P>
<P>
   The NTSB also is urging the FAA to issue guidance to airlines
about the need to notify pilots when cargo involved in a hazardous
material spill is on board a plane.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe it's important, whenever hazardous material is on
board an airplane, that the pilot is aware of what the material is
and what hazards it poses,'' Chipkevich said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
