<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With attention on Democrats, Republicans target voters and wait  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The other side's ticket features the
Energizer Bunny of campaign spending up against a vilified former
governor with a $2.8 billion tax increase on his resume.
</P>
<P>
   Polls say more than half of likely voters don't know the
Republican U.S. Senate candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But with attention now mainly on the Democratic primary,
Republicans say that only helps June's winner in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whoever our candidate is, I think the guy is going to do very
well because the other two guys on the other side are beating each
other up,'' said Republican State Committee Chairman Garabed
''Chuck'' Haytaian.
</P>
<P>
   ''When all is said and done, we don't have to do a whole lot of
opposition research on those guys. They'll have done it for us,''
Haytaian said.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Corzine is spending more than a million dollars a week on
glossy network television ads to convince Democrats to choose him
over former governor Jim Florio.
</P>
<P>
   Big numbers make big news in that campaign: Corzine's estimated
$400 million personal bankroll and the apparent will to spend it;
Florio's billion-dollar tax increase and the defiant defense of his
action.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans have numbers of their own.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. William L. Gormley, R-Atlantic; Essex County
Executive Jim Treffinger; U.S. Rep. Bob Franks, R-7th; and college
professor Murray Sabrin are likely to draw an estimated 250,000
voters, say campaign staffers and political analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate with around 40 percent -- in some views that's as
little as 90,000 votes -- gets to challenge the Democratic survivor.
</P>
<P>
   So while Corzine spends to boost name recognition and Florio
fights the ghosts of his past, Republican candidates target
Republican voters with selected mailings and limited television
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ''There really are two different games being played,'' said
Charlie Smith, a spokesman for the Franks campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our audience is different. The Republican campaign is not
being overshadowed by the Democratic campaign by distracting
Republican voters,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   News agencies are following the Democrats for a number of
reasons, said David Murray, a spokesman for Gormley's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And, Murray said, it's not just Corzine's money.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is much easier to follow a campaign between two rather than
four,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Florio is ''known by about 99 percent of New Jerseyans'' while
Corzine spends to promote programs the state's ''centrists voters''
won't find appealing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   All of that adds to the Republican advantage, Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe Jon Corzine is spending a small fortune to define
himself as far too much to the left to be acceptable to a very
central state,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   But the talk of Corzine's cash could further lull voters, said
political analyst and Rider University professor David Rebovich.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is almost a mindset in the state that this is a guy that
will spend twice as much in the general campaign,'' Rebovich said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a former governor can't beat him, what can four
lesser-known guys do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another apparent mark against the Republican candidates is the
fact that Gov. Christie Whitman first appeared to run, then backed
out.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately they have the look of second-string about
them,'' Rebovich said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
