<HEADLINE> Authorities Lookout for Schlichter  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS SUNDHEIM
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Federal marshals are fanning out across the
Midwest looking for Art Schlichter, the former Indianapolis Colts
and Ohio State quarterback whose gambling problems ended his NFL
career and led to years of legal troubles.
</P>
<P>
   At least a dozen marshals are mounting an intense effort to find
Schlichter after learning he recently tried to obtain a handgun
from a friend, authorities said. Police in Grove City, Ohio, a
suburb of Columbus, are also seeking Schlichter on a felony charge
of using someone else's credit card to try to obtain cash.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities Monday charged Schlichter, 40, with money
laundering. Prosecutors say he accepted advance payments for
tickets to sporting events he could not obtain, then tried to repay
the money by making unauthorized charges on his father's credit
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Schlichter was accused of driving a car at a
motorcycle police officer after a routine traffic stop in Columbus.
He also is free on bond on charges of illegal gambling while he was
in prison recently in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   Schlichter also is wanted for violating his probation. He had
been ordered to make daily visits to Hoch Correctional Consultants
and Services in Indianapolis but has not been seen since April 28.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities have made the hunt for Schlichter ''a major
case,'' meaning it will get extra manpower and other resources if
need be, Deputy U.S. Marshal Mark Robinett said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It's not known if Schlichter is armed, but agents are proceeding
cautiously. Investigators believe he has left the Indianapolis
area, Robinett said.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents filed this week shed additional light on
allegations that Schlichter swindled money from an Indianapolis
physician.
</P>
<P>
   Schlichter approached the doctor in September with an investment
scheme to buy tickets to sporting events, then sell them at a
profit. She gave him more than $100,000, according to an affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   On several occasions, Schlichter used the threat of media
exposure to get the woman to give him more money, but he never
obtained the tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The woman later had to turn to her father to pay debts that
arose from the payments to Schlichter. Her father -- also a doctor --
asked Schlichter to repay $45,000, the affidavit said.
</P>
<P>
   Schlichter said he could make payments with credit cards that
were in his father's name. He demanded that the woman's father make
charges on the credit cards from his business. Some of the money
from the credit charges was repaid to the woman's father, some went
in cash to Schlichter.
</P>
<P>
   In early February, authorities said, Schlichter also contacted a
sports-related business and offered to sell it tickets to the NCAA
Final Four. The Sports Corp. in Indianapolis gave him $6,000 for
tickets that Schlichter never obtained. Schlichter later said he
could repay the money with a $15,000 charge to his father's credit
cards if the business would return $8,100 in cash to him.
</P>
<P>
   Schlichter's father, John ''Max'' Schlichter, told an IRS
investigator last month that he never authorized his son to use the
credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Wednesday at his Columbus, Ohio, home, the elder
Schlichter declined to comment on the case against his son.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted on the federal charges, Art Schlichter faces up to
20 years in prison. He faces five years on the Ohio felony charge.
</P>
<P>
   Schlichter, a first-round draft pick by the then-Baltimore Colts
in 1982, was suspended by the NFL in 1983 when it was learned that
bookies threatened him over $150,000 in gambling debts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Schlichter returned to the Colts, who by then had
relocated to Indianapolis. He was released following the 1985
season.
</P>
<P>
   Schlichter was freed from an Indiana prison last September after
serving less than half of a four-year sentence on charges of theft,
forgery and fraud in connection with the theft of $800,000 to
support his gambling habit.
</P>
<P>
   Since his release, he has been charged with using the Indiana
prison's pay phones to bet on football and hockey games.
</P>
<P>
   Before beginning his Indiana prison term, Schlichter served a
federal sentence in Kentucky for a probation violation. He
surrendered to Indiana authorities on Jan. 26, 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
