<HEADLINE> Bonds Fall on Inflation Worries  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices slipped Wednesday, amid expectations
that the Federal Reserve hasn't finished raising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 10-year Treasury note fell { point,
or $5.00 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction, rose to 6.49 percent from 6.42 percent late
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year Treasury bond fell 1 1/16 points with the yield
rising to 6.18 percent from 6.10 percent a day earlier, according
to Bridge Telerate news service.
</P>
<P>
   Traders are worried the Federal Reserve, which has raised
short-term rates six times since June 1999, will raise them again
in an effort to contain inflation.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the central bank raised rates by one-half percentage
point and said it remained worried about the risk of rising
inflation. The five previous rate hikes had each been a more
moderate one-quarter point.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates reduce the value of investments that pay a
fixed rate of return, such as bonds.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading Tuesday, short-term Treasury securities fell
1/16 to 3/32 point, while intermediate maturities ranged from
declines of [ point to { point.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 6.03 percent while
the discount rate was 5.87 percent, down 0.15 percentage point from
Tuesday. Yields are the interest bills pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   Six-month yields finished at 6.41 percent with a discount of
6.14 percent, falling 0.09 percentage point from Tuesday. One-year
yields settled at 6.34 percent with a discount of 6.03 percent,
falling 0.01 percentage point from late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, rose to 6 percent from 5.75 percent late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 3/16 point to 92 1/16. The average
yield to maturity rose to 6.22 percent from 6.21 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
