<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bombing Rebuilt Rights Movement  </HEADLINE>
By KENDAL WEAVER
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- In the basement of the Sixteenth Street
Baptist Church, the four black girls in white dresses were getting
ready for the main Youth Day service. As it would be recounted
later, the last conversation of their lives was on their
Sunday-school class topic: ''The Love That Forgives.''
</P>
<P>
   For many in the generation of the civil rights era, the dynamite
explosion that killed the four girls at the church in downtown
Birmingham on Sept. 15, 1963, was a turning point -- an act of
segregationist violence that made the struggle for equal rights a
national cause.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was mind-boggling in its depravity,'' said Taylor Branch,
author of a history of the civil rights period. ''Bombing churches
while girls are getting ready to go to Sunday school was
unspeakably evil.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It made some people stand up and speak out against racial
hatred and violence and segregation,'' said Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga.,
who was in Alabama and went to the scene of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw the devastation. I remained for the funerals,'' he said.
''More than anything else, I think it created a sense of righteous
indignation.''
</P>
<P>
   It also expanded the movement. Lewis said voting rights
demonstrations in Selma and elsewhere, culminating in passage of
the Voting Rights Act of 1965, were a product of the church
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Selma was conceived as an answer to this crime,'' said Branch.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing came after months of protests in Birmingham,
including children's demonstrations as segregationists sought to
keep blacks out of schools and public places.
</P>
<P>
   ''Children had been so vitally a part of those demonstrations,
and the church bombed was the church they marched out of,'' said
Branch. ''It was chilling, a brutal attack on the very place where
the movement came of age, nationally really.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the bombers were seeking to intimidate the movement, the
crime did just the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think tragedy always moves good people to make a
commitment,'' said the Rev. Fred Shuttlesworth, a leader of the
demonstrations in Birmingham in the 1960s and now a pastor in
Cincinnati. ''It's unfortunate that it's like that, but it does.''
</P>
<P>
   The church was not the headquarters of the movement, said
Shuttlesworth, but it was ideally located downtown as the site
where demonstrators could gather for mass protests. Today it is
something of a shrine of the movement, located across the street
from the Birmingham Civil Rights Institute and memorials to the
black children and others who survived snarling police dogs and
fire hoses -- and bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttlesworth, whose home was bombed twice, said the jailing
Wednesday of two former Ku Klux Klansmen in the 1963 church bombing
is good for the families of the victims and the many others who
suffered in a reign of Klan violence in Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   ''It brings some relief,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttlesworth said the deaths of the girls showed the extent of
the danger for those involved. But, he said, ''we already had made
a commitment: No matter what happened, we would struggle on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1916 </TRAILER>
