<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Knocks Bush on Social Security  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Al Gore told 10,000 senior citizens
Wednesday that ''we could see the end of Social Security as we know
it'' under George W. Bush's plan to allow private investment of
government retirement funds.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, campaigning a continent away in Washington state, accused
his Democratic presidential rival of being ''mired in the past''
while Bush leads by proposing changes to ensure Social Security's
future.
</P>
<P>
   Gore addressed a big AARP convention, campaigning for Florida's
25 electoral votes and support from senior citizens nationwide. He
quoted from Bush's news conference on Tuesday to argue that the
Republican has moved onto dangerous ground with his proposal -- not
entirely fleshed out in specifics -- to allow Americans to invest
some of their Social Security taxes in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   In that news conference in Oregon, Bush, the Texas governor,
said it was ''conceivable'' that a worker taking advantage of the
investment accounts would get a lower guaranteed benefit from
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said, and I quote word for word, 'That's all up for
discussion,''' Gore told AARP members at their biennial convention.
Some of them groaned.
</P>
<P>
   ''With all due respect, I don't think your retirement security
should be up for discussion,'' Gore added.
</P>
<P>
   The senior citizens applauded.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had also said it was possible workers would eventually be
allowed to invest their entire Social Security tax, not just a
portion.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the group he ''could scarcely believe it'' when he
read those comments. ''Governor Bush said that what he really
envisioned was -- and I'm quoting again here -- 'a system where
personal savings accounts are the predominant part -- a completely
different world.'''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president added that because Bush could not guarantee a
minimum benefit, ''In his 'completely different world' -- in his
phrase -- we could see the end of Social Security as we know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has alternately proposed using budget surpluses to infuse
the Social Security Trust Fund with revenues for the baby boom's
retirement. He would also improve benefits for widows and
homemakers at an estimated cost of $100 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Washington state, Bush told reporters Wednesday:
''My job as the president is to assure Congress that I will spend
the capital necessary to get something done and lay out the
framework for reforms. This is an issue that shows the vice
president is mired in the past and my campaign is willing to think
about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, just before Gore spoke in a cavernous hall to the
AARP, a local official, Orange County Chairman Mel Martinez, called
reporters to a side room and said Gore should ''stop spreading fear
and panic'' on Social Security -- now the centerpiece issue of the
Bush-Gore contest.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe candidate Al Gore came to the AARP convention to
scare his way to the White House,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   But at the convention, Republicans, Democrats and independents
alike seemed cold to Bush's proposed change in the Social Security
system.
</P>
<P>
   ''It puts it at risk,'' said Mary Ann Van Oostendorp, 63, a
Republican postal worker from Woodbridge, N.J. ''True it's a bull
market. ...''
</P>
<P>
   ''Not right now. It's up and down, up and down. It's scary,''
interrupted her retired husband, Bart, an independent. ''That's
scary. It's been guaranteed since Roosevelt.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Steiman, 77, from Orlando, said, ''The way the market is
going, I don't want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting that this campaign could create a generational
schism, Van Oostendorp, who said he is leaning toward Gore solely
on the Social Security issue, worried that younger workers could be
drawn to Bush's plan. ''Those who made a killing (on the stock
market) are going to say it's a good plan! It's a good plan!''
</P>
<P>
   Beaming from a front row at the Orange County Convention Center
was Gore's 87-year-old mother, Pauline. She flew here aboard Air
Force Two from her granddaughter's law school graduation in New
York Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The plane made a detour through Nashville, Tenn., en route back
to Washington, where Gore and his wife were to celebrate their 30th
wedding anniversary with a long weekend at home, so that Gore could
give his mother a ride home and meet with his media crew filming
campaign footage.
</P>
<P>
   Horace Deets, executive director of the 34-million-member AARP,
said Bush declined invitations to speak at Wednesday's convention,
as well as forums earlier this year in Iowa, New Hampshire, South
Carolina and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- AP Writer Mike Schneider contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1925 </TRAILER>
