<HEADLINE> Haitians, Reporters Rescued At Sea  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- A U.S. Coast Guard ship rescued 44
illegal Haitian migrants and two U.S. free-lance journalists from a
sinking sailboat off Haiti, the Coast Guard said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The crew of the Coast Guard cutter Forward spotted the 35-foot
sailboat slowly sinking late Sunday in international waters about
20 miles northwest of Haiti, the Coast Guard said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   A Coast Guard team boarded the vessel and determined it was
unseaworthy. The Coast Guard ship took all 46 people northward to
Great Inagua Island in the Bahamas, arriving early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 44 Haitians were being transferred to Nassau, the Bahamian
capital, on Wednesday, said William Nottage, Bahamian
superintendent of immigration. They were to be interviewed, and the
government will decide whether they will be repatriated, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two journalists left on their own to return home, Nottage
said.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Mathis, a spokeswoman for The New York Times, said the
free-lancers, writer Michael Finkel, and a photographer, were
working on an article for The New York Times Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Bahamian officials identified the photographer as Christopher
Anderson, but Mathis said she was not sure of his name or where the
journalists are based.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were on assignment for The New York Times Magazine, but I
don't have any further details,'' Mathis said.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, thousands of Haitians attempt illegal boat trips to
the United States, crammed into rickety boats. Last month, 288
Haitians were rescued when their boat ran aground in the Bahamas,
and rescuers found two dead. Survivors said as many as 17 died.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have complained of a surge in the number of Haitian
migrants as the country readies itself for long-delayed elections
on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
