<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jackson St. Track on Probation  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY R. BROWN
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- The men's cross country and track and
field programs at Jackson State were placed on five years'
probation by the NCAA for numerous violations dating to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The punishment, which limits athletic grants and makes the
school ineligible for postseason championships for two years, was
announced Wednesday by the NCAA Committee on Infractions.
</P>
<P>
   Committee chairman Jack Friedenthal said in a teleconference
that Jackson State was slapped with stiff penalties because the
historically black institution had similar violations in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ''A number of international athletes received cash for living
expenses. A number of athletes competed while ineligible. The head
coach was found to be engaged in unreasonable conduct,''
Friedenthal said. ''As a result of all of this, the university was
found to lack institutional control.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA made Jackson State ineligible for postseason
competition for the 2001-02 season. The school already imposed a
sanction, making itself ineligible for postseason competition in
2000 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The committee limited Jackson State to no more than nine
grants-in-aid in men's cross country and track during the current
year, 10 during the following season, and 11 beginning in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The school already had imposed a cut in scholarships for the
program. A total of six scholarships will be cut through 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Among the violations, Jackson State athletes used the names of
teammates in order to get around eligibility problems and
participate in track and cross country, the NCAA said.
</P>
<P>
   Former coach Willie McCoy was found to have provided cash,
ranging from $200 to $500, to seven international student-athletes
to pay for meals during holiday periods.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy, who retired in July, distributed $7,320 of university
money from 1995-99 to cover room and board for team members
ineligible to receive it, the committee said.
</P>
<P>
   During a two-year period ending in 1997, McCoy provided cash to
three international student-athletes in small amounts to pay for
the cost of laundry, long-distance telephone calls, transportation
and other items, the NCAA said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the NCAA, former Jackson State athletic director
Paul Covington approved the payments.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I signed off for that, that was a terrible oversight on my
part,'' Covington, who retired last spring, said after an
investigation began into the violations.
</P>
<P>
   Several international athletes were also given impermissible
housing benefits and participated in out-of-season practices,
according to the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy's lack of experience may have been the reason for some of
the violations, Friedenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   ''On the whole, especially since we were dealing with a
first-year coach that really didn't have any experience ... there
was a lot of stuff done from the goodness of the heart,'' he said.
''Many of the things, like the payment of the funds to help
student-athletes during Christmas vacation, he just didn't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Freidenthal, however, didn't cut the school any slack.
</P>
<P>
   He said Jackson State did not exercise control over the programs
and NCAA officials will visit the university periodically to see if
things have improved.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson State will have to prepare an annual progress report for
the NCAA as part of the probation.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is standard procedure for violations for any schools,''
Friedenthal said. ''The enforcement staff will take the time needed
to look at their report and verify that it is accurate. The purpose
here is not to punish. If they are going to compete in Division I
they are going to obey by the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson State won Southwestern Athletic Conference cross country
championships in 1996, 1997, 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Culberson, Jackson State's new athletic director, was
unavailable for comment on the case. Calls made to new head coach
Edmond Donald on Wednesday were not returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 1928 </TRAILER>
