<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers, governor expected to allow towns to thin deer herds  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The trees are all chewed up. More than 300
deer get hit by cars each year. Lyme disease is a constant worry.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to leafy Princeton Township -- a wealthy Mercer County
community overrun by an estimated 1,300 deer. That's more than four
times what the 16-square-mile township can comfortably accommodate,
according to wildlife experts.
</P>
<P>
   Under a Senate bill up for a vote Thursday, township officials
would be allowed to bring in sharpshooters to thin the herd and
correct what they say is an ecological imbalance.
</P>
<P>
   ''Deer-car accidents have increased over the last 20 years from
30 a year to over 300,'' said Tom Poole, a member of the township's
wildlife committee. ''Forget the fact that it costs an average of
$2,500 to fix the car. It's the danger factor. And, it's a cruel
way for the animals to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Poole also laments the damage the deer do to the woods. With so
many, they ravage entire stands of trees.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't replace the saplings that they are destroying in the
woods, where tomorrow's forests are going to be determined by what
the deer are eating today,'' Poole added. ''Pretty soon the woods
are going to be nothing but garlic mustard, which the deer won't
eat.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, A-2129, would allow towns to apply to the Division of
Fish, Game and Wildlife to, essentially, break state hunting rules
and use various methods to kill deer.
</P>
<P>
   While contraception is mentioned in the bill, ''deer
management'' typically means bringing in marksmen, putting down
bait to lure the deer and then shooting them, probably at night.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Princeton Township would likely do, Poole said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'd probably have one person who would move each night to a
particular spot,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Lund, acting chief of the state's Bureau of Wildlife
Management, said controlled hunts pose no public threat.
</P>
<P>
   Similar programs are conducted in other states, he said, and
''in most cases, the community is not even aware a control
operation is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   ''A community-based management plan has all kinds of checks and
balances, including approvals at various levels, before a community
can put this into effect,'' Poole added. ''This is not the six-pack
crowd running around in your backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed both houses last year, but Gov. Christie Whitman
vetoed it in January, citing public safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, bill supporters have added additional safety
measures, such as requiring county prosecutors to approve the use
of silencers and mandating public notification on when and where
the hunts will take place.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're comfortable that the bill now addresses the public
safety issues raised by the governor,'' said Jayne O'Connor,
Whitman's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The measure passed the Assembly in March, so if it passes the
Senate Thursday as expected, it heads to the governor's desk.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, a town would first have to apply to the
state for a permit to hunt at night, use high-powered rifles and
silencers and otherwise prohibited measures.
</P>
<P>
   Towns would submit plans for the hunt, including information
about an organization they might hire to shoot the deer.
</P>
<P>
   The bill applies to both suburbs, where deer are destroying
property and getting hit by cars, and rural areas, where they are
damaging farmers' fields.
</P>
<P>
   Airports also could be designated as areas for controlled hunts
if it's determined that deer are a danger to planes taking off or
landing.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates put the state's deer herd at 200,000, double what it
was 20 years ago. Crop damage related to deer has been measured in
the millions of dollars, and about 19,000 car accidents last year
were caused by deer.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the bill have objected to allowing the use of
silencers and nighttime shooting. Animal rights advocates say
allowing more hunting of deer is not a solution. They have
suggested farmers use higher fences around crop fields and airports
and place road reflectors to alert motorists to deer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-17-00 1930 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
