<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebel Leader's Arrest Concerns U.N.  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United Nations expressed concern
Wednesday that the arrest of Sierra Leone rebel leader Foday Sankoh
could complicate arrangements now under way for the release of
several hundred U.N. peacekeepers taken hostage by his forces.
</P>
<P>
   While U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said it was ''a relief'' to
know where Sankoh was, he reflected the overriding concern at U.N.
headquarters over the fate of the peacekeepers, who were among
about 500 seized earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have freed about 150 peacekeepers. In an encouraging
sign, Eckhard announced that the United Nations had been informed
Wednesday afternoon that 80 more detainees had been moved from
Sierra Leone to the Liberian border town of Foya. If their release
is confirmed, that would mean about 270 U.N. peacekeepers are still
being held hostage.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations authorized an 11,100-strong force to help
implement a peace agreement signed 10 months ago between the
government and rebels that ended an eight-year war. After the
hostage-taking and a resumption of fighting earlier this month by
Sankoh's rebels, the Security Council has moved to beef up the U.N.
mission.
</P>
<P>
   Britain on Wednesday circulated a draft resolution that would
increase the peacekeeping force to 13,000 troops, and said it
expected council approval on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials have some justification for expressing concern at
the possible rebel reaction to Sankoh's arrest. When rebel fighters
heard media reports last week that Sankoh had been placed under
house arrest by U.N. peacekeepers, rebels began a spontaneous
advance and clashed with U.N. troops at Rogberi, a key intersection
60 miles east of the capital, Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   Eckhard stressed that the United Nations was waiting for the
reaction of the Sierra Leone government.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the peace deal, Sankoh was granted amnesty for the
rebels' war atrocities and was given a ministerial-level post in
the government of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah as commissioner for
the management of strategic resources, national reconstruction and
development.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials wondered whether there was any alternative
leadership to Sankoh's Revolutionary United Front, and what the
future holds for the 10-month-old peace agreement that the
government and rebels signed in Lome, Togo.
</P>
<P>
   The government could choose to try Sankoh or send him into
exile, or even execute him. Human Rights Watch urged a fair trial
for Sankoh -- even by an international tribunal -- saying he
shouldn't be subjected to ''mob rule'' despite extensive evidence
of his involvement in crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Sankoh's arrest could influence what happens to
the hostages, Eckhard said: ''We are concerned that it could
complicate the arrangements that are under way now concerning the
release of the remaining detainees. It's too soon to say what
impact it will have.''
</P>
<P>
   Liberian President Charles Taylor has been charged by West
African nations with the job of getting the U.N. troops released.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 2000 </TRAILER>
