<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Limits Talks  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- By wide margins, the parliament gave first
approval Wednesday to two measures setting limits on the
government's ability to negotiate key issues with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The measures would require absolute majorities of 61 of the 120
members of parliament to allow changes in the present boundaries of
Jerusalem or to permit Palestinian refugees to return to their
former homes in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Cabinet ministers said the opposition bills reflect government
policy. Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak was notably absent in
both votes.
</P>
<P>
   Though the bills would have to survive three more votes and
committee debates to become law, the votes created an
uncompromising atmosphere just as peace talks appeared off to a
fresh start. The Palestinians reacted angrily to the bills, warning
that they will mean the end of peace talks if they become law.
</P>
<P>
   Many members of Barak's coalition government joined the
hard-line opposition in voting for the bills. Critics of the
measures charged that its backers are trying to sabotage the peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Israeli government knows very well that these laws would
mean the end of negotiations,'' Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat
said. ''This raises many questions about the real intentions of
this government.''
</P>
<P>
   There were minor clashes in the West Bank and Gaza Strip
Wednesday, with Palestinians throwing rocks at Israeli soldiers,
who responded with rubber-coated steel pellets and tear gas. At
least five Palestinians, one Israeli civilian and two soldiers were
injured in the events, the Israeli army said.
</P>
<P>
   But the protests were far smaller than the riots Monday that
deteriorated into gunbattles that killed three Palestinians. Israel
demanded in peace talks Wednesday that the Palestinians collect all
illegal weapons in the areas under their control, Israel radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem and the fate of Palestinian refugees are two of the
most sensitive issues facing negotiators, who hope to sign a peace
treaty by September. The Palestinians want to set up a state, with
traditionally Arab east Jerusalem as the capital. They insist that
refugees who fled Israel when it was created in 1948 have the right
to return.
</P>
<P>
   The bills forced government officials to take hard-line
positions in peace talks, just days after it emerged that top-level
negotiations are under way between Israeli and Palestinian
officials in Stockholm, Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   The Jerusalem measure, introduced by hawkish Likud lawmaker
Yehoshua Matza, confirms the expanded boundaries of the city,
including the Arab sections Israel captured and annexed in 1967 and
forbids the government from handing any land or authority there to
an outside body.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister David Levy called on members to vote for the
opposition bill, so that there would not be even ''the smallest
shadow of doubt'' that the government rejects compromise over
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The law would scuttle another idea that has been raised -- giving
autonomy to the Palestinian residents of the city. The measure
passed by a vote of 68 to 21.
</P>
<P>
   The second measure, introduced by Israel Katz, also of the
Likud, bans return of Palestinian refugees to communities in what
is now Israel. Agreeing, Cabinet minister Haim Ramon declared that
recognizing the right of some 3 million refugees to return would
''mean the end of the state of Israel'' as a Jewish nation.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon said when the Palestinians bring up the right of refugees
to return to their homes, Israeli negotiators ''reject it
totally.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
