<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeologists find pottery kiln at Trenton road construction site  </HEADLINE>
By NINA RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- An archaeological team monitoring
construction on Route 29 has unearthed a well-preserved pottery
kiln built in the 1770s, a rare find from one of Trenton's biggest
Colonial-era industries.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-by-9-foot brick structure is the oldest kiln discovered
in the city, which grew into the nation's largest supplier of
toilets, china and other stoneware a century later.
</P>
<P>
   ''It (the kiln) is extremely well-preserved and we can see
exactly how it worked,'' said Ian Burrow, vice president of Hunter
Research Inc., an archaeology firm working with the state
Department of Transportation on the Route 29 project. The only
other kilns of this kind uncovered in the United States were found
in Cheesequake, Middlesex County, and Yorktown, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is important not just for Trenton but it will be useful
for archaeological studies all over the region. If an archaeologist
finds some pottery like the ones found here, they will know the
date it was made and where it comes from,'' Burrow said.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of pottery pieces from the kiln have been unearthed,
including chamber pots, teacups, syrup jars and jugs. The items
will be cleaned and catalogued, and valuable pieces will be donated
to area museums.
</P>
<P>
   The kiln itself is too fragile to be moved without risk of
damage and will most likely be preserved in the ground, said John
Dourgarian, a Department of Transportation spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be a great challenge to preserve it,'' Burrow said,
adding that instead, it will be ''preserved in place'' and left for
another generation to study.
</P>
<P>
   The archeologists were to continue sifting through the site
until Friday, extracting as many artifacts as they can find around
the kiln.
</P>
<P>
   ''The important thing is that we get what we can out of there
and then leave it there as it has been for the past 225 years,''
Dourgarian said.
</P>
<P>
   The kiln was built in 1774 by William Richards, a wealthy
Philadelphia merchant who had several business dealings in the
port, then known as Lamberton. The kiln is believed to have ceased
operations when Richards died in 1787.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're learning a tremendous amount about this forgotten port
along the Delaware River,'' said Burrow.
</P>
<P>
   By tracking where the pottery traveled, historians can learn
more about the local economy, which had businesses known for
trading with other American colonies, Europe and the Caribbean,
Burrow said.
</P>
<P>
   The state has dedicated $2.3 million for excavation and research
along the two-mile extension of Route 29, Dourgarian said.
</P>
<P>
   In July, archeologists discovered thousands of artifacts in the
root cellar of a two-story wooden mansion once owned by Richards.
That dig uncovered teapots, wine bottles, animal bones and other
refuse that was disposed of there before the days of curbside
pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ''This area of Trenton is a treasure trove of history,'' said
Dourgarian.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-17-00 2038 </TRAILER>
