<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Edison police officer convicted on bank robbery charge  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A federal jury on Wednesday convicted an
Edison police officer of stealing $3,500 at gunpoint from a bank in
his patrol district, rejecting defense arguments of mistaken
identity.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Spinello was found guilty on all three charges he faced:
bank robbery, armed bank robbery and using a gun during a crime.
</P>
<P>
   Spinello, 32, of Brick, did not testify during the nine-day
trial. His lawyer told the jury that the 11-year officer was the
victim of ''an unfortunate series of coincidences.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict was returned after about six hours of deliberations
over two days.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious charge, armed bank robbery, carries up to 25
years in prison, although under sentencing guidelines, the actual
term would be about four years. Combined with a 5-year mandatory
consecutive term on the gun charge, he faces about nine years
without parole when sentenced Sept. 6 by U.S. District Judge Joseph
A. Greenaway Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Spinello gave no reaction to the verdict. When the jury left the
courtroom, he removed his tie, waved to his wife, and was taken
into custody. He had been under house arrest since shortly after
his arrest the day of the robbery.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Lawrence S. Lustberg said they were disappointed,
and would discuss whether to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Spinello is the third New Jersey law officer jailed for bank
robbery in the past few years:
</P>
<P>
   --A former Mercer County Jail guard dubbed the ''pipe bomb
bandit,'' Freddie Feliciano, of Hamilton, is serving more than 10
years in prison after pleading guilty last year to using fake pipe
bombs to rob 16 banks in five states from August to October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   --A former Trenton police officer, Christopher Kerins, pleaded
guilty in 1998 and is now serving 6 1/2 years for seven bank
robberies from November 1995 to April 1996 attributed to the
''camouflage bandit.''
</P>
<P>
   Spinello was arrested shortly after he reported to work Jan. 13,
1999, about an hour after a man not wearing a mask showed a teller
at the First Savings Bank in Edison a revolver and fled with
$3,500.
</P>
<P>
   He was suspended without pay after his arrest and Edison
officials said he would be fired.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Edward Costello said Spinello's future is in the
hands of Mayor George A. Spadoro, who also serves as police
director. The mayor did not immediately return a call seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Robert J. Cleary, who tried the case himself,
maintained that Spinello turned to robbery amid desperation over
debts.
</P>
<P>
   The teller and a customer who saw the bandit escape in a green
Ford Explorer identified Spinello as the robber. The vehicle was
registered to the officer's wife, Angela.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI recovered $3,500 in a nearby condominium that Spinello
rented to one of his brothers. The cash was in the same
denominations as the money taken from the bank, Cleary said: $1,000
in $100 bills, $1,000 in $50 bills, $1,000 in $20 bills, and $500
in $10 bills.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lustberg told the jury that the money was only part of
a larger amount that Spinello had won in an Atlantic City casino
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Lustberg also said that the teller mistakenly identified
Spinello as the robber, and that the customer lost sight of the
robber as they went outside the bank, and erred by saying the
robber got into the green Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   The officer was getting into the vehicle about that time,
Lustberg said: ''Mr. Spinello was, as he openly admitted, in the
wrong place at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   Lustberg also asked the jury to consider whether the officer, in
the space of an hour, could have robbed the bank, stashed the
money, disposed of the clothes worn during the heist, the gun, as
well as the straps on the cash -- none of which have been found --
and reported to work.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. attorney's office news release:
http://www.njusao.org/break.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
