<HEADLINE> US: Surveillance of Embassies Common  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. surveillance detection teams have
uncovered more than 700 incidents of suspected monitoring of
American personnel and facilities over the last 16 months, a top
State Department official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Secretary of State David Carpenter testified that the
teams were deployed in January, 1999 after the State Department
concluded that surveillance against U.S. facilities is intense
prior to a terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
   He said that lesson was learned at the time of the bombings of
two American embassies in East Africa in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter, testifying before the House International Relations
Committee, said the presence of the teams has expanded the security
perimeter and the zone of control beyond previous limitations.
</P>
<P>
   The program is still a work in progress, he said, adding that
the administration nonetheless believes that ''it is destined to
become a major aspect of our overseas security defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department Inspector General Jaquelyn Williams-Bridgers,
who also testified, said U.S. officials are trying to collect
information about the various groups which have had U.S. facilities
under surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter said the surveillance detection teams are no
substitute for having a minimum 100-foot buffer between an official
facility and the nearest street.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until we can build embassies meeting the setback and other
security standards, our efforts cannot provide the degree of
security all of us want for our people and facilities,'' Carpenter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Committee chairman Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., convened the hearing
for a progress report on embassy security upgrades since the 1998
bombings in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Kennedy, assistant secretary of state for
administration, said a record $800 million was obligated in the
last fiscal year on embassy security but much remains to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fully 85 per cent of our facilities do not meet minimum
security standards,'' he said. ''Some are seriously overcrowded.
Most, however have to be replaced...Our goal is to expeditiously
locate into safe facilities more than 22,000 embassy staff in over
220 vulnerable buildings.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
