<HEADLINE> 13 Die in Indonesia Violence  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMBON, Indonesia (AP) -- At least 13 people were killed and a
senior army commander injured Wednesday as fighting between Muslims
and Christians intensified in the eastern Indonesian town of Ambon,
officials and witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Ten of the dead were Muslims, said Malik Selang, an official at
the main mosque Al Fatah. All were shot by gunmen or security
officers trying to disperse the mobs, he said, adding that 40
others had been injured.
</P>
<P>
   One Christian also died and eight others injured during
Wednesday's clashes that erupted in the neighborhoods of Mardika
and Batu Merah, where sectarian fighting first broke out in January
last year, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   A police sergeant and an army corporal also died Wednesday after
being hit by gunfire, a military official said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,500 people have been killed in 16 months of
sectarian clashes in Maluku and neighboring North Maluku,
collectively known as the Spice Islands, or Moluccas, during Dutch
colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
   The strife is fueled by old rivalries and more recent complaints
by Christians that Muslim newcomers from other parts of Indonesia
have been taking their jobs and are not respecting local customs.
</P>
<P>
   The latest outbreak came after a sharp drop in sectarian
violence during the past six weeks. Inter-communal fighting abated
significantly in April -- when a dozen deaths were recorded -- and
the first half of May.
</P>
<P>
   Ambon, 1,450 miles east of Jakarta, is the capital of Maluku
province.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Irwan Kusnadi, the local army commander, was injured after
being shot in the cheek during Wednesday's clashes, a military
official said. Some of the soldiers accompanying him were also
injured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
