<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Breeder charged with bilking customers of $91,000  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PATERSON, N.J. (AP) -- A dog breeder on probation for theft was
indicted on charges he failed to deliver purebred, highly trained
dogs to customers nationwide, bilking them of $91,000.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick V. Chestnut, 34, either delivered sick, mixed-breed
canines to customers or didn't deliver the dogs at all, Passaic
County prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The victims include an Illinois woman who paid Chestnut $3,250
for a dog that never arrived, and a California woman who paid
$13,500 for two dogs, one of which had severe physical disabilities
and another that never arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of the people were dog-lovers, so they kept the dogs
anyway,'' said Assistant Passaic County Prosecutor Eileen Kane.
''As one victim said, 'I just bought myself one very expensive
house pet.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut's home telephone number and the number of his Haledon
business, Chestnut Dog Command, are not listed.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut is serving probation for a 1997 theft conviction and
has been sentenced to probation twice before on theft charges. He
was fined $500 in Totowa Municipal Court in 1994 for neglecting one
of his dogs.
</P>
<P>
   From 1994 to 1999, Chestnut defrauded customers in Totowa,
Paterson, Wisconsin, Michigan and California of $91,400, an
indictment said. He put out advertisements in dog magazines
claiming his animals were purebred and trained in the Schutzhund
method, a regimen to train dogs in obedience and home protection.
</P>
<P>
   Paterson couple Darryl and Gathlyn Smoot paid Chestnut $4,500
for a specially trained German shepherd in 1996, but didn't get the
protection they had hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   ''They said that a contractor came over to their home one day
and was working on the gutters and the dog was just lying in the
kennel,'' Kane said. ''Eventually, the guy just came up and gave
the dog a sandwich.''
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut forged pedigree papers to cover up health problems of
some of his dogs, Kane said.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged with 14 counts of theft by deception, two counts
of attempted theft by deception, two counts relating to bad checks,
and two counts of forgery.
</P>
<P>
   He was also separately charged Tuesday with theft for allegedly
agreeing to sell a car to a man for $3,200 in June 1999, but never
delivering the car.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-17-00 2131 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chavez Leads Venezuelan Poll  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- With less than two weeks before his
re-election bid, President Hugo Chavez maintains a 20-point lead
over his closest rival, according to a poll published Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Conducted by the private Consultores 21 firm, it found that of
1,200 people interviewed, 51 percent said they would vote for
Chavez while 31 percent favored Francisco Arias Cardenas. The
former army commander helped Chavez stage a failed 1992 coup
attempt, but who now accuses the president of grabbing too much
power.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted from May 9 through May 12 and had a
margin of error of 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The poll comes a day after leaders of an observer team from the
Organization of American States expressed concern over a perceived
lack of public confidence in the May 28 elections. The absence of
an independent firm to audit the printing of ballots and the
computer used to count them was also listed as problematic.
</P>
<P>
   National election officials had planned to hire a firm but said
this week that the lone company that bid on the contract did not
qualify.
</P>
</TEXT>
