<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressPaul Bartel:
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Paul Bartel, acclaimed director of cult hits
including ''Eating Raoul'' and ''Death Race 2000,'' as well as a
character actor in numerous movies, died Saturday of liver cancer.
He was 61.
</P>
<P>
   Bartel's most recent role was as ''Osric'' in a version of
''Hamlet'' released last week.
</P>
<P>
   After some years doing documentary work, Bartel came out with
his first feature film, ''Private Parts,'' in 1972. That led to a
directing assignment from producer Roger Korman and ''Death Race
2000,'' a 1975 black comedy about a cross-country race in which
drivers were encouraged to mow down pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   ''Eating Raoul,'' released in 1982, was Bartel's first
self-financed film. He also wrote and starred in the movie, which
focused on a couple -- Bartel and actress Mary Woronov -- who decide
to finance their dream of opening a restaurant through murder.
</P>
<P>
   His acting roles included parts in ''Basquiat,'' ''Escape from
L.A.,'' and ''The Usual Suspects.''
Herbert Cahoon:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Herbert Cahoon, a curator who helped the Morgan
Library acquire a letter from Voltaire to Alexander Pope, died
Sunday. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Cahoon was curator at the library, one of the world's top
repositories of literary and historical manuscripts and handwritten
papers, for 35 years, ending in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Major acquisitions under Cahoon's tenure included the Mary
Flagler Collection, which contained original copies of Brahms's
First Symphony and Beethoven's ''Ghost'' Trio, and many works by
Mozart, Bach and Verdi.
</P>
<P>
   The items Cahoon added to the library's holding of 150,000
documents include a pencil draft of ''The Little Prince'' and
drawings by Saint-Exupery, a ''Travels with Charley'' manuscript
donated by John Steinbeck and letters from Erasmus, Wordsworth,
Melville and others.
</P>
<P>
   Cahoon wrote a book of poetry, ''Thanatopsis,'' in 1949. He also
collaborated on an extensive James Joyce bibliography.
Margaret Connors Driscoll:
</P>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- Margaret Connors Driscoll, a retired
Superior Court judge who championed the rights of juvenile
offenders, died Tuesday. She was 85.
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll was the state's first woman to serve as chief Juvenile
Court judge. She was known for her steadfast stand against
mandatory sentencing for juveniles and extended incarceration and
for her advocacy of broad human rights protections.
Red Kelso:
</P>
<P>
   CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) -- Red Kelso, a longtime photojournalist and
first editor of the Sunday Eagle-Tribune, died May 11. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   Kelso was editor of the Wyoming Tribune-Eagle's Sunday Magazine,
photo reporter for the Denver Post and also a photojournalist for
Chevrolet's Friends magazine, Popular Mechanics, Colliers and
several Japanese and German magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Kelso was an FAA examiner. He was also a member of the Civil Air
Patrol and founder of the Wyoming Aviation Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Kelso is survived by his wife, two sons and two grandchildren.
Robert Lee Knous:
</P>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Former Lt. Gov. Robert Lee Knous died Monday. He
was 82.
</P>
<P>
   Knous was a prominent member of a political dynasty in Colorado
during the 1950s and 60s.
</P>
<P>
   Knous, a Democrat, had the distinction of being elected
lieutenant governor under both a Democratic governor and a
Republican governor.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, Knous' father, W. Lee Knous, started the dynasty when
he was elected governor.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, Bob Knous was elected to the state Senate, an at-large
position then, and was the largest vote-getter in the state.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, he ran for lieutenant governor, winning 59 of 63
counties, but lost. Knous ran again for lieutenant governor in 1958
and won. He was re-elected in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Knous tried for the top seat in 1966, but lost when the
incumbent was re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   He retired from politics in the early 1970s and served several
years in Washington as a commissioner with the Bureau of Indian
Affairs.
Karl Shapiro:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Karl Shapiro, whose World War II poetry earned
him a Pulitzer Prize in 1945, died Sunday. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro wrote when he was a soldier in New Guinea. His highly
acclaimed poems include ''Elegy for a Dead Soldier,'' written in
1944. He won the Pulitzer for ''V-Letter and Other Poems.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1950s and '60s, he edited Poetry magazine and then
Prairie Schooner and published poetry and criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Among his other works are ''English Prosody and Modern Poetry''
(1947), ''The Bourgeois Poet'' (1964), ''To Abolish Children''
(1968), the novel ''Edsel'' (1971), ''Adult Bookstore'' (1976) and
several anthologies.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro published his autobiography, ''Reports of My Death,'' in
1990.
Nestor Vornicescu:
</P>
<P>
   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) -- Nestor Vornicescu, a leading Romanian
Orthodox cleric who made his career under communism and maintained
links with former leftists after the 1989 revolution, died
Wednesday after suffering a stroke. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
   Nestor, No. 4 in the hierarchy of the Romanian Orthodox Church,
was appointed Metropolitan of Oltenia, the largest Orthodox Church
parish in Romania, 22 years ago. In 1992 he wanted to run for
Senate for the leftist Party of Social Democracy but his candidacy
was blocked by the Patriarch Teocist, head of the Orthodox Church.
</P>
<P>
   He rose through the church ranks with political support from the
then-communist regime. In 1969-70 he traveled to Switzerland to
study at an ecumenical institute.
</P>
</TEXT>
