<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Thursday, led by
information technology issues, following a decline on Wall Street.
The dollar was lower against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 194.31 points,
or 1.11 percent, to 17,209.72 points in the first 30 minutes of
trading. On Wednesday, the average closed up 147.22 points, or 0.84
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 108.82 yen, down 0.56 yen from late Wednesday
in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 109.41 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index opened lower Thursday
after drops in New York on Wednesday led shares in Japanese high
technology issues and major brokerages into negative territory.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 164.83 points
to 10,769.74 at Wednesday's close. The Nasdaq composite index lost
72.61 points to close at 3,644.96.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 20.19 points, or 1.23 percent, to 1,616.26
points. The TOPIX closed up 6.62 points, or 0.40 percent, the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, traders said the dollar slipped from the
109 yen level in line with its downward trend in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The yen was supported against the greenback by a Japanese
government report revising industrial output data to a 2.4 percent
rise in March above February, reversing its initial assessment of a
1.0 percent drop. The upward revision partly reflected a change in
the government calculation method.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 97.26 yen, down from
98.04 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell
to 1.7550 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.77 percent. Its
price rose 0.13 point to 100.38.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Tokyo Stock Exchange: http://www.tse.or.jp./
</P>
</TEXT>
