<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Feels Impact of US Rates  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Stock markets dipped and currencies
closed weaker Wednesday in Latin America's two largest economies in
the wake of the U.S. Federal Reserve's half-point interest rake
hike.
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, share prices ended sharply lower as bearishness on
Wall Street weighed heavily on local investor sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, stocks slid 2.8 percent on the growing realization
that further monetary tightening in the U.S. is likely.
</P>
<P>
   The Bovespa index of the Sao Paulo Stock Exchange -- Latin
America's largest -- shed 3.2 percent Wednesday to finish at 14,870
points. Trading volume was well below average at $189 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tuesday's interest rate hike by the Federal Reserve may slow
down the inflow of foreign capital, making it difficult for Brazil
to lower its interest rates,'' when monetary authorities meet next
week, said Carlos Kawall, chief economist at Citibank in Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
   ''American investors will seek other safer alternatives like
treasury bonds,'' Kawall added. ''And with a possible weakening of
the real, the government will have no choice but to leave interest
rates as they are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian real closed weaker against the dollar Wednesday on
very low volumes, with the local currency following New York stock
markets, traders said. The real closed at 1.83 per dollar, compared
with Tuesday's finish of 1.8190.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, regional markets gained and heaved a collective sigh
of relief Tuesday as investors cheered the end of uncertainty.
Analysts said the Fed's hike had been fully priced in.
</P>
<P>
   But comfort was short-lived as investors on Wednesday focused on
the Fed's statement that further rate hikes were likely if
inflationary pressures didn't cede.
</P>
<P>
   Local traders say that uncertainty was sidelining investors, who
were also growing jittery ahead of Mexico's presidential elections
July 2. Opposition candidate Vicente Fox is running neck-and-neck
with the ruling party's Francisco Labastida in recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   Market jitters also spread to the peso, which weakened against
the dollar. Mexico's currency closed at 9.545 to the dollar,
compared to Tuesday's close of 9.518.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
