<HEADLINE> Argentina Recovers From Storm  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Thousands of people left
emergency shelters Wednesday following a powerful storm that killed
four people, injured dozens and flooded homes and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy downpours, combined with winds gusting above 50 mph, also
caused dozens of injuries from flying debris, falling trees, and
highway accidents in parts of the capital and outlying Buenos Aires
Province.
</P>
<P>
   The storm, sweeping in from the South Atlantic Ocean to mark the
approach of the southern hemisphere winter, forced more than 25,000
people to evacuate their homes and left 140,000 people temporarily
without electricity.
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando De la Rua praised local authorities for a
speedy response to Tuesday's storm, saying fast action blunted the
worst effects. ''The fast reaction of Buenos Aires' government was
crucial to solving the problems caused by the severe weather,'' De
la Rua said in a statement transmitted by news agency Diarios y
Noticias.
</P>
<P>
   Workers cleared away scores of fallen trees and commuters forded
water-clogged arteries Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Three children died Tuesday when a tree fell on a shelter in
Rosario, 180 miles northwest of the capital, authorities said. In a
fourth fatality, a 28-year-old man was electrocuted when he stepped
on a fallen power line in Buenos Aires.
</P>
</TEXT>
