<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Koreas Preparing for Summit  </HEADLINE>
By SANG-HUN CHOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) -- North and South Korea resumed high-level
talks on Thursday amid indications that weeks of negotiations may
soon produce an accord on the agenda for a summit of their leaders
in June.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean officials were upbeat about the prospect of
Thursday's meeting, saying that both sides had made progress in
unofficial contacts on one last pending issue -- the size of the
South Korean press corp for the June 12-14 summit.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have much time left to the summit. We must wrap up a
deal today in one way or another,'' Unification Minister Park
Jae-kyu said before the meeting opened in the southern sector of
Panmunjom, a neutral border village.
</P>
<P>
   In a report by its overseas news outlet, KCNA, on Wednesday,
North Korea also said ''basic agreement'' was reached on the South
Korean press coverage for the summit in its capital of Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's Cabinet-level meeting at Panmunjom was the fifth
since April 22. After failing to reach accord in four rounds of
talks, the two sides last week decided to discuss details through
documents and telephone contacts.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea had proposed sending an 80-member press corp but
North Korea asked that the number be halved. Seoul officials said
the issue would not jeopardize the summit.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea plans to send a 30-member advance team to North
Korea toward the end of this month to prepare for the summit.
Officials said the team will include specialists in security,
protocol and communications.
</P>
<P>
   Local media, quoting unidentified government sources, said the
two Koreas would agree not to use their national flags and songs
during the summit.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reduced protocol is line with the precedent set by East
and West Germany when they started contact to improve ties,'' the
Chosun Ilbo newspaper quoted one unidentified government official
as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The summit would be the first ever between the two Koreas which
were divided into the communist North and the pro-Western South in
1945. Their three-year war in the early 1950s ended in an
armistice, not a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   In a luncheon meeting with religious leaders on Wednesday,
President Kim Dae-jung said he would not seek ''too much at a
time'' from the summit with North Korean leader Kim Jong Il.
</P>
<P>
   High on South Korea's summit agenda are economic cooperation and
reunions of separated family members. North Korea is expected to
raise the U.S. military presence in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean officials believe that North Korea was driven to
agree to the summit for economic reasons. With its economy in
tatters, the North has been relying on foreign aid to feed its 22
million people since 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 2226 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russians Recover Pilots' Bodies  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- Russian troops combing through mountain
forests have found the bodies of two pilots whose plane was shot
down by rebels, the military said Wednesday, one of just a few
aircraft downed in the nine-month war.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov, meanwhile, said he was
prepared to negotiate an end to the war with Russian President
Vladimir Putin. Putin has said he could talk with Maskhadov, but
only if the rebels unconditionally surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Troops conducting a search-and-rescue operation in Chechnya's
southern mountains found the bodies of the crew of a Su-24MR
reconnaissance plane that crashed May 7, the office of presidential
aide Sergei Yastrzhembsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Wreckage of the aircraft was found two miles from the village of
Benoi-Vedeno.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has been established that the plane was shot down during
combat operations and its crew, a pilot and a navigator, were
killed,'' the military said in a statement. ''The bodies of the
dead pilots, the black boxes and the main fragments of the plane
have been recovered from the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels lack sophisticated anti-aircraft weapons, and have
shot down few Russian planes.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's air campaign has remained steady despite the loss of
the aircraft. Air force planes flew 14 combat missions over the
past 24 hours, targeting rebel formations in the mountains in the
south and southeast, the military said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said Russian aircraft also bombed sheep fields and
farms in southwest Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   As the war drags on, the Kremlin has hinted it could be seeking
a political solution. But Moscow demands that the rebels surrender
their weapons and release all Russian hostages -- conditions most
rebel leaders reject.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov has said he is ready to negotiate, but his authority
over the fractured rebel bands is questionable. In a videotape
interview obtained by The Associated Press on Wednesday, he said he
was prepared to negotiate with Putin.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Chechen people are tired of eternal wars,'' Maskhadov
said. ''The recent war has been a terrible ordeal for us.''
</P>
<P>
   He said: ''Although I am a military man, I am also the president
and I am ready to do everything to start negotiations to stop this
war. As I was ready for talks with President (Boris) Yeltsin, now
I'm ready for this dialogue with President Putin.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops entered Chechnya in September after
Chechnya-based Islamic militants seized several villages in
neighboring Dagestan, and after about 300 people died in apartment
bombings that the government blames on Chechens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
