<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unionists Urged To Take IRA Offer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Protestant unionists in Northern Ireland should
''seize the credit'' for recent progress on IRA disarmament,
instead of blocking the restoration of a power-sharing government
with new conditions, Britain's senior official for the province
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland Secretary Peter Mandelson told lawmakers in the
House of Commons that it now appeared possible to both restore the
government and make ''real, lasting and permanent progress in the
removal of arms from Northern Ireland politics forever.''
</P>
<P>
   ''And I think it's an opportunity that we should seize for fear
that if it slips from our grasp now, we may not be able to recreate
it in the future,'' Mandelson said.
</P>
<P>
   The governing council of the Ulster Unionist Party, which
receives the bulk of Protestant votes in Northern Ireland, meets
Saturday to decide whether to go back into the government.
</P>
<P>
   The government was suspended in February after the Ulster
Unionists threatened to walk out because the Irish Republican Army
had done nothing about disarmament. On May 6, the IRA reversed
direction and offered to open its weapons dumps to international
inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Some Ulster Unionists have said that doesn't go far enough. They
also have demanded assurances that the name of the Royal Ulster
Constabulary will not be changed as part of the process of
reforming the police service, and that British flags will fly over
public buildings in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair, responding to a question from Ulster
Unionist leader David Trimble, said in the Commons that the IRA
gesture was ''an important confidence-building measure'' but only
the start of a process of silencing the guns.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to make progress until the time when these weapons are
indeed completely, verifiably, beyond use,'' Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson said that ''what is unprecedented about the situation
now is that we have the real prospect both of returning power to
Northern Ireland and at the same time making very real and
substantive progress on arms.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Both these objectives are ones that unionists have rightly
held out for. Now I believe they should seize the credit for the
progress that is being made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While traveling Wednesday in Greenwich, Conn., President Clinton
also urged the parties in Northern Ireland to seize this chance for
peace, which he called ''an opportunity that must not be lost.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a chance to lock in the unprecedented progress that
has been attained and propel the process forward,'' Clinton said in
a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I urge the parties to lift their sights, seize the
possibilities that are within their grasp, and take the steps
necessary to advance the cause of peace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 2239 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
