<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Opposition Party Splits  </HEADLINE>
By BASSEM MROUE
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- An opposition party blamed for recent riots
has splintered after some members revolted against its top leaders,
accusing them of sedition and Islamic fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
   After the revolt Tuesday night, the Islamic-oriented Labor Party
appears to have broken into three factions, likely increasing
President Hosni Mubarak's governing National Democratic Party's
domination of Egyptian politics.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Labor Party had only two seats in the 454-member
Parliament, its members frequently raised questions uncomfortable
to the government in the party's newspaper, such as relations with
Israel, corruption and Islamic values.
</P>
<P>
   Hamdi Ahmed, a movie actor and a member of the party's Central
Committee, organized a rally late Tuesday in Cairo, attended by
hundreds of supporters. The rally named Ahmed as party president to
replace Ibrahim Shukri, who has led the party since its
establishment in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued by Ahmed's faction accused Shukri and his
followers of changing the party's socialist principles by adopting
the slogan ''Islam is the solution'' and by allowing members of
militant Islamic groups to join the party. The statement was
reported by Egypt's Middle East News Agency on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another rally was held simultaneously in a different
part of the capital by Ahmed Idriss, also a member of the 14-member
party Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
   That rally also elected Idriss as party president, accusing
Shukri's leadership of changing the Labor Party ''to a religious
party and forming coalitions with (Muslim) brotherhood and
fanatics.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Shukri held a news conference at the party's
headquarters in which the party's chairman described the rallies as
a ''sabotage attack against an office of the party.'' The party
also issued a statement describing Tuesday night's events as an
''ugly aggression against the law and the practicing of
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The developments came as the Political Parties Committee, a
government watchdog that licenses political groups, began
discussions Tuesday on whether to allow the Labor Party and its
newspaper, the biweekly Al-Shaab, to exist.
</P>
<P>
   The government began considering a ban on the two after Al-Shaab
published an article on May 5, saying a book approved by the
Culture Ministry for publication in Egypt was un-Islamic and
blasphemous. On May 7 and 8, hundreds of Muslim students rioted in
Cairo and clashed with police.
</P>
<P>
   Culture Ministry officials said the book, ''Banquet for
Seaweed,'' by Syrian author Haider Haider, was reprinted as part of
a series of classics of Arabic literature. Literary experts
appointed by the Culture Ministry have said the novel does not
defame religion and should not be judged from a nonliterary
perspective.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 2256 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, May 17, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Defends Microsoft Breakup Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In its legal reply to arguments outlined by Microsoft, the
Justice Department today reinforced its assertion that a breakup was the best
way to prevent anticompetitive behavior by a company found to have acted in wide
violation of federal laws. The Justice Department and 17 of the states that
successfully sued on antitrust charges want Microsoft to be broken up into two
companies. One would develop the company's dominant Windows computer operating
system and the other everything else, including Microsoft's Office software and
its Internet services. Jim Cullinan, a Microsoft spokesman, said: ''It's
unfortunate but not surprising that the government is attempting to defend its
extreme remedy proposal.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Arrests Made in 1963 Church Bombing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- Two former Ku Klux Klansmen were arrested on murder
charges today in the 1963 Birmingham church bombing that killed four black girls
-- a crime that galvanized the civil rights movement. Thomas E. Blanton Jr., 61,
of Birmingham, and Bobby Frank Cherry, 69, of Mabank, Texas, surrendered on the
state charges and were jailed without bail. If convicted, they could get life in
prison with the possibility of parole. U.S. Attorney Doug Jones would not say
what led to the break in the case after 37 years. But over the past year,
estranged family members of Cherry have said publicly that he talked of helping
plant the dynamite.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Unionists Urged To Take IRA Offer
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Protestant unionists in Northern Ireland should ''seize the
credit'' for recent progress on IRA disarmament, instead of blocking the
restoration of a power-sharing government with new conditions, Britain's senior
official for the province said Wednesday. Northern Ireland Secretary Peter
Mandelson told lawmakers in the House of Commons that it now appeared possible
to both restore the government and make ''real, lasting and permanent progress
in the removal of arms from Northern Ireland politics forever.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Key Panels OK China Trade Bill
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation normalizing trade relations with China
overwhelmingly won the support today of key committees in the House and Senate.
The House Ways and Means Committee approved the measure 34-4 as previously
undecided committee members flocked to support the Clinton administration. A
showdown on the House floor was set for next week. The Senate Finance Committee
approved the legislation 18-1. The bill would grant Beijing the same low-tariff
access to U.S. markets nearly every other nation now enjoys.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dr. Dre Joins Showdown With Napster
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Rapper Dr. Dre joined the heavy metal band Metallica in
a showdown with Napster Inc. today, demanding the music sharing software company
block access to his copyrighted work. Andre ''Dr. Dre'' Young e-mailed to
Napster a list of 935,500 recordings of pirated copies of his music offered by
computer users through the company's MusicShare service, and asked Napster to
block or remove the songs, stored in the popular MP3 digital format.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell Thursday, led by information technology
issues, following a decline on Wall Street. The Nikkei Stock Average shed 194.31
points to 17,209.72 points in early trading. In New York on Wednesday, the Dow
Jones industrial average fell 164.83 to close at 10,769.74. The Nasdaq Composite
Index fell 72.61 to 3,644.96.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Heat Defeat Knicks 87-81
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The Miami Heat moved within one victory of winning their annual
tug of war with the New York Knicks. Getting two clutch late 3-pointers from Dan
Majerle and another from Bruce Bowen, the Heat defeated the New York Knicks
87-81 tonight to take a 3-2 lead in the best-of-seven Eastern Conference
semifinals. Neither of the teams has beaten the other two straight times in the
postseason since the end of their 1998 series, and that is exactly what Miami
will try to do Friday night when the series resumes at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Source: Seattle Picks Up Henderson
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Rickey Henderson, released by the New York Mets over the
weekend, has reached an agreement to play for the Seattle Mariners, The
Associated Press learned tonight. The deal includes a team option for a 2001
contract at $3 million, a baseball source who asked not to be identified told
the AP. Henderson and the Mariners agreed about eight hours after baseball's
career stolen base leader cleared waivers. The Montreal Expos also pursued
signing him. Henderson was cut by the Mets on Saturday in the midst of a
troubling season.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY
</SUBHEAD>
