<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Astros, Brewers Game Postponed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Houston manager Larry Dierker lamented the
scheduling quirk that only delayed the stress on his overworked
pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's game between the Houston Astros and the
Milwaukee Brewers was postponed by rain and will be made up as part
of a doubleheader Thursday beginning at 1:05 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   Although both teams are in the NL Central, it is the final trip
to Milwaukee this year for the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rainout would have helped us if we only had one more game
today,'' said Dierker, who used eight pitchers in Tuesday night's
6-5, 16-inning loss to the Brewers. ''Since we have two more games
to play, all it does is delay things and gets everybody that
pitched last night ready for tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewers pitching coach Bob Apodaca said the rainout might have
cost his staff a slight edge.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had some guys ready to pitch tonight,'' Apodaca said. ''We
felt if we had an advantage, that would be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said the schedule that has the Astros playing both
series in Milwaukee before the end of May forced the doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is more rain expected tomorrow,'' Dierker said. ''If we
can't get two games in tomorrow, this is our last trip to
Milwaukee. They would have to play a game in Houston that would
have been a home game or we would have to find a mutually
acceptable off day where they were here, or were coming here and we
were somewhere near here. So that complicates things. It's a lot
easier to get the three games in while we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said the unequal number of teams in different divisions
and unbalanced schedules means some division rivals will not meet
down the pennant stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ''The math doesn't work with 30 teams,'' Dierker said. ''If we
had two 16-team leagues and four four-team divisions, the math
would work great. We could play in our own division early, middle
and late like we used to.
</P>
<P>
   ''With 30 teams and two 15-team leagues, it doesn't work because
you have seven games per day and you've got a team that is off.
You've got a team in the other league that's off and supposedly
they could play each other. I haven't tried to do that math, but
from what I understand, that doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's scheduled starters, Steve Woodard (1-4) for
Milwaukee and Octavio Dotel (1-3) for Houston, will start
Thursday's opener. Jimmy Haynes (5-2) will start the second game
for the Brewers, with Chris Holt (1-6) pitching for the Astros as
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Holt was the last of eight Houston pitchers Tuesday night,
pitching 1 1-3 innings and getting the loss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
