<HEADLINE> Ethiopia-Eritrea Embargo Deal Near  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Security Council members neared a decision
Wednesday night on a proposal for an arms embargo against Ethiopia
and Eritrea following the latest flare-up in their two-year war.
</P>
<P>
   The council met behind closed doors for several hours to try to
resolve differences over the time limit for an embargo, with the
United States and Britain on one side and Russia and France on the
other.
</P>
<P>
   Talks adjourned without an agreement so the 15 council members
could consult with their capitals. Another meeting was scheduled
late Wednesday night, and diplomats were hopeful that it would be
followed by a vote.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain proposed that the council review
compliance with an embargo after 12 months. Other council members
proposed a shorter timetable for a review, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, a major arms supplier to both countries, dropped its
objection to an arms embargo Tuesday and joined France and other
countries in demanding a time limit.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-drafted resolution would ban the sale or supply of
weapons, ammunition, military vehicles and equipment, paramilitary
equipment and spare parts to both countries. It would also ban
military-related training or technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict over the 620-mile border between Ethiopia and
Eritrea -- among the world's poorest countries -- has cost the lives
of thousands of soldiers and civilians on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting forced the World Food Program to temporarily halt
food distribution in Ethiopia's western border area, which could
affect tens of thousands of displaced people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
