<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 49ers GM Reports Progress on Rice  </HEADLINE>
By DENNIS GEORGATOS
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- The chances Jerry Rice will finish
his career in San Francisco appear much better. Steve Young's
future, though, remains foggy.
</P>
<P>
   Both 49ers general manager Bill Walsh and Jim Steiner, the agent
for Rice, said they had made significant progress in working out a
new deal for the NFL's career leading receiver after meeting for 2{
hours Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While the sides were closing in on a more salary-cap friendly
contract for Rice, 37, the future of the 38-year-old Young, who has
combined with Rice to form the league's top touchdown-pass tandem,
is still up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said Young, who missed the final 13 games of last season
after a head blow left him with his fourth concussion in three
years, continues mulling over whether to resume his career and
probably won't make a final decision for at least several more
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, a 12-time Pro Bowl selection and the NFL career leader in
touchdowns, receptions and yards receiving, initially balked at the
cap-strapped 49ers' demands that he take a significant pay cut. San
Francisco said it couldn't afford to keep Rice unless he agreed to
renegotiate his contract, which included a $5.49 million cap figure
for the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   While attending the team's minicamp last month, Rice said he
would be willing to take a cut in pay and expressed hope he could
finish his career in San Francisco. He also made a point of saying
he could serve as a mentor to the younger wideouts on the
rebuilding 49ers, who are coming off a 4-12 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Steiner said he presented the 49ers with a proposal Wednesday
and the 49ers made a counterproposal which included an upgrade to
their original offer. No terms were disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've each made some adjustments on incentives and the gap is
closing,'' Steiner said. ''I was pleasantly surprised. This is the
first meaningful meeting we've had on the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said there's a chance a new deal for Rice could be worked
out within the next few days. Steiner is staying in town for five
days and the sides say they'll stay in touch.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're all optimistic,'' Walsh said. ''We had a friendly open
conversation and we're very hopeful that we can reach agreement
soon but I can't guarantee it because things can crop up at the
last minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Young has met several times with Walsh and coach Steve Mariucci
in recent weeks. Walsh said he plans to meet with Young again soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really don't have any sense of what Steve is thinking,''
Walsh said. ''I don't necessarily think he'll reach a conclusion
very soon on whether to play or retire. I'm not sure he's ready for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said the team is willing to be patient while Young
considers his options though he said the sooner there is a
resolution the better. There has been persistent speculation that
Young may choose to play elsewhere if the 49ers, who picked two
quarterbacks in the draft, decide the two-time league MVP doesn't
fit in their plans. But Young, who was married in the offseason,
also could opt to call it a career.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to have a timetable of our own in all these cases. We
have to move forward,'' Walsh said. ''We have such tremendous
regard for Steve, for both of these men that we'll give them all
the time they'd like to have. But at some point, we have to take
the field and that will be by training camp (July 15).''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
