<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Cash Machines Running Dry  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- More than 60 percent of the cash machines in France
sat empty Wednesday as striking armored truck guards rejected a key
offer on the ninth day of a protest against unsafe working
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In dealing with a nationwide cash shortage, merchants have
lowered the minimum amount required to use credit cards. Other
stores have asked clients to pay in exact change.
</P>
<P>
   The truck guards on Wednesday rejected an offer of a $136
monthly pay increase. The guards are demanding a ''risk bonus'' of
$205 per month after a recent series of brutal beatings by robbers.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, a security guard died of injuries sustained in a
May 5 attack in the Parisian suburb of Nanterre, adding more
tension to the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   By rejecting the ''take it or leave it offer,'' the unionized
guards risked losing all previous offers, including salary
increases and an early retirement offer, negotiators for the
guards' companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement presented a bill to
parliament Wednesday with safety improvements for guards. The bill,
to be fast-tracked, would force banks and businesses to provide a
parking space for guards that would shorten the distance they walk
to refill cash machines, among other measures.
</P>
<P>
   The guards on Wednesday threatened to step up their protest.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just suffered a blow,'' union negotiator Jean-Louis Tayot
told LCI television, referring to the latest death of a security
guard.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not going to just continue to block the banks of France
in such a nice manner,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
