<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-17 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Neighbors of a woman stabbed in Bucks County react with shock, 13-year-old charged as adult </HEADLINE>
By TINA MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORRISVILLE, Pa. (AP) -- A 13-year-old boy accused of stabbing a
33-year-old neighbor and mother of three to death would only have
had to walk about 300 feet from his own apartment, past a
dilapidated playground and a few yards down a tree-lined street to
commit the horrendous crime.
</P>
<P>
   There, he would have turned up a driveway and entered the white,
Cape Cod-style home where Darlyne Jules lived.
</P>
<P>
   Then, according to police, Kareem Watts stabbed Jules several
times in the head, face, neck, chest, torso and arm, spattering
blood on a sofa and other living room furniture and leaving her
body under a pile of clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't even imagine an adult doing what I saw done to that
young woman. She was stabbed so many times that the officers aren't
even sure how many times she was stabbed,'' Bucks County District
Attorney Diane Gibbons said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday, Gibbons said an autopsy revealed the victim was
stabbed more than 60 times. She said she knew of no motive.
</P>
<P>
   Jules's 7-year-old son, Alan Lubin, would later tell police that
Watts entered the home Monday night saying he needed to use the
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   At about 11 p.m. Monday, Alan said, he heard his mother
screaming his name and for someone to call police. He went
downstairs and looked into the living room and saw his mom lying on
the couch with Watts on top of her.
</P>
<P>
   He told police that Watts had a knife in his hand and was
stabbing Jules in the chest. She was moving around and screaming,
he told police.
</P>
<P>
   He ran upstairs, called to his mother, and heard Watts respond
that he was helping her with some clothing, he said. The 7-year-old
said Watts offered to get him some candy.
</P>
<P>
   But Alan knew Kareem was lying, he told police. In the morning,
the 7-year-old went back downstairs and found his mother lying
under a pile of clothes with only one leg visible.
</P>
<P>
   His younger brother and his newborn baby sister were also in the
house all night Monday with their wounded and dying mother. After
shaking their mother and seeing that she wouldn't wake up, the boys
ran next door to their mom's friend's house for help.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's scary, real scary,'' said Koupa Samuels, 25, who lives in
the two-story brick barracks-style apartment house next to the one
in which Watts lived. ''I know I'm going to be looking for
somewhere else soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Other neighbors said they were shocked and surprised by the
killing.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect's mother, Janice Watts, told police that she left
the apartment several times during the night to purchase crack
cocaine and that she had also gone looking for her son, who was
upset.
</P>
<P>
   Court papers showed Watts had pleaded guilty to a charge of
possession of crack cocaine in 1998. In the two years since then,
she had violated her probation at least once by using drugs,
according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors who knew Jules, who was unemployed, said she was a
kind woman who loved her children.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was very nice, friendly, devoted to her kids,'' said Lee
Ann McClease, 26, who was pregnant at the same time as Jules. The
two women talked about having babies; Jules had had her newborn
just over a week before she was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was too trusting and too friendly,'' said neighbor Mary
Singleton, 46. She said she hoped the community would come together
in the wake of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Both woman live around about a block from Jules's home.
</P>
<P>
   Watts had a preliminary hearing at 12:30 a.m. Wednesday before
Judge Joanne V. Kline in Morrisville.
</P>
<P>
   ''I asked him if he understood. He just shook his head,'' Kline
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   She said Watts showed no emotion during the hearing. He is being
held in a juvenile detention center without bail.
</P>
<P>
   ''He didn't do it,'' Janice Watts told WCAU-TV. ''I know he
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The house where Jules lived lies nestled in the back corner of a
neighborhood of Cape Cod-style homes. The home is backed by a
supermarket parking lot, and the small playground, containing a set
of swings and a basketball court without a net.
</P>
<P>
   The Americana Terrace Apartments where Watts lived consists of
several two-story brick bunkers and fronts a stretch of road that
neighbors call ''apartment row.''
</P>
<P>
   Police were looking for the murder weapon on Wednesday. Officer
pulled on plastic gloves before they stepped inside the house,
which was surrounded with yellow crime-scene tape.
</P>
<P>
   Gibbons said all three children were doing fine. The boys were
staying with their father, whom officials identified as John Lubin,
a Willingboro, N.J., truck driver.
</P>
<P>
   Jules, a native of Haiti whose mother lives in Boston, had been
renting the house in the community across the Delaware River from
Trenton, N.J., for about a year and a half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-17-00 2335 </TRAILER>
