<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Actors' Union Criticizes Strike Ad  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN ELBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The fallout from an actors' strike against
commercial producers includes a magazine advertisement that the
Screen Actors Guild says insults women and blacks.
</P>
<P>
   The ad was placed in a trade publication called Shoot by a
commercial production firm headed by top film directors Ridley
Scott (''Gladiator'') and Tony Scott (''Top Gun''). It features a
picture of an older, bare-breasted black woman and the headline,
''In South Africa, this is what SAG means.''
</P>
<P>
   ''To service clients, Marcus Nispel is setting up a temporary
office in South Africa, where production is cost effective and
they've never heard of SAG,'' the ad for the Scotts' RSA USA
company says.
</P>
<P>
   The ad, with a reference to high-profile RSA USA commercial
director Nispel, was intended to provoke a reaction and has drawn a
mostly positive industry response, the firm's managing director,
Linda Ross, told Daily Variety.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have had some negative reaction about the ad being in
questionable taste,'' Ross told the trade paper. ''It's a bit of
shock value for shock value's sake. But there is a lot of business
at stake here.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Ridley Scott, whose ''Gladiator'' is currently the nation's
No. 1 movie, and brother Tony Scott were working out of the office
and unavailable for comment, an employee at RSA USA said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   SAG spokesman Greg Krizman called the ad offensive and said a
protest rally was scheduled for Thursday outside the West Hollywood
offices of RSA USA.
</P>
<P>
   Nispel told Variety the ad was not meant to insult but rather to
draw attention to such issues as runaway production, the term used
to refer to Hollywood production lost to countries in which costs
are lower than in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got loads of messages from people who got a good chuckle
about the ad,'' Nispel said. ''I wanted to make it clear that we
can produce in other countries as well as we can here.''
</P>
<P>
   Actors are striking over the pay structure for commercials. They
get a minimum of about $478 for a day's work and get
''pay-per-play'' residuals of roughly $50 to $120 each time a spot
airs on network television. When it comes to cable TV, they receive
a flat fee of $1,000 or less for each 13-week, unlimited run.
</P>
<P>
   With two-thirds of all TV ads now being made for cable, actors
are demanding that pay-per-play be extended to cable. Advertisers
want to extend the flat fee from cable to the networks.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.sag.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.aftra.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.aaaa.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.ana.net
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-17-00 2352 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000517.0298 </DOCNO>
